WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.600
[Amit Varma]: If a tree falls in a forest and no one is around to hear it, does it make a sound?

00:00:10.600 --> 00:00:15.480
[Amit Varma]: That's an old philosophical thought experiment to which I will add this further question.

00:00:15.480 --> 00:00:21.160
[Amit Varma]: If you feel a desire that you cannot name or understand, does that desire exist?

00:00:21.160 --> 00:00:25.520
[Amit Varma]: This question is a poignant one with social and political implications.

00:00:25.520 --> 00:00:31.200
[Amit Varma]: We instinctively think of some desires as legit and others as desires that we must hide

00:00:31.200 --> 00:00:34.160
[Amit Varma]: away from the world and perhaps even from ourselves.

00:00:34.160 --> 00:00:39.920
[Amit Varma]: We think of some desires as sanskari and others as somehow sinful, even if we don't act upon

00:00:39.920 --> 00:00:40.920
[Amit Varma]: them.

00:00:40.920 --> 00:00:43.080
[Amit Varma]: But what is this sanskar?

00:00:43.080 --> 00:00:48.600
[Amit Varma]: Look a little deeper and you will find that much of what we think of as traditional Indian

00:00:48.600 --> 00:00:55.180
[Amit Varma]: morality is actually a by-product of colonialism, an imposition by the British or Victorian

00:00:55.180 --> 00:01:01.360
[Amit Varma]: prudishness onto a society that has otherwise acknowledged and respected so many different

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:02.360
[Amit Varma]: kinds of desires.

00:01:02.360 --> 00:01:06.680
[Amit Varma]: You might argue that, hey, the Manusmriti is such a repressive document, to which one

00:01:06.680 --> 00:01:11.480
[Amit Varma]: can point out that the Kama Sutra written around the same period is not, and it was

00:01:11.480 --> 00:01:15.920
[Amit Varma]: a British choice, not an Indian one, to privilege one over the other.

00:01:15.920 --> 00:01:21.960
[Amit Varma]: Indeed, the fact that we are today such an incredibly sexually repressed nation speaks

00:01:21.960 --> 00:01:26.080
[Amit Varma]: to the victory of a strain of politics that has led to this.

00:01:26.080 --> 00:01:28.240
[Amit Varma]: India was not always like this.

00:01:28.240 --> 00:01:33.200
[Amit Varma]: India was not even mainly like this, but we suppressed the better angels of our nature

00:01:33.200 --> 00:01:34.700
[Amit Varma]: and here we are.

00:01:34.700 --> 00:01:35.960
[Amit Varma]: But it's not too late.

00:01:35.960 --> 00:01:38.000
[Amit Varma]: We can still reclaim our true selves.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:43.120
[Amit Varma]: And one way of doing this is by acknowledging and understanding the infinite variety of

00:01:43.120 --> 00:01:59.040
[Unknown]: our desires.

00:01:59.040 --> 00:02:00.720
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the Scene and the Unseen.

00:02:00.720 --> 00:02:05.600
[Amit Varma]: Today's episode is about the history of desire and the history of sexuality in India.

00:02:05.600 --> 00:02:10.720
[Amit Varma]: And my guest today is Madhavi Menon, author of the superb book, Infinite Variety, A History

00:02:10.720 --> 00:02:12.240
[Amit Varma]: of Desire in India.

00:02:12.240 --> 00:02:16.640
[Amit Varma]: This was an eye-opening read for me and for those of you who are not interested in sex

00:02:16.640 --> 00:02:21.840
[Amit Varma]: because hey, sex is sinful, worry not, this book is full of stories about gods and you

00:02:21.840 --> 00:02:26.040
[Amit Varma]: will find many moral lessons in their virtuous behavior.

00:02:26.040 --> 00:02:30.640
[Amit Varma]: Before I give in to my desire to begin this conversation, though, I will practice momentary

00:02:30.640 --> 00:02:36.520
[Amit Varma]: renunciation by pausing for a commercial break.

