00:03:48.560 --> 00:03:49.560
[Guest]: Thank you, Amit.

00:03:49.560 --> 00:03:53.360
[Guest]: Thank you for your wonderful introduction, which frankly says everything I want to say

00:03:53.360 --> 00:03:54.920
[Guest]: much better than I could ever say it.

00:03:54.920 --> 00:03:57.600
[Guest]: So I don't know whether to say thank you or we're done.

00:03:57.600 --> 00:03:59.320
[Amit Varma]: We can go have coffee now.

00:03:59.320 --> 00:04:00.320
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

00:04:00.320 --> 00:04:01.320
[Amit Varma]: So before we...

00:04:01.320 --> 00:04:02.800
[Amit Varma]: No, no, there is so much in your great book.

00:04:02.800 --> 00:04:07.520
[Amit Varma]: And if I had a choice, I would keep you in the studio for all day to talk about it.

00:04:07.520 --> 00:04:10.160
[Unknown]: Let's first talk about yourself.

00:04:10.160 --> 00:04:11.620
[Amit Varma]: You know, what did you study?

00:04:11.620 --> 00:04:14.520
[Amit Varma]: What were your sort of formative influences?

00:04:14.520 --> 00:04:19.400
[Amit Varma]: You know, you've specialized in queer theory for a long time before you came to this.

00:04:19.400 --> 00:04:20.920
[Amit Varma]: What's your journey been like?

00:04:20.920 --> 00:04:21.920
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:04:21.920 --> 00:04:28.240
[Guest]: I find those kinds of questions hard to answer because my life seems quite unremarkable actually.

00:04:28.240 --> 00:04:30.120
[Guest]: But maybe that's what makes it fun.

00:04:30.120 --> 00:04:36.560
[Guest]: I've always been interested, I guess, in underdogs.

00:04:36.560 --> 00:04:41.560
[Guest]: I've always been interested in people who are not privileged, who are not in the center,

00:04:41.560 --> 00:04:46.680
[Guest]: people who are marginalized, which at a very young age included women.

00:04:46.680 --> 00:04:52.100
[Guest]: And so from a very young age, I was actually very keen on taking up arms against boys and

00:04:52.100 --> 00:04:53.100
[Guest]: against men.

00:04:53.100 --> 00:04:57.040
[Guest]: And I remember one of my earliest memories is when I was 10 years old, I was the editor

00:04:57.040 --> 00:05:00.280
[Guest]: of my colony newsletter or newspaper.

00:05:00.280 --> 00:05:07.880
[Guest]: And my first editorial had the wonderful title of boys, colon, something needs to be done.

00:05:07.880 --> 00:05:08.880
[Amit Varma]: This would have been 1981.

00:05:08.880 --> 00:05:14.920
[Guest]: I don't want to give your age away, but early 80s, right?

00:05:14.920 --> 00:05:15.920
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:05:15.920 --> 00:05:16.920
[Guest]: Wow.

00:05:16.920 --> 00:05:21.560
[Guest]: So, given that evidence, obviously, from an early age onwards, I was very invested both

00:05:21.560 --> 00:05:25.780
[Guest]: in speaking up for people who I thought did not have a voice and be and actually trying

00:05:25.780 --> 00:05:28.280
[Guest]: to do something about it.

00:05:28.280 --> 00:05:34.860
[Guest]: And so I can't remember when exactly I turned to queer theory or to an interest in sexuality,

00:05:34.860 --> 00:05:40.000
[Guest]: but I've always been interested in thinking about things that we ignore or take for granted

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:45.520
[Guest]: or vilify or actively sort of resist and push into a corner.

00:05:45.520 --> 00:05:48.800
[Guest]: And I've always been free or felt free to do that.

00:05:48.800 --> 00:05:55.140
[Guest]: My parents have always been supportive, maybe a bit puzzled by me at times, but always supportive.

00:05:55.140 --> 00:05:59.940
[Guest]: My mother was a professor of English until she retired, so she was very interested in

00:05:59.940 --> 00:06:03.060
[Guest]: sort of intellectual flights of fancy.

00:06:03.060 --> 00:06:09.320
[Guest]: And my father, from whom I get my politics, was just always very politically active.

00:06:09.320 --> 00:06:13.280
[Guest]: You know, their families come from Kerala, even though they grew up in Madras, and from

00:06:13.280 --> 00:06:20.280
[Guest]: a Kerala in which the Land Distribution Act was happening when they were younger.

00:06:20.280 --> 00:06:25.400
[Guest]: And my father, who comes from a very huge landowning family, a lot of their land got

00:06:25.400 --> 00:06:26.680
[Guest]: taken away.

00:06:26.680 --> 00:06:30.500
[Guest]: And all his life, he said that was absolutely the right thing to do.

00:06:30.500 --> 00:06:34.660
[Guest]: And so I imbibed a lot of my politics from him, a lot of my intellect from my mother.

00:06:34.660 --> 00:06:39.280
[Guest]: And there was never a question of my having to fight against them or fight against my

00:06:39.280 --> 00:06:43.800
[Guest]: family, which I realized is a huge absence of pressure.

00:06:43.800 --> 00:06:48.120
[Guest]: You know, a lot of people have to fight against their families first before they can do anything.

00:06:48.120 --> 00:06:52.360
[Guest]: But for me, it was just always easy for me to focus on what I wanted to, because that

00:06:52.360 --> 00:06:57.840
[Guest]: was never a problem, that I never had to fight at home, the battles that I could fight outside.

00:06:57.840 --> 00:07:00.560
[Guest]: And for that, I think I'm very, very lucky.

00:07:00.560 --> 00:07:02.560
[Amit Varma]: And who was sort of your formative influences?

00:07:02.560 --> 00:07:07.640
[Amit Varma]: Like one question I often ask my guests, and one doesn't always have a pat answer to this

00:07:07.640 --> 00:07:12.640
[Amit Varma]: is, you know, what are the books or what is the book that changed the way you think about

00:07:12.640 --> 00:07:13.640
[Amit Varma]: the world?

00:07:13.640 --> 00:07:18.840
[Amit Varma]: And is this, you know, some thinkers or some books that you can identify as just opening

00:07:18.840 --> 00:07:22.800
[Amit Varma]: your eyes to a new way of looking at the world or clarifying things a little bit more?

00:07:22.800 --> 00:07:28.120
[Guest]: Yeah, I am so bad at answering those kinds of questions, because I just sort of don't

00:07:28.120 --> 00:07:29.360
[Guest]: keep lists.

00:07:29.360 --> 00:07:36.880
[Guest]: But if I look back over my own lived reality, clearly, someone who influenced me a lot,

00:07:36.880 --> 00:07:41.080
[Guest]: so much that I wanted to work on him, ever since I could remember, was Shakespeare.

00:07:41.080 --> 00:07:46.160
[Guest]: I mean, my dissertation work was on Shakespeare, my first three books are on Shakespeare, and

00:07:46.160 --> 00:07:48.740
[Guest]: I'm very deeply invested in him.

00:07:48.740 --> 00:07:53.480
[Guest]: And I hate to admit it, but I'm that kind of nerd that when I'm feeling down, and need

00:07:53.480 --> 00:07:58.840
[Guest]: something to pick me up, I actually turn to Shakespeare to read him, because that immediately

00:07:58.840 --> 00:08:00.540
[Guest]: picks me up.

00:08:00.540 --> 00:08:07.840
[Guest]: And so I've always known from, I'd say my middle teens, that I wanted to work on Shakespeare.

00:08:07.840 --> 00:08:11.560
[Guest]: And when I went to graduate school in the US, I remember having a conversation with

00:08:11.560 --> 00:08:15.160
[Guest]: my advisor, because I thought, you know, I wanted to work on Shakespeare.

00:08:15.160 --> 00:08:18.360
[Guest]: And he said, that's great, do it.

00:08:18.360 --> 00:08:21.480
[Guest]: But people have been writing on him for over 400 years.

00:08:21.480 --> 00:08:25.320
[Guest]: So try and see if there's something different that you can do.

00:08:25.320 --> 00:08:29.000
[Guest]: And that, I would say, is the first time I actually started thinking about what it was

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:34.500
[Guest]: in Shakespeare that uplifted me, that actually drew me to it.

00:08:34.500 --> 00:08:36.640
[Guest]: Because before that, it was just, oh, my God, I love this, right?

00:08:36.640 --> 00:08:39.280
[Guest]: And this is something that we work against with our students.

00:08:39.280 --> 00:08:43.160
[Guest]: It's like, it's great that you love it, and now think about what it is that's inspiring

00:08:43.160 --> 00:08:44.320
[Guest]: that love.

00:08:44.320 --> 00:08:48.080
[Guest]: And so for me, when my advisor said, now think about what it is that you want to do with

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:53.520
[Guest]: Shakespeare, and maybe you want to look at him slightly differently, it became very,

00:08:53.520 --> 00:08:59.280
[Guest]: very clear to me then, and it's something that I'm still sort of amazed by, how you

00:08:59.280 --> 00:09:08.280
[Guest]: can say in wonderful language, in fabulous poetry and prose, things that are really hard

00:09:08.280 --> 00:09:12.200
[Guest]: hitting, things that are really subversive.

00:09:12.200 --> 00:09:18.800
[Guest]: And it's almost like packaging a radical politics in a gorgeous form.

00:09:18.800 --> 00:09:22.800
[Guest]: So whether it's his poetry or his plays, and you know, I'm happy to talk about both, there's

00:09:22.800 --> 00:09:27.620
[Guest]: a way in which Shakespeare is just sort of hits you when you least expect it.

00:09:27.620 --> 00:09:30.400
[Guest]: And that's a skill I don't have, because I'm sort of very blunt edged, and it's like I

00:09:30.400 --> 00:09:32.120
[Guest]: will hit you openly.

00:09:32.120 --> 00:09:34.800
[Guest]: But Shakespeare is a real artist that way.

00:09:34.800 --> 00:09:41.520
[Guest]: And one of the things I love most about his work, it's something like the poet Keats later

00:09:41.520 --> 00:09:46.080
[Guest]: diagnosed about Shakespeare, and he said, Shakespeare has a negative capability, which

00:09:46.080 --> 00:09:54.320
[Guest]: is to say he himself will not be anything, but he'll take on board any persona, any idea,

00:09:54.320 --> 00:09:56.120
[Guest]: and become that.

00:09:56.120 --> 00:10:01.000
[Guest]: And for me, that's always been important, especially in a day and age now where the

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:05.640
[Guest]: idea of the self is so important, it's like this is who I am, or this is what I am.

00:10:05.640 --> 00:10:10.680
[Guest]: And I think we are so obsessed with the self that we forget to take on board otherness.

00:10:10.680 --> 00:10:16.240
[Guest]: And so for me, that taking on board otherness is what Shakespeare exemplifies par excellence,

00:10:16.240 --> 00:10:19.560
[Guest]: he is able to take on board multiplicity.

00:10:19.560 --> 00:10:23.880
[Guest]: And that for me, just comes through in his works in ways that I find absolutely mind

00:10:23.880 --> 00:10:24.880
[Amit Varma]: boggling.

00:10:24.880 --> 00:10:26.560
[Amit Varma]: And that's fundamentally what art does, right?

00:10:26.560 --> 00:10:29.320
[Amit Varma]: It takes on otherness, and it takes on those multiplicities.

00:10:29.320 --> 00:10:35.040
[Amit Varma]: If Shakespeare was alive today, in this age of Instagram and TikTok and YouTube, web series

00:10:35.040 --> 00:10:36.560
[Guest]: and all that, what do you think he'd be doing?

00:10:36.560 --> 00:10:40.640
[Guest]: You know, the thing about Shakespeare that we forget, I mean, maybe you don't forget,

00:10:40.640 --> 00:10:44.440
[Guest]: most of us forget, is that he was a popular writer, right?

00:10:44.440 --> 00:10:49.560
[Guest]: He was writing for entertainment, he was writing to make money, like there is no question about

00:10:49.560 --> 00:10:50.560
[Guest]: that.

00:10:50.560 --> 00:10:53.760
[Guest]: He was very clear that he needed to make money, he was not writing, he didn't think of his

00:10:53.760 --> 00:10:56.160
[Guest]: writing as high art in any sense.

00:10:56.160 --> 00:11:00.280
[Guest]: So whatever is most popular now, and you will know that better than me, that's what he would

00:11:00.280 --> 00:11:02.160
[Guest]: be doing, right?

00:11:02.160 --> 00:11:05.760
[Guest]: And one of my colleagues was, I was telling you about him, who's written this book called

00:11:05.760 --> 00:11:10.960
[Guest]: Masala Shakespeare, his argument is that he would be writing for cinema, and not for Hollywood,

00:11:10.960 --> 00:11:15.480
[Guest]: but for Bollywood, that Shakespeare would be writing popular scripts, with song and

00:11:15.480 --> 00:11:21.320
[Guest]: dance, because his plays also full of that, all kinds of masala elements thrown into it,

00:11:21.320 --> 00:11:22.520
[Amit Varma]: because that's what his plays do.

00:11:22.520 --> 00:11:27.440
[Amit Varma]: He practically invented masala, like so much of Bollywood tropes come from Shakespeare.

00:11:27.440 --> 00:11:28.440
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:11:28.440 --> 00:11:29.440
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:11:29.440 --> 00:11:33.240
[Guest]: And therefore, it's no surprise that Shakespeare provides the script for a lot of Bollywood

00:11:33.240 --> 00:11:36.480
[Guest]: films as well, you know, various kinds of adaptations.

00:11:36.480 --> 00:11:41.320
[Guest]: My favorite being, of course, Bhansali's Goliyon ki Raas Leela, Ram Leela, which I think is

00:11:41.320 --> 00:11:42.320
[Guest]: just magnificent.

00:11:42.320 --> 00:11:44.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, which I haven't seen.

00:11:44.600 --> 00:11:48.960
[Amit Varma]: So how did you, and in fact, you know, you're talking about Shakespeare's popularity, I

00:11:48.960 --> 00:11:52.240
[Amit Varma]: was telling you before this recording that I teach this course for Takshashila on how

00:11:52.240 --> 00:11:57.800
[Amit Varma]: to write an op-ed in like, four webinars, and the second one of them is called the music

00:11:57.800 --> 00:11:58.800
[Amit Varma]: of language.

00:11:58.800 --> 00:12:00.320
[Amit Varma]: And it talks about Shakespeare a lot.

00:12:00.320 --> 00:12:04.680
[Amit Varma]: It talks about why Shakespeare would have been a great op-ed writer, because part of

00:12:04.680 --> 00:12:08.800
[Amit Varma]: the art of writing an op-ed always has to be to write accessibly.

00:12:08.800 --> 00:12:13.320
[Amit Varma]: And for me, iambic pentameter is just the optimal accessible form.

00:12:13.320 --> 00:12:16.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, because it's rhythmic and easy to say, right.

00:12:16.120 --> 00:12:19.920
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time, that's the optimal length of a sentence, you know, which you can sort

00:12:19.920 --> 00:12:22.440
[Guest]: of read comfortably or say comfortably.

00:12:22.440 --> 00:12:28.560
[Guest]: And the meter, the iambic pentameter, of course, is, as people say, often like the heartbeat.

00:12:28.560 --> 00:12:33.640
[Guest]: So it's just, it comes naturally to the body and viscerally to the body, which is great.

00:12:33.640 --> 00:12:37.440
[Guest]: I'm glad your students get some Shakespeare in how to write an op-ed.

00:12:37.440 --> 00:12:41.880
[Guest]: I mean, this is something we always forget, not always, often forget about Shakespeare,

00:12:41.880 --> 00:12:45.520
[Guest]: because we're so obsessed with the plot of his plays, is that it's his language that's

00:12:45.520 --> 00:12:46.520
[Guest]: doing all the work.

00:12:46.520 --> 00:12:50.320
[Guest]: I mean, my favorite example is, say, Romeo and Juliet, in the first 14 lines of that

00:12:50.320 --> 00:12:53.040
[Guest]: play, he tells you the plot.

00:12:53.040 --> 00:12:56.080
[Guest]: These two people are going to fall in love and they're going to die.

00:12:56.080 --> 00:12:59.800
[Guest]: Then we still have five acts after that, you know.

00:12:59.800 --> 00:13:03.200
[Guest]: So the only reason to read that is not to find out, okay, kya hua?

00:13:03.200 --> 00:13:04.200
[Guest]: What happened?

00:13:04.200 --> 00:13:05.200
[Guest]: There's no suspense.

00:13:05.200 --> 00:13:07.800
[Guest]: It's to find out how does this work out?

00:13:07.800 --> 00:13:08.800
[Guest]: In what language?

00:13:08.800 --> 00:13:09.800
[Guest]: In what form?

00:13:09.800 --> 00:13:10.800
[Guest]: In what way?

00:13:10.800 --> 00:13:15.760
[Guest]: So he's very clear, and none of his plots, with perhaps the exception of The Tempest or

00:13:15.760 --> 00:13:20.720
[Guest]: a play like Pericles, actually not even Pericles, none of his plots is original.

00:13:20.720 --> 00:13:24.840
[Guest]: So our obsession right now, for instance, with the idea of originality, Shakespeare

00:13:24.840 --> 00:13:26.360
[Guest]: would not have understood what that meant.

00:13:26.360 --> 00:13:29.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, there's a very cool book called The Seven Basic Plots by Christopher Booker, I

00:13:29.920 --> 00:13:30.920
[Amit Varma]: think.

00:13:30.920 --> 00:13:34.120
[Amit Varma]: And as a teacher of English, you must have access to so many such books.

00:13:34.120 --> 00:13:37.960
[Amit Varma]: But essentially, there are just a handful of plots which are recycled over and over

00:13:37.960 --> 00:13:38.960
[Unknown]: again.

00:13:38.960 --> 00:13:39.960
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

00:13:39.960 --> 00:13:43.840
[Amit Varma]: And what is important is perhaps a journey and not so much the destination.

00:13:43.840 --> 00:13:48.520
[Amit Varma]: And your destination through all of this was this book, which we are talking about today.

00:13:48.520 --> 00:13:49.760
[Amit Varma]: But what was your journey to it?

00:13:49.760 --> 00:13:55.160
[Amit Varma]: Like, how did you arrive at this subject of writing about the history of desire?

00:13:55.160 --> 00:14:00.000
[Guest]: Yeah, you know, I'm struck by what you said about when you teach your students about how

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:04.680
[Guest]: to write an op-ed, you sort of insist to them on accessibility.

00:14:04.680 --> 00:14:07.240
[Guest]: And that's something I pride myself on as well.

00:14:07.240 --> 00:14:10.640
[Guest]: And it's something that comes quite naturally to me.

00:14:10.640 --> 00:14:15.840
[Guest]: Because I think writing should be accessible, not in the sense of dumbed down, because I

00:14:15.840 --> 00:14:18.520
[Guest]: think writing needs to deal with extremely rigorous ideas.

00:14:18.520 --> 00:14:20.720
[Guest]: And I'm a great believer in rigor.

00:14:20.720 --> 00:14:26.520
[Guest]: But that it needs to draw people in, insufficiently so that they want to deal with that difficulty,

00:14:26.520 --> 00:14:27.520
[Guest]: right?

00:14:27.520 --> 00:14:30.440
[Guest]: If you put them off at the very outset, then they're not going to come in to deal with

00:14:30.440 --> 00:14:32.120
[Guest]: that difficulty.

00:14:32.120 --> 00:14:37.840
[Guest]: So for me, I've always, even when I was writing my academic books, very invested in writing

00:14:37.840 --> 00:14:41.200
[Guest]: accessibly.

00:14:41.200 --> 00:14:47.920
[Guest]: And but as you know, when you're writing academic books, there is a certain degree of formal

00:14:47.920 --> 00:14:48.920
[Guest]: constraint, right?

00:14:48.920 --> 00:14:53.600
[Guest]: So you have to cite various texts, you have to have a bibliography that's very long.

00:14:53.600 --> 00:14:58.640
[Guest]: And I was never fond of that, because I always thought that interrupted the flow of the writing.

00:14:58.640 --> 00:15:05.280
[Guest]: And so I guess over the last 20 years, as I've been writing my books, I've been sort

00:15:05.280 --> 00:15:11.840
[Guest]: of filing away certain lessons about how I would ideally like a popular book to be.

00:15:11.840 --> 00:15:16.800
[Guest]: And all this was while I was still in the US, I was studying there, working there.

00:15:16.800 --> 00:15:21.400
[Guest]: And then after I came back, one of the things I loved about being back, and one of the reasons

00:15:21.400 --> 00:15:27.560
[Guest]: I wanted to move back, is that the intellectual culture in India is just much more broad based

00:15:27.560 --> 00:15:29.260
[Guest]: than it is in the US.

00:15:29.260 --> 00:15:34.720
[Guest]: As with so many things in the US, if you are an academic, you're an academic, you don't

00:15:34.720 --> 00:15:39.440
[Guest]: really interact with anybody else, you're speaking to one another, five people will

00:15:39.440 --> 00:15:43.320
[Guest]: read your book, and your book will come out two years after you've actually written it

00:15:43.320 --> 00:15:45.280
[Guest]: when you've even forgotten what it is.

00:15:45.280 --> 00:15:51.880
[Guest]: And so that kind of lag, time lag in terms of publication, social lag in terms of interaction,

00:15:51.880 --> 00:15:54.840
[Guest]: is deeply ingrained in the US.

00:15:54.840 --> 00:15:59.160
[Guest]: One of the many things I love about being here is that academics are reading the same

00:15:59.160 --> 00:16:04.180
[Guest]: thing that lawyers are reading, that podcasters are reading, that activists are reading.

00:16:04.180 --> 00:16:09.960
[Guest]: And so the conversation is much more multiform, right, that you can speak to many more demographics,

00:16:09.960 --> 00:16:14.400
[Guest]: which I find enriching and enlivening, I really find it exciting.

00:16:14.400 --> 00:16:15.600
[Guest]: So that was one thing.

00:16:15.600 --> 00:16:24.040
[Guest]: And the second thing was that the conversations that people have can actually be about really

00:16:24.040 --> 00:16:28.640
[Guest]: difficult subjects, but they can be had conversationally.

00:16:28.640 --> 00:16:30.520
[Guest]: And so I was very invested in that as well.

00:16:30.520 --> 00:16:35.440
[Guest]: And so I came back, I started writing a lot of op-eds, a lot of articles, which I loved

00:16:35.440 --> 00:16:37.760
[Guest]: doing, because I was reaching a huge audience right away.

00:16:37.760 --> 00:16:41.160
[Guest]: I was writing it the previous day, next day, it would emerge, right, which was unheard

00:16:41.160 --> 00:16:42.160
[Amit Varma]: of with academics.

00:16:42.160 --> 00:16:46.240
[Amit Varma]: How does an academy cope with the shock of reading a book?

00:16:46.240 --> 00:16:48.440
[Guest]: That was really shocking.

00:16:48.440 --> 00:16:52.240
[Guest]: But more important than that, I was been doing this for a year or two.

00:16:52.240 --> 00:16:59.480
[Guest]: And then I met Ravi Singh, who was my editor, who was then with Aleph Books.

00:16:59.480 --> 00:17:05.200
[Guest]: And Ravi had read one of my articles, I don't remember which one, I think it was something

00:17:05.200 --> 00:17:12.240
[Guest]: about 377 or something about the national flag or one of those uncontroversial topics

00:17:12.240 --> 00:17:15.120
[Guest]: about which I write.

00:17:15.120 --> 00:17:19.400
[Guest]: And he approached me and he said, I want you to write something about desire in India.

00:17:19.400 --> 00:17:23.400
[Guest]: And I said to Ravi, I have no training in India.

00:17:23.400 --> 00:17:28.520
[Guest]: I am not a scholar of Indian literature, philosophy, history, religion, nothing.

00:17:28.520 --> 00:17:30.840
[Guest]: I can't write about India.

00:17:30.840 --> 00:17:36.240
[Guest]: And when you meet Ravi, which I hope you will at some point, you will realize he's an extremely

00:17:36.240 --> 00:17:38.320
[Guest]: persistent man.

00:17:38.320 --> 00:17:43.520
[Guest]: So he said, actually not dissimilar to what my advisor said to me, he said, you just need

00:17:43.520 --> 00:17:46.040
[Guest]: to think about it differently.

00:17:46.040 --> 00:17:50.920
[Guest]: Because I'm not asking you to write the definitive history of India.

00:17:50.920 --> 00:17:55.360
[Guest]: I'm asking you to think about how these questions of desire that are affecting the way in which

00:17:55.360 --> 00:18:00.480
[Guest]: you're thinking about life around you can actually be written in book form.

00:18:00.480 --> 00:18:02.560
[Guest]: So I promised him I'd think about it at least.

00:18:02.560 --> 00:18:04.740
[Guest]: And then I thought about it for a while.

00:18:04.740 --> 00:18:10.440
[Guest]: And what became clear to me is that I could never write the book on desire in India.

00:18:10.440 --> 00:18:14.880
[Guest]: But what I could do, and this is what I tried to do, is that I tried to think about the

00:18:14.880 --> 00:18:17.480
[Guest]: important questions that animate queer theory.

00:18:17.480 --> 00:18:21.840
[Guest]: Now, queer theory as a field barely even exists here, right?

00:18:21.840 --> 00:18:26.000
[Guest]: But the important questions that animate queer theory, which, you know, broadly are questions

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:33.760
[Guest]: of identity, desire, sort of clothing, behavior, biology, I mean, all that stuff.

00:18:33.760 --> 00:18:44.380
[Guest]: And think about what Indian writings, thoughts, beliefs have said about these questions.

00:18:44.380 --> 00:18:49.360
[Guest]: So my framing narratives were very much derived from my training as a queer theorist.

00:18:49.360 --> 00:18:51.880
[Guest]: Those are the questions I was going in with.

00:18:51.880 --> 00:18:56.200
[Guest]: But the material I was looking at from the vantage point of these questions were Indian

00:18:56.200 --> 00:18:59.740
[Guest]: materials, which I had never really looked at before.

00:18:59.740 --> 00:19:04.000
[Guest]: And I remember starting out by saying, I am not going to touch the Kama Sutra because

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:05.480
[Guest]: it's been done to death, right?

00:19:05.480 --> 00:19:07.640
[Guest]: Anyone who thinks about Indian sexuality does that.

00:19:07.640 --> 00:19:09.440
[Guest]: But I said, I have to read it at least.

00:19:09.440 --> 00:19:11.960
[Guest]: And when I read it, I was blown away.

00:19:11.960 --> 00:19:16.360
[Guest]: And so, as you know, I refer to the Kama Sutra a lot in my book.

00:19:16.360 --> 00:19:23.440
[Guest]: But my goal in the book was to be accessible, to be focused on specific questions and arguments

00:19:23.440 --> 00:19:29.280
[Guest]: and ideas so people can actually engage, not be esoteric at all, which is what people think

00:19:29.280 --> 00:19:32.680
[Guest]: when it's, oh, my God, this is Indian philosophy or Indian religion.

00:19:32.680 --> 00:19:35.400
[Guest]: People get completely turned off by that.

00:19:35.400 --> 00:19:38.040
[Guest]: But I'm used to that because that's what people do with Shakespeare as well, right?

00:19:38.040 --> 00:19:40.960
[Guest]: It's like, oh, my God, Shakespeare is so esoteric, I can't deal with it.

00:19:40.960 --> 00:19:44.940
[Guest]: So I'm actually very used to dealing with subjects that people think of as difficult,

00:19:44.940 --> 00:19:48.240
[Guest]: but that I know actually affects our everyday life.

00:19:48.240 --> 00:19:52.580
[Guest]: And so I guess I've had a lot of training thinking about these subjects and insisting

00:19:52.580 --> 00:19:59.520
[Guest]: to people that, in fact, you're not, you don't have to be brilliant or have a PhD in order

00:19:59.520 --> 00:20:00.520
[Guest]: to address these subjects.

00:20:00.520 --> 00:20:02.560
[Guest]: These are subjects you're addressing already.

00:20:02.560 --> 00:20:04.740
[Guest]: So let's just pause and think about them.

00:20:04.740 --> 00:20:09.200
[Guest]: And so that was the way in which I arrived at this book, with a lot of encouragement

00:20:09.200 --> 00:20:15.600
[Guest]: from Ravi and a lot of encouragement to sort of change the way I was thinking about India.

00:20:15.600 --> 00:20:20.600
[Guest]: And so for me, as soon as I was able to get my questions right, I was able to delve into

00:20:20.600 --> 00:20:21.600
[Guest]: the material.

00:20:21.600 --> 00:20:25.520
[Guest]: Because otherwise, I think, if I had just jumped into the material without any clue,

00:20:25.520 --> 00:20:28.920
[Guest]: I wouldn't have been able to anchor myself in any way.

00:20:28.920 --> 00:20:33.820
[Guest]: So I had to anchor myself as a queer theorist, and then approach this material that was new.

00:20:33.820 --> 00:20:34.820
[Guest]: And it was just exhilarating.

00:20:34.820 --> 00:20:38.520
[Amit Varma]: No, and it was exhilarating as a reader for me to read it.

00:20:38.520 --> 00:20:40.000
[Amit Varma]: I had a lot of fun reading it.

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:42.920
[Amit Varma]: So I could make out that you had a lot of fun writing it.

00:20:42.920 --> 00:20:47.920
[Amit Varma]: And it sort of strikes me that there is the role of happenstance, that you weren't thinking

00:20:47.920 --> 00:20:48.920
[Amit Varma]: of doing this.

00:20:48.920 --> 00:20:49.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:20:49.920 --> 00:20:52.000
[Amit Varma]: And then Ravi happened to ask you, and then you looked at it.

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:55.400
[Amit Varma]: And you went along a different path than you otherwise would have.

00:20:55.400 --> 00:20:59.240
[Guest]: And who knows, maybe there's some other book at the end of the path not taken.

00:20:59.240 --> 00:21:02.020
[Amit Varma]: And that's kind of fascinating.

00:21:02.020 --> 00:21:06.800
[Amit Varma]: So you know, one of the things that you say in your book, and you've said in your talks,

00:21:06.800 --> 00:21:11.440
[Amit Varma]: and that you're very adamant about is that you will not define desire, right?

00:21:11.440 --> 00:21:15.960
[Amit Varma]: So I won't ask you to define it, obviously, that would be mildly silly.

00:21:15.960 --> 00:21:21.760
[Amit Varma]: But I'm just curious as to whether, you know, for example, it strikes me that, you know,

00:21:21.760 --> 00:21:23.680
[Amit Varma]: yesterday, I was craving a biryani.

00:21:23.680 --> 00:21:25.960
[Amit Varma]: Now my desire for biryani is not desire.

00:21:25.960 --> 00:21:29.360
[Amit Varma]: That's not what you mean in the book.

00:21:29.360 --> 00:21:35.920
[Amit Varma]: From what I could make out your book includes your book accommodates carnal desire, romantic

00:21:35.920 --> 00:21:41.680
[Amit Varma]: desire, which some would say is a rationalization, but at some biological level of carnal desire,

00:21:41.680 --> 00:21:47.200
[Amit Varma]: perhaps even a little bit of spiritual desire thrown in, I don't know, I mean, so how does

00:21:47.200 --> 00:21:51.280
[Amit Varma]: one then think about desire in this sense, without necessarily trying to nail it down,

00:21:51.280 --> 00:21:54.720
[Guest]: which is a mistake all these patriarchs have made through history?

00:21:54.720 --> 00:21:55.720
[Guest]: Right.

00:21:55.720 --> 00:21:57.720
[Guest]: And that's a great question.

00:21:57.720 --> 00:22:04.600
[Guest]: I think after the victory in Delhi, we should all be eating biryani to celebrate.

00:22:04.600 --> 00:22:07.480
[Amit Varma]: We are recording this on February 13.

00:22:07.480 --> 00:22:08.480
[Amit Varma]: That's right.

00:22:08.480 --> 00:22:12.000
[Amit Varma]: I would say it was a victory for us, but not necessarily a defeat for the BJP.

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:16.200
[Guest]: And therefore, we should eat biryani just to make sure that we continue fighting.

00:22:16.200 --> 00:22:17.200
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:22:17.200 --> 00:22:18.800
[Guest]: Well said.

00:22:18.800 --> 00:22:25.520
[Guest]: I would disagree that your desire for biryani is not the kind of desire I'm talking about.

00:22:25.520 --> 00:22:31.440
[Guest]: Because I think one of the things I have done that we find convenient to do is precisely

00:22:31.440 --> 00:22:39.320
[Guest]: to sort of separate desires from one another, devaluing some and overvaluing, I would say,

00:22:39.320 --> 00:22:40.320
[Guest]: others.

00:22:40.320 --> 00:22:45.680
[Guest]: And so your desire for biryani seems to fall into the lower class of desire, because it's

00:22:45.680 --> 00:22:50.280
[Guest]: merely appetite, it's merely bodily, it has nothing to do with intellect, this, that and

00:22:50.280 --> 00:22:51.280
[Guest]: the other.

00:22:51.280 --> 00:22:55.600
[Guest]: I'm sort of paraphrasing what I think you might have felt when you said that.

00:22:55.600 --> 00:23:01.960
[Guest]: And I would disagree with that because I really think one doesn't know the seat of desire.

00:23:01.960 --> 00:23:07.960
[Guest]: One doesn't know what the confluences are that create certain desires.

00:23:07.960 --> 00:23:12.680
[Guest]: And so I would say your mind was very much active in your bodily desire for biryani.

00:23:12.680 --> 00:23:17.940
[Guest]: And so one of the things, of course, that I am interested in is not making that distinction

00:23:17.940 --> 00:23:22.640
[Guest]: between mind and body, that there is something about the body that is very much controlled

00:23:22.640 --> 00:23:27.120
[Guest]: by the mind, equally something about the mind that is very much controlled by the body.

00:23:27.120 --> 00:23:32.320
[Guest]: And these things come together in all these desires that you mentioned.

00:23:32.320 --> 00:23:36.640
[Guest]: And so for me, that desire for biryani, and as you know, I have a chapter on paan in the

00:23:36.640 --> 00:23:41.960
[Guest]: book, and I could easily have had a chapter on food in general.

00:23:41.960 --> 00:23:51.360
[Guest]: Because our desire for X is always a desire that comes from not necessarily a known source.

00:23:51.360 --> 00:23:55.580
[Guest]: So we don't know necessarily, oh, why do I want biryani now?

00:23:55.580 --> 00:24:00.840
[Guest]: And I think that absence of an origin or the complicated nature of an origin is always

00:24:00.840 --> 00:24:02.880
[Guest]: what is interesting for me.

00:24:02.880 --> 00:24:04.120
[Guest]: That's number one.

00:24:04.120 --> 00:24:11.000
[Guest]: Number two becomes, we rank desires because we sort of feel some can be satisfied, which

00:24:11.000 --> 00:24:14.760
[Guest]: are the lesser desires, and some can't be satisfied, which are the higher desires.

00:24:14.760 --> 00:24:18.800
[Guest]: But of course, as you yourself already know, you'd be quite happy to eat biryani again

00:24:18.800 --> 00:24:19.800
[Guest]: today.

00:24:19.800 --> 00:24:23.120
[Guest]: But just because you ate it yesterday doesn't mean your desire is satisfied.

00:24:23.120 --> 00:24:28.800
[Guest]: And this is precisely how we actually live sexuality.

00:24:28.800 --> 00:24:32.480
[Guest]: And someone like Freud was one of the early people to theorize this, although, as I say

00:24:32.480 --> 00:24:36.600
[Guest]: in my book, we've had these ideas around in India for centuries.

00:24:36.600 --> 00:24:45.480
[Guest]: The idea that an act or a deed can exhaust your desire of any kind is completely fallacious.

00:24:45.480 --> 00:24:50.120
[Guest]: So whether it is the act of genital sex, whether it is the act of eating biryani, whether it

00:24:50.120 --> 00:24:56.040
[Guest]: is the act of writing a letter or an op-ed, that desire, as long as it's desire, always

00:24:56.040 --> 00:24:58.160
[Guest]: needs to be refueled.

00:24:58.160 --> 00:25:02.800
[Guest]: And that is precisely why desire is both so scary and necessary.

00:25:02.800 --> 00:25:06.240
[Guest]: It's what keeps us going from day to day.

00:25:06.240 --> 00:25:10.560
[Guest]: It's also what gets us charged up because it's the thing that can never be satisfied

00:25:10.560 --> 00:25:13.480
[Guest]: in any lasting manner.

00:25:13.480 --> 00:25:18.520
[Guest]: And so that's why desire, which is why there's so much legislation against it, desire can

00:25:18.520 --> 00:25:25.640
[Guest]: be extremely threatening, both to the self and to the status quo at large, because it's

00:25:25.640 --> 00:25:30.480
[Guest]: the thing that erupts without necessarily having an origin.

00:25:30.480 --> 00:25:34.920
[Guest]: It's the thing that erupts, and even when it seems to subside, can erupt at some other

00:25:34.920 --> 00:25:37.120
[Guest]: point in some other day.

00:25:37.120 --> 00:25:42.360
[Guest]: So it's the thing over which we don't necessarily have control, which is why it's fascinating

00:25:42.360 --> 00:25:47.080
[Guest]: to me to think about, for instance, traditions of celibacy.

00:25:47.080 --> 00:25:51.880
[Guest]: And if I had written a chapter on food, you know, all this sort of fasting, all these

00:25:51.880 --> 00:25:58.040
[Guest]: are ways of trying to establish control over something that actually we fear controls us.

00:25:58.040 --> 00:26:00.320
[Guest]: And that's why desire can be so frightening.

00:26:00.320 --> 00:26:04.520
[Guest]: That's why we want to actually compartmentalize it and say, these desires are okay, but these

00:26:04.520 --> 00:26:05.720
[Guest]: are bad.

00:26:05.720 --> 00:26:11.000
[Guest]: And my argument is that all desire is potentially threatening, no matter what kind.

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:17.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and it's sort of, you know, you quote from the Kama Sutra Vatsyayana saying, passion

00:26:17.120 --> 00:26:22.240
[Unknown]: knows no order, right, where even where he's outlying, you know, the different kinds of

00:26:22.240 --> 00:26:26.440
[Amit Varma]: desires, he also says, look, there are exceptions, I can't contain them.

00:26:26.440 --> 00:26:31.680
[Amit Varma]: And what seems to me, as you outlined so beautifully in your book, that one of the tragedies of

00:26:31.680 --> 00:26:37.240
[Amit Varma]: human society, in a sense, is that we have forced these categories and taxonomies onto

00:26:37.240 --> 00:26:43.640
[Amit Varma]: our desires, which then also have this overlay of normative thinking around them, that you

00:26:43.640 --> 00:26:48.440
[Amit Varma]: know, heterosexuality is good, man and woman having children is good, but something else

00:26:48.440 --> 00:26:49.440
[Amit Varma]: is not good.

00:26:49.440 --> 00:26:54.800
[Amit Varma]: Three lovers together is not good, for example, which you have a chapter on called fractions.

00:26:54.800 --> 00:27:03.560
[Amit Varma]: And so, tell me a little bit about this normative urge, like, is it an inevitable urge, or is

00:27:03.560 --> 00:27:08.920
[Amit Varma]: it just happenstance that that urge run out where at one time in our culture, we had this

00:27:08.920 --> 00:27:15.120
[Amit Varma]: multiplicity of desires that did not need to be given a name and about which value judgments

00:27:15.120 --> 00:27:17.120
[Amit Varma]: were not necessarily made.

00:27:17.120 --> 00:27:23.920
[Amit Varma]: And then we move to this very puritanical sort of setup where, you know, it's all different.

00:27:23.920 --> 00:27:30.240
[Guest]: Yeah, you know, Sudhir Kakkar has a biography of Vatsyayana, which is titled the ascetic

00:27:30.240 --> 00:27:31.240
[Guest]: of desire.

00:27:31.240 --> 00:27:33.800
[Guest]: It's a fictional biography.

00:27:33.800 --> 00:27:38.880
[Guest]: And he's getting that phrase, which seems to be completely sort of contradictory.

00:27:38.880 --> 00:27:43.600
[Guest]: He's getting that phrase from Vatsyayana himself, because Vatsyayana writes at the end of the

00:27:43.600 --> 00:27:49.200
[Guest]: Kama Sutra, in which he sort of outlined all these sexual positions, among other things,

00:27:49.200 --> 00:27:51.520
[Guest]: but all these ways of having sex.

00:27:51.520 --> 00:27:56.320
[Guest]: He says at the end, Vatsyayana was completely celibate for the duration of writing this

00:27:56.320 --> 00:28:02.800
[Guest]: text, that I wrote it not for my pleasure, but for disseminating knowledge.

00:28:02.800 --> 00:28:08.880
[Guest]: And that is a very, that is a sort of nod to a very clear prescription that students

00:28:08.880 --> 00:28:14.120
[Guest]: should not have sex, right, so that that stage of one's life, when one is a student, one

00:28:14.120 --> 00:28:15.120
[Guest]: should not have sex.

00:28:15.120 --> 00:28:19.240
[Guest]: I keep joking about this with my students saying, look how how fallen you are compared

00:28:19.240 --> 00:28:20.800
[Guest]: to that.

00:28:20.800 --> 00:28:24.480
[Guest]: Because the idea was that you need to and it's a complicated idea, because it's an idea

00:28:24.480 --> 00:28:31.600
[Guest]: that is completely opposite, say Greek ideas about education in the in the same time.

00:28:31.600 --> 00:28:37.520
[Guest]: So Vatsyayana says, I was celibate, but my celibacy, and this goes back to what I was

00:28:37.520 --> 00:28:43.080
[Guest]: talking about Shakespeare's negative capability, my celibacy should not take away from the

00:28:43.080 --> 00:28:52.000
[Guest]: fact that I can know and enjoy sexual positions, right, and that kind of ability to speak from

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:57.280
[Guest]: more than one position is what I fear we are losing now.

00:28:57.280 --> 00:29:02.840
[Guest]: And so it's not necessarily that we were more plural and are not now, I think we are every

00:29:02.840 --> 00:29:05.440
[Guest]: bit as plural now as we were then.

00:29:05.440 --> 00:29:11.720
[Guest]: But we are certainly trying to cage that plurality, because it seems to be dangerous.

00:29:11.720 --> 00:29:13.880
[Guest]: It seems to be scary to people.

00:29:13.880 --> 00:29:19.320
[Guest]: And so Vatsyayana can say, I am writing of things that I am not practicing right now.

00:29:19.320 --> 00:29:26.720
[Guest]: Whereas nowadays, the most sort of popular, say tag of a movie is based on a true story,

00:29:26.720 --> 00:29:28.600
[Guest]: or based on real life.

00:29:28.600 --> 00:29:33.600
[Guest]: And we are so invested in people speaking their truth, that we refuse to allow for the

00:29:33.600 --> 00:29:36.480
[Guest]: fact that people have multiple truths.

00:29:36.480 --> 00:29:38.600
[Guest]: And people have multiple falsities as well.

00:29:38.600 --> 00:29:42.840
[Guest]: And no truth is completely the truth in the sense that we understand exactly.

00:29:42.840 --> 00:29:45.080
[Guest]: And so that I feel is what we're losing.

00:29:45.080 --> 00:29:49.520
[Guest]: And that's what say someone like Vatsyayana is able to model for us, that you don't have

00:29:49.520 --> 00:29:53.880
[Guest]: to actually have one truth alone that defines you for the rest of your life, which I fear

00:29:53.880 --> 00:29:58.280
[Guest]: is the problem with sexual identities.

00:29:58.280 --> 00:30:01.560
[Guest]: And now this is a very, and I'm well aware that this is a sort of controversial thing

00:30:01.560 --> 00:30:09.640
[Guest]: I'm saying, but I've said it many times before, that I understand the desire to be able to

00:30:09.640 --> 00:30:19.120
[Guest]: say I am X, but that the people most fully served by my assertion that I am X, are people

00:30:19.120 --> 00:30:22.600
[Guest]: in power over me, not me myself.

00:30:22.600 --> 00:30:28.240
[Guest]: So in this sense, I think identity is a bit of a trap, because it's only people who want

00:30:28.240 --> 00:30:34.160
[Guest]: to curtail my identity and shape it themselves, who want to know who I am.

00:30:34.160 --> 00:30:41.480
[Guest]: So this question of I am X seems to me a wasted statement because I am X, Y, Z and A, B, C

00:30:41.480 --> 00:30:42.840
[Guest]: as well.

00:30:42.840 --> 00:30:46.760
[Guest]: But being forced to say I am X doesn't serve me.

00:30:46.760 --> 00:30:52.240
[Guest]: It only serves those forms with those multiple boxes of which I can take only one.

00:30:52.240 --> 00:30:59.540
[Guest]: And so what is sad for me about identity politics is to see people embracing it as their truth,

00:30:59.540 --> 00:31:04.920
[Guest]: when it's nothing but the idea of truth as singularity being imposed on them.

00:31:04.920 --> 00:31:11.960
[Guest]: And so my quarrel with identity politics is that people like us, and I mean every single

00:31:11.960 --> 00:31:17.440
[Guest]: one of us because every single one of us is on the margins at various points in our lives.

00:31:17.440 --> 00:31:23.640
[Guest]: People like us ought to know better, rather than try and scramble to join the center.

00:31:23.640 --> 00:31:28.560
[Guest]: We need to be able to embrace marginality much more fully, and not necessarily speak

00:31:28.560 --> 00:31:33.560
[Guest]: the language of the oppressor, which in this case, I think is the language of truth with

00:31:33.560 --> 00:31:34.560
[Amit Varma]: a capital T.

00:31:34.560 --> 00:31:40.000
[Amit Varma]: Now, what you just said, and also, you know, a lot of what is in your book, reminded me

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:46.080
[Amit Varma]: of this great insight that I got from Tony Joseph's book last year, Early Indians and

00:31:46.080 --> 00:31:48.960
[Amit Varma]: Tony Joseph was also on the scene in The Unseen.

00:31:48.960 --> 00:31:53.180
[Amit Varma]: And one of the interesting things he pointed out was, of course, all those different migrations

00:31:53.180 --> 00:31:57.360
[Amit Varma]: took place from out of Africa, West Asia, then the Aryan migration.

00:31:57.360 --> 00:32:01.920
[Amit Varma]: And then after the Aryans came and the Aryans were here and the remnants of the Harappans

00:32:01.920 --> 00:32:08.280
[Amit Varma]: were here and the earlier and what happened was that for about 2000 years, it was a party.

00:32:08.280 --> 00:32:10.400
[Amit Varma]: Everybody mingled with everybody else.

00:32:10.400 --> 00:32:13.400
[Amit Varma]: It was full Saturday night, every day, right.

00:32:13.400 --> 00:32:21.200
[Amit Varma]: And then what happened is, around a couple of 1000 years ago, endogamy sets in a particular

00:32:21.200 --> 00:32:27.720
[Amit Varma]: and this is really the victory of a particular political strand, which is that Brahminical

00:32:27.720 --> 00:32:31.680
[Amit Varma]: strand which, you know, sets up the caste system and so on and so forth.

00:32:31.680 --> 00:32:36.480
[Amit Varma]: And there's endogamy and you're not allowed to sort of mingle with others.

00:32:36.480 --> 00:32:41.480
[Amit Varma]: You know, Robert Reich expressed the consequences of this quite brilliantly, the geneticist,

00:32:41.480 --> 00:32:44.800
[Amit Varma]: when he said that, you know, people think of India as a large population.

00:32:44.800 --> 00:32:45.800
[Amit Varma]: It's not.

00:32:45.800 --> 00:32:47.760
[Amit Varma]: The Han Chinese are a large population.

00:32:47.760 --> 00:32:52.480
[Amit Varma]: India is a collection of many, many small populations, which is what endogamy has done

00:32:52.480 --> 00:32:53.480
[Amit Varma]: to us.

00:32:53.480 --> 00:33:00.160
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me from this, that one of the driving forces behind maintaining this sort

00:33:00.160 --> 00:33:06.320
[Amit Varma]: of power structure would be controlling the sexual and reproductive choices of women,

00:33:06.320 --> 00:33:11.800
[Amit Varma]: and therefore, the curtailment of desire and the creation and the propagation of these

00:33:11.800 --> 00:33:12.800
[Guest]: narrow categories.

00:33:12.800 --> 00:33:13.800
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:33:13.800 --> 00:33:14.800
[Guest]: Does that make sense to you?

00:33:14.800 --> 00:33:16.440
[Guest]: It makes perfect sense to me.

00:33:16.440 --> 00:33:19.480
[Guest]: Thank you. Wendy Doniger has done a lot of work on this.

00:33:19.480 --> 00:33:24.400
[Guest]: And as she, as many others have pointed out, the Rig Veda, for instance, begins with a

00:33:24.400 --> 00:33:26.160
[Guest]: hymn to desire.

00:33:26.160 --> 00:33:31.040
[Guest]: And it begins with a hymn that says the only thing we can know is desire.

00:33:31.040 --> 00:33:33.080
[Guest]: And even that we can never fully understand.

00:33:33.080 --> 00:33:37.520
[Guest]: I mean, it pretty much is the thesis of my book, which is that all we know is that we're

00:33:37.520 --> 00:33:41.400
[Guest]: shaped by desire and that we can never know in what way it's going to shape us.

00:33:41.400 --> 00:33:44.360
[Guest]: That's the way the Rig Veda begins.

00:33:44.360 --> 00:33:49.040
[Guest]: It's not till about 800 BC and the Upanishads start getting written, which is sort of several

00:33:49.040 --> 00:33:54.080
[Guest]: hundred years later, that this second strand that you're talking about starts getting injected

00:33:54.080 --> 00:33:56.360
[Guest]: into these discourses.

00:33:56.360 --> 00:34:03.240
[Guest]: And so the Vedic literature in and of itself is actually quite invested in desire and sexuality,

00:34:03.240 --> 00:34:04.440
[Guest]: sometimes very disturbingly.

00:34:04.440 --> 00:34:07.920
[Guest]: For instance, you'll remember the story of Brahma.

00:34:07.920 --> 00:34:12.560
[Guest]: The reason why Brahma has four heads is because he's lusting after his daughter and wants

00:34:12.560 --> 00:34:15.720
[Guest]: to see her whichever direction she goes in.

00:34:15.720 --> 00:34:19.920
[Guest]: And that is, for us now, a shocking story on all kinds of fronts.

00:34:19.920 --> 00:34:22.320
[Guest]: First of all, he's a god, he's meant to be the creator.

00:34:22.320 --> 00:34:24.160
[Guest]: Second, this is what we call incest.

00:34:24.160 --> 00:34:27.280
[Guest]: Third, it's also what we call harassment, because she keeps trying to run away from

00:34:27.280 --> 00:34:31.680
[Guest]: him and he keeps growing heads so as to look at her from every direction.

00:34:31.680 --> 00:34:32.680
[Amit Varma]: That's in the Vedas.

00:34:32.680 --> 00:34:35.240
[Guest]: A fantastic God for the modern surveillance age.

00:34:35.240 --> 00:34:36.240
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:34:36.240 --> 00:34:37.240
[Guest]: That's right.

00:34:37.240 --> 00:34:38.240
[Guest]: The CCTV camera God.

00:34:38.240 --> 00:34:39.240
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:34:39.240 --> 00:34:44.400
[Guest]: And so our literatures of all kinds, our scriptures of all kinds, are actually filled with the

00:34:44.400 --> 00:34:50.000
[Guest]: most disturbing kinds of desires, at least disturbing from our vantage point today.

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:55.920
[Guest]: And so to suddenly then start that purification process must have come as a shock even then

00:34:55.920 --> 00:34:59.940
[Guest]: if it continues to reverberate for us today as a shock, and it does.

00:34:59.940 --> 00:35:05.240
[Guest]: So you can imagine, I don't know what kind of battles must have taken place, but some

00:35:05.240 --> 00:35:11.680
[Guest]: scholars say that one of the battles was the advent of Buddhism and Jainism.

00:35:11.680 --> 00:35:18.360
[Guest]: That they found a lot of people moving away from Vedic Hinduism, which was not of course

00:35:18.360 --> 00:35:21.600
[Guest]: called Hinduism then, so just Vedic religions.

00:35:21.600 --> 00:35:26.340
[Guest]: Moving away from Vedic religions to the asceticism of Buddhism.

00:35:26.340 --> 00:35:29.560
[Guest]: And so Vedic religions then said, oh my God, we're losing popularity.

00:35:29.560 --> 00:35:31.080
[Guest]: What are we going to do?

00:35:31.080 --> 00:35:35.680
[Guest]: And so they decided to inject a strand of asceticism into their discourses in order

00:35:35.680 --> 00:35:37.920
[Guest]: to woo these people back.

00:35:37.920 --> 00:35:42.060
[Guest]: That's why you have this entire sort of four stages of life where they say, okay, you can

00:35:42.060 --> 00:35:47.160
[Guest]: have sex in this one stage, the householder stage, but everything before and after a celibate,

00:35:47.160 --> 00:35:49.320
[Guest]: including the student stage.

00:35:49.320 --> 00:35:52.240
[Guest]: And then the varnaprastha stage, right, when you go into the forest.

00:35:52.240 --> 00:35:54.840
[Guest]: So all these are huge developments.

00:35:54.840 --> 00:36:00.640
[Guest]: We don't quite, we're not privy to the controversies at that time where they debated this.

00:36:00.640 --> 00:36:03.700
[Guest]: But no doubt they existed to a large extent.

00:36:03.700 --> 00:36:08.880
[Guest]: But you can see how this extremely political desire, which unfortunately continues to this

00:36:08.880 --> 00:36:15.340
[Guest]: day, where you want to use your religion to draw people away from other ways of being

00:36:15.340 --> 00:36:18.160
[Guest]: in the world, must have existed.

00:36:18.160 --> 00:36:23.880
[Guest]: It must have because Vedic religions definitely change or start changing.

00:36:23.880 --> 00:36:28.300
[Guest]: Which is why, of course, even in the Mahabharata, you have the story of the invention of marriage.

00:36:28.300 --> 00:36:30.640
[Guest]: Marriage did not exist for the longest time, right?

00:36:30.640 --> 00:36:36.040
[Guest]: And this person called Shweta Ketu is sort of described as the person who started marriage

00:36:36.040 --> 00:36:41.960
[Guest]: and he starts marriage because, and he's the son of a famous, what we would call today

00:36:41.960 --> 00:36:48.960
[Guest]: sexologist, son of a famous sexologist who teaches like Vatsyayana, sex and sexual positions

00:36:48.960 --> 00:36:51.200
[Guest]: to everybody.

00:36:51.200 --> 00:36:57.160
[Guest]: And Shweta Ketu's mother and father, father's a sexologist, mother, like most women then

00:36:57.160 --> 00:36:59.560
[Guest]: would have sex with whoever she wanted.

00:36:59.560 --> 00:37:04.080
[Guest]: And apparently he was so upset when he saw her one day walking off with another Brahmin

00:37:04.080 --> 00:37:07.440
[Guest]: that he said, why on earth should we have this freedom?

00:37:07.440 --> 00:37:11.120
[Guest]: And the father says, but son, this is the way we've always been.

00:37:11.120 --> 00:37:13.760
[Guest]: Why are you getting so upset about this?

00:37:13.760 --> 00:37:16.780
[Guest]: And he says, well, from henceforth, it's not going to be this way.

00:37:16.780 --> 00:37:20.680
[Guest]: Women must marry, to go back to your question of controlling women, women must marry one

00:37:20.680 --> 00:37:22.920
[Guest]: man and stay faithful.

00:37:22.920 --> 00:37:23.920
[Guest]: And that's marriage.

00:37:23.920 --> 00:37:26.040
[Guest]: And this is what it's going to be from now on.

00:37:26.040 --> 00:37:29.600
[Guest]: And apparently the father's horrified at that, but that is the beginning of marriage as we

00:37:29.600 --> 00:37:33.980
[Guest]: know it, which is rooted in the desire to curb women's desire.

00:37:33.980 --> 00:37:38.040
[Amit Varma]: So this is what you just said is a mythical instance of a historical process, obviously,

00:37:38.040 --> 00:37:43.400
[Guest]: but it captures the impulse that, you know, women should not be, our women should not

00:37:43.400 --> 00:37:46.080
[Amit Varma]: be sort of running around.

00:37:46.080 --> 00:37:50.800
[Amit Varma]: So we've had these different strains and we'll come back later to, you know, how wonderfully

00:37:50.800 --> 00:37:55.160
[Amit Varma]: wild and awesome Indian civilization has otherwise always been.

00:37:55.160 --> 00:38:00.240
[Amit Varma]: But the whole process is then further exacerbated by the British coming to India and partly

00:38:00.240 --> 00:38:04.160
[Amit Varma]: the British coming to India because, you know, they are incredibly sexually repressed.

00:38:04.160 --> 00:38:08.440
[Amit Varma]: And as you've pointed out, we had open borders, they walked in because they could and also

00:38:08.440 --> 00:38:12.040
[Amit Varma]: because they wanted some action, I guess, for them, it was like Bangkok is today for

00:38:12.040 --> 00:38:13.040
[Unknown]: many Indian men.

00:38:13.040 --> 00:38:14.040
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:38:14.040 --> 00:38:17.640
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a bit more about what happened, what did colonization do to us?

00:38:17.640 --> 00:38:18.640
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:38:18.640 --> 00:38:23.080
[Guest]: You know, I like to joke that when I was writing my book, I really tried hard not to blame

00:38:23.080 --> 00:38:24.720
[Guest]: the British for everything.

00:38:24.720 --> 00:38:25.720
[Guest]: And I just failed.

00:38:25.720 --> 00:38:29.560
[Guest]: But I want on the record that I made a good faith effort.

00:38:29.560 --> 00:38:36.280
[Guest]: I really tried because I am not overly invested in pointing the finger at one villain and

00:38:36.280 --> 00:38:39.520
[Guest]: saying, you know, that's the villain of the story because I don't think it ever works

00:38:39.520 --> 00:38:40.520
[Guest]: that way.

00:38:40.520 --> 00:38:42.800
[Guest]: I think life is more complicated than that.

00:38:42.800 --> 00:38:50.000
[Guest]: But unfortunately, with every one of my chapters, actually, this idea of plurality, this idea

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:58.560
[Guest]: of complexity, this idea of multiplicity would inevitably screech to a halt around a certain

00:38:58.560 --> 00:38:59.800
[Guest]: historical point.

00:38:59.800 --> 00:39:04.040
[Guest]: Now, whether that's because the British introduced certain laws, which they did, for instance,

00:39:04.040 --> 00:39:13.440
[Guest]: to outlaw hijras or any transsexual or transgender people, or 377, where they outlawed acts against

00:39:13.440 --> 00:39:20.800
[Guest]: nature, or if it was just sort of in pronouncements that they made with, say, Macaulay's minute

00:39:20.800 --> 00:39:28.240
[Guest]: on education, whatever it is, on all fronts, I found myself faced with this huge barrier.

00:39:28.240 --> 00:39:35.560
[Guest]: And so, yes, I think the British were to a large extent responsible for creating a version

00:39:35.560 --> 00:39:38.440
[Guest]: of India that we continue to inhabit largely.

00:39:38.440 --> 00:39:44.240
[Guest]: But, and I've said this in my book as well, they didn't pull this out of thin air.

00:39:44.240 --> 00:39:49.720
[Guest]: They didn't or couldn't have imposed their repression wholesale on us if they didn't

00:39:49.720 --> 00:39:55.040
[Guest]: already find within us some strands that were receptive to that repression.

00:39:55.040 --> 00:39:58.880
[Guest]: And so, as I've said before, and this is what I was stating earlier about the Upanishads

00:39:58.880 --> 00:40:01.480
[Guest]: suddenly sort of taking a turn.

00:40:01.480 --> 00:40:05.900
[Guest]: And as you mentioned, Manusmriti and the caste system, they found in a certain version of

00:40:05.900 --> 00:40:11.120
[Guest]: caste Hinduism, very fertile ground for their repression.

00:40:11.120 --> 00:40:15.680
[Guest]: And so what they were able to do, and this is, you know, completely a master stroke of

00:40:15.680 --> 00:40:22.000
[Guest]: politics, what they were able to do is cater to our worst instincts, because that's what

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:24.960
[Guest]: served their best interests.

00:40:24.960 --> 00:40:29.480
[Guest]: And so they said to us, you know, people are different from one another, you have to rigidly

00:40:29.480 --> 00:40:33.280
[Guest]: maintain that difference, you cannot, in fact, interact with one another.

00:40:33.280 --> 00:40:38.440
[Guest]: And that policy, which is now called by everybody, the policy of divide and rule, was exactly

00:40:38.440 --> 00:40:40.960
[Guest]: what they did in relation to India.

00:40:40.960 --> 00:40:45.160
[Guest]: Not only in relation to religion, as we know, and we're still sort of living the consequences

00:40:45.160 --> 00:40:48.680
[Guest]: of that, but also in relation to desire.

00:40:48.680 --> 00:40:53.960
[Guest]: So again, as I've said before, if you just look back to say, 10th, 11th century sculptures

00:40:53.960 --> 00:40:59.960
[Guest]: and Khajuraho and Puri and Konarak and all these temples across India, if you look at

00:40:59.960 --> 00:41:09.640
[Guest]: Sufi poetry, again, from the 8th century onwards, you will find the celebration of variety,

00:41:09.640 --> 00:41:12.000
[Guest]: the celebration of mixture.

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:17.860
[Guest]: And what the British did was to try and succeed to a large extent in separating the strands

00:41:17.860 --> 00:41:24.880
[Guest]: of that mixture, in sort of saying, oh, here you have a sculpture where there are two women,

00:41:24.880 --> 00:41:32.080
[Guest]: one man and one goat, goats belong in animals, men belong there with one woman, and the other

00:41:32.080 --> 00:41:33.440
[Guest]: woman is out here.

00:41:33.440 --> 00:41:38.080
[Guest]: And so they actually, I mean, you can actually sort of physically envisage it as deconstructing

00:41:38.080 --> 00:41:39.080
[Guest]: a recipe, right?

00:41:39.080 --> 00:41:42.320
[Guest]: It's like, you know, when you eat something delicious and you say, oh, I know what all

00:41:42.320 --> 00:41:45.040
[Guest]: went into it, and you list the ingredients.

00:41:45.040 --> 00:41:50.520
[Guest]: That's what they tried to do, is separate things out rather than enjoying the gorgeously

00:41:50.520 --> 00:41:53.120
[Guest]: delicious finished product.

00:41:53.120 --> 00:41:58.920
[Guest]: And but they were able to do that, as I said, because we already had a language of puritanical

00:41:58.920 --> 00:42:00.160
[Guest]: separation.

00:42:00.160 --> 00:42:08.680
[Guest]: We already had a language in which the shadow of a lower caste polluted an upper caste.

00:42:08.680 --> 00:42:16.200
[Guest]: And that language of pollution, which is very much behind still the language of swachhata

00:42:16.200 --> 00:42:21.680
[Guest]: or cleanliness, that is a language that they used with deadly effect.

00:42:21.680 --> 00:42:23.520
[Guest]: And they used it on all kinds of fronts.

00:42:23.520 --> 00:42:29.560
[Guest]: They used it to make us feel ashamed of our desires, ashamed of our bodies, and sort of

00:42:29.560 --> 00:42:35.640
[Guest]: instigated a wholesale repression, whose consequences, I think, are absolutely awful and horrific.

00:42:35.640 --> 00:42:39.960
[Amit Varma]: No, and as you've pointed out in your book, you know, many of the sculptures and temple

00:42:39.960 --> 00:42:43.760
[Amit Varma]: art of the 10th century were actually made illegal under the British, you won't be able

00:42:43.760 --> 00:42:47.880
[Guest]: to do those things like the two women, a man and a goat, there is actually a sculpture

00:42:47.880 --> 00:42:48.880
[Guest]: like that.

00:42:48.880 --> 00:42:52.240
[Amit Varma]: I don't think it's the goat, it's a horse.

00:42:52.240 --> 00:43:00.400
[Amit Varma]: See, you're embellishing, diminishing, not go to smaller than a horse is suddenly a more

00:43:00.400 --> 00:43:02.000
[Amit Varma]: attractive proposition.

00:43:02.000 --> 00:43:06.600
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that what the British did is somewhat willful, but at the same time,

00:43:06.600 --> 00:43:10.320
[Amit Varma]: there's an element of happenstance to it, in the sense that they come to this country,

00:43:10.320 --> 00:43:14.600
[Amit Varma]: they don't understand it is madly, deeply complex, they don't have the mental bandwidth

00:43:14.600 --> 00:43:17.600
[Amit Varma]: or perhaps capacity to engage with it completely.

00:43:17.600 --> 00:43:20.920
[Amit Varma]: So they try to draw simple narratives around it.

00:43:20.920 --> 00:43:24.960
[Amit Varma]: And their first guides, the interlocutors in the country are obviously the elites, the

00:43:24.960 --> 00:43:25.960
[Amit Varma]: Brahmins.

00:43:25.960 --> 00:43:31.220
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, so they are fed this Brahminical version where Manusmriti is a guide to morality

00:43:31.220 --> 00:43:32.220
[Amit Varma]: and so on.

00:43:32.220 --> 00:43:35.960
[Amit Varma]: And they extrapolate that to be the truth of the nation.

00:43:35.960 --> 00:43:40.680
[Amit Varma]: And it's very convenient because a lot of their Victorian morality aligns with that

00:43:40.680 --> 00:43:42.440
[Guest]: sort of aligns with that.

00:43:42.440 --> 00:43:50.200
[Amit Varma]: And yet what is interesting is that in our popular culture, we see these multiple representations

00:43:50.200 --> 00:43:55.520
[Amit Varma]: of desire, not just in the stories about our gods, but also in popular cinema.

00:43:55.520 --> 00:44:00.520
[Amit Varma]: So I'll just quote from your book here, where you write, quote, desire is of the world,

00:44:00.520 --> 00:44:06.440
[Amit Varma]: and it extends across what we now term, hetero and homosexuality, both of which coexist happily

00:44:06.440 --> 00:44:11.760
[Amit Varma]: alongside polyamory, which is Krishna with many gopis and celibacy, saints with matted

00:44:11.760 --> 00:44:12.760
[Unknown]: hair.

00:44:12.760 --> 00:44:13.760
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:44:13.760 --> 00:44:17.920
[Amit Varma]: And later, you say, quote, all around me in the Delhi of the 1970s and 80s were Hindi

00:44:17.920 --> 00:44:24.520
[Amit Varma]: films that celebrated same sex attachments, Anand, older women desiring younger men, Doosra

00:44:24.520 --> 00:44:28.280
[Amit Varma]: Aadmi, and cross couple desire, Angur.

00:44:28.280 --> 00:44:33.640
[Amit Varma]: So stop quote, yeah, so you know, so and later again, you say, quote, millions of people

00:44:33.640 --> 00:44:38.320
[Amit Varma]: know the stories of cross dressing gods, men hold hands freely, women frequently sleep

00:44:38.320 --> 00:44:39.440
[Amit Varma]: in the same bed.

00:44:39.440 --> 00:44:44.760
[Amit Varma]: This is a country that is deeply homophilic, even as it is often superficially homophobic.

00:44:44.760 --> 00:44:49.600
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote, tell me a bit about this angle, because you know, your book very fascinatingly

00:44:49.600 --> 00:44:54.120
[Amit Varma]: the first chapter, and we are very close to Mehrauli, so I was struck with the urge to

00:44:54.120 --> 00:45:00.760
[Amit Varma]: actually go and see the shrine, you really should, I actually will, and this is the joint

00:45:00.760 --> 00:45:05.240
[Guest]: tomb of Jamali and Kamali, tell me a little bit about that.

00:45:05.240 --> 00:45:10.760
[Guest]: I just want to sort of go back to your thing about cinema, or Hindi cinema, you know, Nick,

00:45:10.760 --> 00:45:15.960
[Guest]: two weeks from now, this much wanted film is going to be released, Shubh Mangal's Yada

00:45:15.960 --> 00:45:22.720
[Guest]: Saavdhan, which is being touted as a gay love story with Ayushman Khurrana and whoever his

00:45:22.720 --> 00:45:24.560
[Guest]: love interest is.

00:45:24.560 --> 00:45:28.800
[Guest]: And people are so delighted, there's a long article in the Indian Express the other day

00:45:28.800 --> 00:45:35.200
[Guest]: about how Indian cinemas finally come of age, and we're dealing with issues of homosexuality

00:45:35.200 --> 00:45:39.920
[Guest]: and openly dealing with issues of desire between men.

00:45:39.920 --> 00:45:46.480
[Guest]: And that article, like many other such things really irritated me, because it seemed just

00:45:46.480 --> 00:45:54.440
[Guest]: to blindly be speaking a language of Americanized identity politics, completely oblivious to

00:45:54.440 --> 00:45:57.520
[Guest]: what's quite literally in our backyards.

00:45:57.520 --> 00:46:02.680
[Guest]: And so this idea of, oh, here is a gay film, and finally, Indian movies have come of age,

00:46:02.680 --> 00:46:08.440
[Guest]: A, forgets the history of Hindi cinema, which is the queerest history of any cinema tradition

00:46:08.440 --> 00:46:10.640
[Guest]: anywhere in the world.

00:46:10.640 --> 00:46:15.160
[Guest]: And so to forget that is, first of all, not to know your Hindi cinema very well.

00:46:15.160 --> 00:46:21.400
[Guest]: But the second thing it's forgetting is a much older, much longer tradition of celebrating

00:46:21.400 --> 00:46:25.300
[Guest]: same sex desire in this part of the world.

00:46:25.300 --> 00:46:30.480
[Guest]: And the example that you just used from my book, which I talk about, which is the example

00:46:30.480 --> 00:46:36.720
[Guest]: of various Dargahs across the subcontinent, most close by to us, the Dargah of Jamali

00:46:36.720 --> 00:46:38.200
[Guest]: and Kamali.

00:46:38.200 --> 00:46:41.400
[Guest]: And this is one of those Dargahs, it's called the Gay Taj Mahal.

00:46:41.400 --> 00:46:45.800
[Guest]: It's actually beautiful, although one can't get into the actual tomb because it's under

00:46:45.800 --> 00:46:51.040
[Guest]: lock and key, but it's beautiful when you look at it from the outside as well.

00:46:51.040 --> 00:46:58.200
[Guest]: And Jamali and Kamali's Dargah is extremely commonplace, which is to say, as an idea in

00:46:58.200 --> 00:47:03.180
[Guest]: which two men are buried together side by side, it is extremely commonplace.

00:47:03.180 --> 00:47:08.600
[Guest]: And as we continue to know that the idea of being together in this life and the next and

00:47:08.600 --> 00:47:16.840
[Guest]: the next is a very, very strong indicator of desire, lasting love, love that sort of

00:47:16.840 --> 00:47:19.320
[Guest]: does not know the barrier of death.

00:47:19.320 --> 00:47:24.640
[Guest]: And so you have these multiple sites across the subcontinent in which a saint and his

00:47:24.640 --> 00:47:28.600
[Guest]: male disciple are buried side by side.

00:47:28.600 --> 00:47:33.080
[Guest]: This is to go back to what I said about the complicated relation to education as well

00:47:33.080 --> 00:47:36.200
[Guest]: that we have, right, and desire and education.

00:47:36.200 --> 00:47:42.700
[Guest]: The saint and his disciple are buried side by side, two men, without any problem, without

00:47:42.700 --> 00:47:44.700
[Guest]: any comment.

00:47:44.700 --> 00:47:48.720
[Guest]: Clearly the student is buried by people who have survived him.

00:47:48.720 --> 00:47:52.040
[Guest]: So there's no sort of talk even after these two men are dead.

00:47:52.040 --> 00:47:54.840
[Guest]: And so you have these spaces.

00:47:54.840 --> 00:48:00.300
[Guest]: And of course, Nizamuddin and Khosrow are perhaps even more famous an example, also

00:48:00.300 --> 00:48:08.280
[Guest]: in our backyard here, where Khosrow's poetry about Nizamuddin is just frankly, so erotic

00:48:08.280 --> 00:48:10.600
[Guest]: that it beats most erotic poetry I've ever read.

00:48:10.600 --> 00:48:12.320
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I want to quote from a bit of it.

00:48:12.320 --> 00:48:15.200
[Amit Varma]: And this, of course, is translation because he didn't write in English.

00:48:15.200 --> 00:48:20.480
[Amit Varma]: This is quoted in your book, Amir Khosrow on Nizamuddin Auliya, quote, my blossoming

00:48:20.480 --> 00:48:22.200
[Amit Varma]: youth is red with passion.

00:48:22.200 --> 00:48:23.760
[Amit Varma]: How can I spend this time alone?

00:48:23.760 --> 00:48:26.120
[Amit Varma]: Will someone persuade Nizamuddin Auliya?

00:48:26.120 --> 00:48:30.160
[Amit Varma]: For the more I coax him, the more he acts coy, I'll break my bangles and throw them

00:48:30.160 --> 00:48:31.160
[Amit Varma]: on the bed.

00:48:31.160 --> 00:48:32.940
[Amit Varma]: I'll set fire to these bodies of mine.

00:48:32.940 --> 00:48:34.200
[Amit Varma]: The empty bed frightens me.

00:48:34.200 --> 00:48:36.440
[Amit Varma]: The fire of separation scorches me.

00:48:36.440 --> 00:48:37.440
[Guest]: Stop quote.

00:48:37.440 --> 00:48:38.440
[Guest]: Exactly right.

00:48:38.440 --> 00:48:39.440
[Guest]: See what I mean.

00:48:39.440 --> 00:48:45.360
[Guest]: You know, we are so timid today and this is a very blazing, literally explicit expression

00:48:45.360 --> 00:48:47.160
[Guest]: of desire now.

00:48:47.160 --> 00:48:49.000
[Amit Varma]: And these are the people who are buried side by side.

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:51.680
[Amit Varma]: And it's not just sexual desire, it's also romantic love.

00:48:51.680 --> 00:48:56.480
[Amit Varma]: Like after Nizamuddin dies, you quote in your book about this couplet of his, where he talks

00:48:56.480 --> 00:49:00.440
[Amit Varma]: about let the hair hang over my face because the universe is dark.

00:49:00.440 --> 00:49:01.440
[Guest]: It's dark.

00:49:01.440 --> 00:49:02.440
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:49:02.440 --> 00:49:03.960
[Guest]: That, you know, darkness has set upon the world.

00:49:03.960 --> 00:49:08.080
[Guest]: And so my hair is just going to cover my face because there's no light left to see.

00:49:08.080 --> 00:49:15.360
[Guest]: That kind of intensity, that kind of passion is unheard of in whatever shubh, mangal, saavdhan,

00:49:15.360 --> 00:49:18.520
[Guest]: zyada saavdhan, kam saavdhan, whatever it is that we want to do.

00:49:18.520 --> 00:49:20.400
[Guest]: I'm glad it's being made.

00:49:20.400 --> 00:49:27.240
[Guest]: But to tout that as finally India has arrived is such an act of ignorance that it boggles

00:49:27.240 --> 00:49:28.760
[Guest]: my mind.

00:49:28.760 --> 00:49:34.160
[Guest]: And the sense of even as we are trying to elevate India as finally arriving, we're actually

00:49:34.160 --> 00:49:39.160
[Guest]: forgetting India and its histories in all their multiplicities.

00:49:39.160 --> 00:49:42.360
[Guest]: And that's what is just completely mind boggling to me.

00:49:42.360 --> 00:49:43.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:49:43.360 --> 00:49:44.360
[Amit Varma]: And I was also struck in all of this.

00:49:44.360 --> 00:49:48.280
[Amit Varma]: It's not just Jamali and Kamali and you, of course, describe their tomb, showing how the

00:49:48.280 --> 00:49:51.200
[Amit Varma]: tomb itself is both male and female.

00:49:51.200 --> 00:49:52.200
[Guest]: Right.

00:49:52.200 --> 00:49:53.200
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:49:53.200 --> 00:49:56.600
[Guest]: To go back to what we were saying earlier, when we said, you know, this desire is desire

00:49:56.600 --> 00:49:58.600
[Guest]: and that desire is not desire.

00:49:58.600 --> 00:50:02.840
[Guest]: One of the things I'm fascinated by is the desire of architecture.

00:50:02.840 --> 00:50:10.640
[Guest]: And what is fascinating about this Dargah is that among Sufis, the graves are very carefully

00:50:10.640 --> 00:50:13.160
[Guest]: delineated between male and female.

00:50:13.160 --> 00:50:18.480
[Guest]: And so the male graves have a sort of pen box on top of them because it's understood

00:50:18.480 --> 00:50:22.120
[Guest]: that the Sufis will write the Kalam, will use the Kalam to write.

00:50:22.120 --> 00:50:26.600
[Guest]: And this is what they're taking with them because they're so intellectually oriented.

00:50:26.600 --> 00:50:31.260
[Guest]: And the women Sufis have a flat top on them because the idea is that they are paper on

00:50:31.260 --> 00:50:33.720
[Guest]: which will be written.

00:50:33.720 --> 00:50:38.200
[Guest]: And if we sort of set aside the sort of sexist nature of that for a minute, what's fascinating

00:50:38.200 --> 00:50:43.440
[Guest]: to me about Jamali and Kamali's Dargah is that it is flat on top, which is to say it

00:50:43.440 --> 00:50:49.920
[Guest]: is feminine on top, whereas inside it's a dome, it's a pen box.

00:50:49.920 --> 00:50:56.880
[Guest]: And so it's a male sign of masculinity overlaid by a sign of femininity without deciding necessarily

00:50:56.880 --> 00:50:59.900
[Guest]: which one is the correct one or the proper one.

00:50:59.900 --> 00:51:03.320
[Guest]: It's giving us quite literally a hermaphroditic desire.

00:51:03.320 --> 00:51:07.960
[Amit Varma]: And you call them signs of femininity because it was a custom that the tombs of female saints

00:51:07.960 --> 00:51:10.960
[Guest]: will be flat on top and the men will have domes.

00:51:10.960 --> 00:51:16.520
[Amit Varma]: So this very interesting sort of incorporation of both elements into the design also.

00:51:16.520 --> 00:51:17.520
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:51:17.520 --> 00:51:19.600
[Guest]: And this is this is something that continues to this day.

00:51:19.600 --> 00:51:25.360
[Guest]: For instance, I always sort of tell my students the way in which desks and chairs are designed

00:51:25.360 --> 00:51:27.520
[Guest]: have desire in mind when they do that.

00:51:27.520 --> 00:51:35.160
[Guest]: So, for instance, when you go to schools, the desks will always be blank in front because

00:51:35.160 --> 00:51:38.180
[Guest]: the assumption is that the teacher should be able to see what the students are doing

00:51:38.180 --> 00:51:42.440
[Guest]: with their hands and between their legs, whereas the older you get.

00:51:42.440 --> 00:51:46.520
[Guest]: And so, for instance, if you're a professor in an office or if you're an older student,

00:51:46.520 --> 00:51:53.280
[Guest]: the desks will have what are known officially this is a technical term as modesty panels.

00:51:53.280 --> 00:51:57.160
[Guest]: The covering of the front of the table is known as a modesty panel because the assumption

00:51:57.160 --> 00:52:01.280
[Guest]: is you should be able to free to do whatever you want behind that table without anyone

00:52:01.280 --> 00:52:02.560
[Guest]: seeing you.

00:52:02.560 --> 00:52:08.120
[Guest]: So everything around us is articulated in relation to desire.

00:52:08.120 --> 00:52:11.900
[Guest]: And that was one of the things I was just fascinated by, which is that let's think about

00:52:11.900 --> 00:52:13.920
[Guest]: everyday life.

00:52:13.920 --> 00:52:14.920
[Guest]: Forget anything else.

00:52:14.920 --> 00:52:21.000
[Guest]: How our everyday life is saturated with these things about desire and how the origin plays

00:52:21.000 --> 00:52:25.520
[Amit Varma]: back to something we didn't even realize, like this is news to me, you know, and modesty

00:52:25.520 --> 00:52:28.880
[Amit Varma]: covering is indeed a great help in my office years.

00:52:28.880 --> 00:52:32.240
[Guest]: But maybe modesty is alien to you, Amit.

00:52:32.240 --> 00:52:34.240
[Amit Varma]: Well, what can I say?

00:52:34.240 --> 00:52:38.760
[Amit Varma]: And I also found this fascinating, I mean, this is really hilarious, where you spoke

00:52:38.760 --> 00:52:44.800
[Guest]: about the traveling tomb of Bulleh Shah as an example of mobile desire.

00:52:44.800 --> 00:52:45.800
[Guest]: What is this traveling tomb?

00:52:45.800 --> 00:52:46.800
[Guest]: It's just fascinating.

00:52:46.800 --> 00:52:51.120
[Guest]: I mean, there is a tomb of Bulleh Shah in what is now Pakistan.

00:52:51.120 --> 00:52:58.800
[Guest]: And I'm driving down from Manali, and there's a sign saying Bulleh Shah Ji Ka Dargah.

00:52:58.800 --> 00:53:01.960
[Guest]: And so I asked the driver, it's like, oh, my God, is this suddenly changed?

00:53:01.960 --> 00:53:04.160
[Guest]: Are we suddenly in Pakistan?

00:53:04.160 --> 00:53:05.560
[Guest]: Isn't this, wouldn't this be amazing?

00:53:05.560 --> 00:53:09.640
[Guest]: And the taxi driver says, nahi, nahi, jee, yeh Bulleh Shah Ji Ka Dargah toh har jagah

00:53:09.640 --> 00:53:10.640
[Guest]: hota hai.

00:53:10.640 --> 00:53:12.600
[Guest]: It's anywhere you want it to be.

00:53:12.600 --> 00:53:18.840
[Guest]: Which actually among, for instance, the Bhakti saints, there was this Namdev in Maharashtra

00:53:18.840 --> 00:53:23.280
[Guest]: and things like that, there is a very clear sense of what's called a mobile temple, which

00:53:23.280 --> 00:53:26.600
[Guest]: is you carry your temple with you wherever you go.

00:53:26.600 --> 00:53:30.720
[Guest]: So you don't have to, in fact, be fixed on a temple or a particular site, which of course

00:53:30.720 --> 00:53:34.280
[Guest]: throws new light on the entire Ram Janmabhoomi Ayodhya thing, right?

00:53:34.280 --> 00:53:39.820
[Guest]: Which is that a fixed temple actually was not the truth of practicing religions that

00:53:39.820 --> 00:53:41.600
[Guest]: now call themselves Hinduism.

00:53:41.600 --> 00:53:48.320
[Guest]: Similarly, in Sufi traditions, this idea of a Dargah is both something that is there set

00:53:48.320 --> 00:53:53.120
[Guest]: in stone, quite literally, and something that travels with you wherever you go.

00:53:53.120 --> 00:53:58.600
[Guest]: And so people can be in love with Nizamuddin wherever they are, or people can be followers

00:53:58.600 --> 00:54:03.040
[Guest]: of Jamali wherever they are, they don't need to be present at that physical site.

00:54:03.040 --> 00:54:06.120
[Guest]: And that to me is something that's deeply spiritual, right?

00:54:06.120 --> 00:54:13.000
[Guest]: That's deeply evocative in the sense of, I am, I both am and I'm not here.

00:54:13.000 --> 00:54:16.560
[Guest]: And that kind of Sufi tradition, and I talk about that story in my book about how they

00:54:16.560 --> 00:54:23.120
[Guest]: say the mark of a Sufi saint is someone who can preside over his own burial, right?

00:54:23.120 --> 00:54:27.680
[Guest]: And that sense of both being here and not here, going back to Shakespeare's negative

00:54:27.680 --> 00:54:31.880
[Guest]: capability, I'm writing, but I'm not writing myself.

00:54:31.880 --> 00:54:35.320
[Guest]: That kind of ability I find absolutely powerful.

00:54:35.320 --> 00:54:42.000
[Guest]: And that kind of ability is what I think encourages empathy, understanding across borders.

00:54:42.000 --> 00:54:44.720
[Guest]: And that's what we're so in danger of losing now.

00:54:44.720 --> 00:54:48.560
[Amit Varma]: So you know, before we head into a commercial break, I want to take you back to what you

00:54:48.560 --> 00:54:51.400
[Amit Varma]: said a little earlier, which is, you know, it's not there in your book, but I found it

00:54:51.400 --> 00:54:56.120
[Amit Varma]: fairly interesting where you were talking about the queer histories of Bollywood, for

00:54:56.120 --> 00:54:57.120
[Amit Varma]: example.

00:54:57.120 --> 00:55:02.080
[Amit Varma]: And this notion which I have, you know, I can see both sides of where it is coming from

00:55:02.080 --> 00:55:07.360
[Amit Varma]: that on the one hand, I'm really glad that films like Kapoor and Sons and shows like

00:55:07.360 --> 00:55:12.240
[Amit Varma]: Made in Heaven are being made where, you know, gay protagonists are shown as completely normal

00:55:12.240 --> 00:55:16.360
[Amit Varma]: people with completely normal desires, and it's not like something exceptional or not

00:55:16.360 --> 00:55:19.320
[Amit Varma]: caricatured in other ways.

00:55:19.320 --> 00:55:24.880
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, it strikes me that the reason that these specific films are like

00:55:24.880 --> 00:55:30.240
[Amit Varma]: this is that Bollywood right now is being driven by elites.

00:55:30.240 --> 00:55:35.040
[Amit Varma]: And this is a reflection of how the elite see themselves or how they want to see themselves.

00:55:35.040 --> 00:55:36.040
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:55:36.040 --> 00:55:41.800
[Amit Varma]: And it's not necessarily a reflection of popular culture necessarily, I think TikTok gets closer

00:55:41.800 --> 00:55:43.280
[Amit Varma]: to popular culture.

00:55:43.280 --> 00:55:48.240
[Amit Varma]: And while it's incredibly, I'm addicted to TikTok, and it's absolutely awesome.

00:55:48.240 --> 00:55:54.080
[Amit Varma]: But it's also, you know, it also shows our society's misogyny and sexism, and all of

00:55:54.080 --> 00:55:55.080
[Amit Varma]: these things.

00:55:55.080 --> 00:55:58.880
[Amit Varma]: So, since you've thought more deeply about this than I have, obviously, can you elaborate

00:55:58.880 --> 00:55:59.880
[Guest]: a little bit?

00:55:59.880 --> 00:56:03.200
[Guest]: Actually, one thing that you said really struck a chord with me, and a friend of mine said

00:56:03.200 --> 00:56:08.240
[Guest]: this the other day, she said, and I enjoyed Made in Heaven as much as anybody else, although

00:56:08.240 --> 00:56:11.960
[Guest]: it took me a bit of time to get into it, but I'm really waiting for the second season to

00:56:11.960 --> 00:56:13.200
[Guest]: come out and things like that.

00:56:13.200 --> 00:56:18.600
[Guest]: But a friend of mine pointed out what's interesting about Made in Heaven is that the gay male

00:56:18.600 --> 00:56:24.160
[Guest]: protagonist who finally comes out at the end, in the narrative of the story, he's the one

00:56:24.160 --> 00:56:29.120
[Guest]: who goes out and starts a certain gay rights movement.

00:56:29.120 --> 00:56:35.120
[Guest]: Rather than placing him within the long history of sort of queer rights movements in India,

00:56:35.120 --> 00:56:38.160
[Guest]: he is shown as the person who is leading the way.

00:56:38.160 --> 00:56:42.440
[Guest]: To go back to your point of a certain elite kind of narrative that sees itself as being

00:56:42.440 --> 00:56:47.680
[Guest]: emancipated, that sees itself as being the sort of torchbearers of freedom, rather than

00:56:47.680 --> 00:56:53.000
[Guest]: actually saying freedoms have existed in this part of the world for much longer than you

00:56:53.000 --> 00:56:55.200
[Guest]: can even remember.

00:56:55.200 --> 00:56:59.800
[Guest]: And what about if we go back to that rather than sort of saying, here we are in a brand

00:56:59.800 --> 00:57:00.800
[Guest]: new direction.

00:57:00.800 --> 00:57:05.600
[Guest]: So this idea of reinventing the wheel, as though it has never been done before, is something

00:57:05.600 --> 00:57:08.320
[Guest]: that can be very irksome and very annoying.

00:57:08.320 --> 00:57:11.480
[Guest]: And because I enjoyed Made in Heaven, it was not that annoying to me there, but it's annoying

00:57:11.480 --> 00:57:12.880
[Guest]: to me in several other places.

00:57:12.880 --> 00:57:16.120
[Guest]: I didn't love Kapoor and Sons, I didn't hate it, for instance.

00:57:16.120 --> 00:57:21.760
[Guest]: But for me, a film like Goliyon ki Raas Leela Ram Leela is much more queer.

00:57:21.760 --> 00:57:29.040
[Guest]: A film like Dostana is much more queer than someone that has an openly gay protagonist.

00:57:29.040 --> 00:57:33.480
[Guest]: That is no doubt doing an important kind of work.

00:57:33.480 --> 00:57:37.800
[Guest]: But it is also catering to a kind of identity politics that I find problematic.

00:57:37.800 --> 00:57:44.240
[Guest]: So for instance, generations of gay men in India, like generations of gay men in the

00:57:44.240 --> 00:57:48.280
[Guest]: US with a different relation to a different person, generations of gay men in India have

00:57:48.280 --> 00:57:53.920
[Guest]: grown up identifying with the icon of Helen, for instance, just like generations of gay

00:57:53.920 --> 00:57:57.560
[Guest]: men in the US have grown up identifying with the icon of Marilyn Monroe.

00:57:57.560 --> 00:58:00.760
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I had an episode with a friend of mine, Vivek Tejuja, who's just written a book

00:58:00.760 --> 00:58:05.040
[Amit Varma]: and he spoke at length about how he grew up, you know, with Helen as his icon.

00:58:05.040 --> 00:58:06.040
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:58:06.040 --> 00:58:11.040
[Guest]: And so that kind of cross-identification is what is queer.

00:58:11.040 --> 00:58:17.160
[Guest]: Nowadays, when you're saying, oh, gay men should look for a gay man in the narrative,

00:58:17.160 --> 00:58:19.400
[Guest]: you're shutting down on other possibilities.

00:58:19.400 --> 00:58:22.640
[Guest]: You're shutting down on the fact that gay men might identify with women.

00:58:22.640 --> 00:58:26.400
[Guest]: You're shutting down on the fact that gay women might identify with men or any kinds

00:58:26.400 --> 00:58:28.760
[Guest]: of cross-border attraction.

00:58:28.760 --> 00:58:34.880
[Guest]: And so I see what is to be gained, but I also see what is being lost in that.

00:58:34.880 --> 00:58:39.460
[Guest]: So every time we present a gay protagonist and pat ourselves on the back for being so

00:58:39.460 --> 00:58:45.140
[Guest]: liberal and liberated, we also have to remember that what we're losing is that texture of

00:58:45.140 --> 00:58:50.680
[Guest]: desire that did not predict in advance who I must identify with, that was able to leave

00:58:50.680 --> 00:58:57.200
[Guest]: scope for cross-identification, that was able to leave scope for me as a gay man to identify

00:58:57.200 --> 00:58:59.880
[Guest]: with a female vamp.

00:58:59.880 --> 00:59:01.160
[Amit Varma]: That's what we're losing right now.

00:59:01.160 --> 00:59:04.080
[Amit Varma]: Now these textures of desires are very complicated.

00:59:04.080 --> 00:59:06.360
[Amit Varma]: The real world is very complex.

00:59:06.360 --> 00:59:11.440
[Amit Varma]: Cinema and all popular art necessarily aims to keep it simple, simpler narratives work

00:59:11.440 --> 00:59:12.440
[Amit Varma]: better.

00:59:12.440 --> 00:59:13.440
[Amit Varma]: You know, the Shakespeare would disagree.

00:59:13.440 --> 00:59:14.440
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:59:14.440 --> 00:59:15.440
[Guest]: I was just going to say that.

00:59:15.440 --> 00:59:16.440
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:59:16.440 --> 00:59:20.080
[Amit Varma]: But over here, that is sort of, I mean, unless you're Shakespeare, you're not going to pull

00:59:20.080 --> 00:59:22.400
[Amit Varma]: off complexity quite like that.

00:59:22.400 --> 00:59:27.240
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, you have these urges to therefore simplify the narrative, make it explicable

00:59:27.240 --> 00:59:28.240
[Unknown]: and so on.

00:59:28.240 --> 00:59:29.240
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:59:29.240 --> 00:59:33.920
[Amit Varma]: Which is why I'm curious about what you meant by the queer history of Bollywood per se.

00:59:33.920 --> 00:59:34.920
[Guest]: Can you elaborate a bit on that?

00:59:34.920 --> 00:59:38.600
[Guest]: I mean, if you just look at these films of the, of the seventies and eighties, all these

00:59:38.600 --> 00:59:46.360
[Guest]: so-called, you know, dosti films, these yaari films, always sort of featuring two or more

00:59:46.360 --> 00:59:51.320
[Guest]: of a cast from Amitabh Bachchan, Dharmendra, Shashi Kapoor, Rajesh Khanna.

00:59:51.320 --> 00:59:52.800
[Guest]: And you refer to Anand, of course.

00:59:52.800 --> 00:59:53.800
[Guest]: Of course.

00:59:53.800 --> 01:00:00.800
[Guest]: And that's just one example where the intensity of the bond between the men, it may end up

01:00:00.800 --> 01:00:02.600
[Guest]: in heterosexual marriage, right?

01:00:02.600 --> 01:00:07.520
[Guest]: With Jaya Bhaduri or Hema Malini or whoever it is, but the film is about the intensity

01:00:07.520 --> 01:00:09.000
[Guest]: of the bond between the men.

01:00:09.000 --> 01:00:14.120
[Guest]: Now, this is where actually an analogy with Shakespeare comes in because all of Shakespeare's

01:00:14.120 --> 01:00:22.560
[Guest]: plays, especially his comedies, will end with heterosexual couplings without question.

01:00:22.560 --> 01:00:28.620
[Guest]: But the force of the narrative is the force of the bonds between same-sex couples.

01:00:28.620 --> 01:00:29.620
[Guest]: So what do you do with that?

01:00:29.620 --> 01:00:30.620
[Guest]: We have a choice, right?

01:00:30.620 --> 01:00:33.320
[Guest]: Either we say the end justifies everything.

01:00:33.320 --> 01:00:36.920
[Guest]: And the fact that Amitabh Bachchan and Jaya Bhaduri get together at the end means forget

01:00:36.920 --> 01:00:38.960
[Guest]: anything else that happened with anybody else.

01:00:38.960 --> 01:00:39.960
[Guest]: You can certainly do that.

01:00:39.960 --> 01:00:41.880
[Guest]: And a lot of people have done that.

01:00:41.880 --> 01:00:46.000
[Guest]: So people like me who are interested in The Textures of Desire, we know that the end is

01:00:46.000 --> 01:00:49.920
[Guest]: by no means the only thing that is going on.

01:00:49.920 --> 01:00:54.640
[Guest]: So for us, our energy is derived from the fabric of the rest of the film.

01:00:54.640 --> 01:00:59.760
[Guest]: Like two hours and 58 minutes, these two men are staring deep into each other's eyes.

01:00:59.760 --> 01:01:02.940
[Guest]: For two minutes at the end, you have the man and the woman together.

01:01:02.940 --> 01:01:05.640
[Guest]: How does the one outweigh the other?

01:01:05.640 --> 01:01:09.960
[Guest]: And so for me, if we actually take cinema seriously, the tropes of cinema seriously,

01:01:09.960 --> 01:01:14.560
[Guest]: who is looking into whose eye, who is saying, I cannot live without you, who is saying,

01:01:14.560 --> 01:01:20.360
[Guest]: I'm going to die if I cannot have you, quite literally in the shape of Anand, that's where

01:01:20.360 --> 01:01:21.360
[Guest]: desire is.

01:01:21.360 --> 01:01:26.000
[Guest]: So for instance, if you just sort of did a blind test and you say, here are a list of

01:01:26.000 --> 01:01:30.640
[Guest]: the dialogues that character A is saying to character B, identify who character A is and

01:01:30.640 --> 01:01:32.760
[Guest]: who character B is.

01:01:32.760 --> 01:01:37.560
[Guest]: Most people from a heterosexist perspective will say one is a man and A is a man and B

01:01:37.560 --> 01:01:38.560
[Guest]: is a woman.

01:01:38.560 --> 01:01:43.280
[Guest]: And then you say, reveal A is Amitabh Bachchan and B is Rajesh Khanna.

01:01:43.280 --> 01:01:45.960
[Guest]: What do you do with that?

01:01:45.960 --> 01:01:47.640
[Guest]: And so this is what I'm interested in.

01:01:47.640 --> 01:01:53.360
[Guest]: That's what I mean about the queer pasts of Bollywood is that there has been a comfort

01:01:53.360 --> 01:02:00.440
[Guest]: with even a celebration of that mode of queerness that will not come out and say, hey, I am

01:02:00.440 --> 01:02:07.160
[Guest]: gay, but that covers a spectrum of desire that I find more interesting and fascinating

01:02:07.160 --> 01:02:11.840
[Guest]: than the sort of identity category mode of sexuality, which we are inhabiting today.

01:02:11.840 --> 01:02:16.520
[Amit Varma]: I think there's also, you know, I mean, what instinctively comes to me is how should one

01:02:16.520 --> 01:02:19.680
[Amit Varma]: distinguish sexual desire from non-sexual desire?

01:02:19.680 --> 01:02:23.880
[Amit Varma]: Like it just seems to me, for example, looking back at Anand, which I will never view in

01:02:23.880 --> 01:02:27.680
[Amit Varma]: the same way because of you, you have spoilt it for me, or perhaps you made it better for

01:02:27.680 --> 01:02:29.440
[Amit Varma]: me, who knows.

01:02:29.440 --> 01:02:33.680
[Amit Varma]: But it seems to me that it doesn't come across as sexual desire in the film, certainly not

01:02:33.680 --> 01:02:39.080
[Amit Varma]: as overtly sexual desire, or maybe my gaze was wrong, and I'll see differently now, regardless.

01:02:39.080 --> 01:02:44.080
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, is there a danger that when you're sort of, let's say that as a scholar,

01:02:44.080 --> 01:02:47.080
[Amit Varma]: when you're looking at that kind of cinema, and you're studying queer cinema, is there

01:02:47.080 --> 01:02:52.560
[Amit Varma]: a danger of looking too much and reading into, like, I remember, you know, when I was a teenager,

01:02:52.560 --> 01:02:56.640
[Amit Varma]: I saw the film Dead Poets Society, which is such a lovely film, and I absolutely loved

01:02:56.640 --> 01:02:57.640
[Amit Varma]: it then.

01:02:57.640 --> 01:03:01.520
[Amit Varma]: And then I came across a review in some esoteric magazine, which spoke about the suppressed

01:03:01.520 --> 01:03:03.720
[Amit Varma]: homoerotic desire in the film.

01:03:03.720 --> 01:03:05.560
[Amit Varma]: And I was like, what is this rubbish?

01:03:05.560 --> 01:03:08.800
[Amit Varma]: These are people who are over-interpreting, over-analyzing.

01:03:08.800 --> 01:03:09.800
[Guest]: Is that a danger?

01:03:09.800 --> 01:03:15.360
[Guest]: You know, what always fascinates me about questions like this, and I think it's a very

01:03:15.360 --> 01:03:18.400
[Guest]: good question, because the question a lot of people have.

01:03:18.400 --> 01:03:23.800
[Guest]: What fascinates me about these kinds of questions is the implicit assumption that my reading

01:03:23.800 --> 01:03:26.720
[Guest]: is just the right amount of reading.

01:03:26.720 --> 01:03:32.520
[Guest]: And somebody else's reading is over-interpreting or over-reading, and it's too much or excessive.

01:03:32.520 --> 01:03:38.120
[Guest]: And that seems to me to emerge always from a position in which my reading is challenged,

01:03:38.120 --> 01:03:42.820
[Guest]: or my reading is shown perhaps to be inadequate to the material at hand.

01:03:42.820 --> 01:03:45.680
[Guest]: So I don't think there is any such thing as over-interpretation.

01:03:45.680 --> 01:03:49.960
[Guest]: I certainly think there are wrong readings or bad readings, but I don't think there's

01:03:49.960 --> 01:03:54.400
[Guest]: anything known as over-interpretation, as opposed to just right interpretation.

01:03:54.400 --> 01:03:57.720
[Guest]: I think all interpretation is reading into the material.

01:03:57.720 --> 01:04:00.800
[Guest]: You're always interpreting in a certain way.

01:04:00.800 --> 01:04:09.760
[Guest]: We've all grown up in such a misogynistic, heterosexist framework that that kind of reading

01:04:09.760 --> 01:04:11.480
[Guest]: appears normal to us.

01:04:11.480 --> 01:04:14.600
[Guest]: And I'm including myself in this 100%.

01:04:14.600 --> 01:04:18.360
[Guest]: And that kind of reading appears normal to us precisely because we've always been told

01:04:18.360 --> 01:04:19.360
[Guest]: that is the truth.

01:04:19.360 --> 01:04:20.480
[Guest]: You don't need to think about it.

01:04:20.480 --> 01:04:22.360
[Guest]: Again, back to truth with a capital T.

01:04:22.360 --> 01:04:31.880
[Guest]: If, however, and this is what I guess we're all banking on, if we allow the truths of

01:04:31.880 --> 01:04:38.940
[Guest]: our lived reality to trump that singular emphasis on truth with a capital T, we can read much

01:04:38.940 --> 01:04:41.880
[Guest]: more widely than we usually do.

01:04:41.880 --> 01:04:46.040
[Guest]: Now the best way, for instance, I always tell people, the best way to lose friends is to

01:04:46.040 --> 01:04:47.040
[Guest]: go to a film with them.

01:04:47.040 --> 01:04:50.560
[Guest]: And when they say, oh, I really loved it, you say, yes, but what about this that happened

01:04:50.560 --> 01:04:51.560
[Guest]: there?

01:04:51.560 --> 01:04:53.000
[Amit Varma]: I just went to get entertained.

01:04:53.000 --> 01:04:54.000
[Guest]: Are you that person?

01:04:54.000 --> 01:04:55.000
[Guest]: I am that person.

01:04:55.000 --> 01:04:57.400
[Guest]: But I still have lots of friends, thank God.

01:04:57.400 --> 01:05:01.720
[Guest]: But to me, that is what is reading, right?

01:05:01.720 --> 01:05:04.040
[Guest]: That we are always reading films.

01:05:04.040 --> 01:05:08.980
[Guest]: But what does it mean to oppose a reading that is not given to us, that we are coming

01:05:08.980 --> 01:05:13.880
[Guest]: up with, rather than just inheriting a misogynistic, heterosexist framework and say, but this is

01:05:13.880 --> 01:05:16.880
[Guest]: about love between a man and a woman.

01:05:16.880 --> 01:05:21.120
[Guest]: Which brings me back to something you said a little bit earlier before this question,

01:05:21.120 --> 01:05:23.760
[Guest]: which is that how do we know it's sexual desire?

01:05:23.760 --> 01:05:26.140
[Guest]: My answer to that very clearly is we don't.

01:05:26.140 --> 01:05:27.800
[Guest]: We have no idea.

01:05:27.800 --> 01:05:32.800
[Guest]: But then my question to you would be, how do we know what sexual desire is?

01:05:32.800 --> 01:05:36.120
[Guest]: Do we understand sexual desire as meaning genital intercourse?

01:05:36.120 --> 01:05:40.280
[Guest]: Clearly not, because there are lots of people who feel sexual desire for others who never

01:05:40.280 --> 01:05:42.480
[Guest]: have genital sex with them, right?

01:05:42.480 --> 01:05:44.480
[Guest]: So that's not what we mean.

01:05:44.480 --> 01:05:53.640
[Guest]: What we mean by sexual desire is a desire that wants some kind of physical consummation.

01:05:53.640 --> 01:05:54.640
[Guest]: What does that mean?

01:05:54.640 --> 01:05:59.040
[Guest]: Arm around the shoulder, pat on the back, holding hands, kissing, hugging, whatever

01:05:59.040 --> 01:06:03.000
[Guest]: it is, other than kissing, all these things these two men do, if that's the lens through

01:06:03.000 --> 01:06:05.320
[Guest]: which we're looking at.

01:06:05.320 --> 01:06:10.480
[Guest]: What we generally understand by sexual desire, in fact, is not shown in any Hindi cinema.

01:06:10.480 --> 01:06:16.240
[Guest]: You never see, at least in the 70s and 80s, you never ever saw men and women having sex.

01:06:16.240 --> 01:06:23.320
[Guest]: What you saw were tropes of desire, the flower falling, the shirt untucked, the door that

01:06:23.320 --> 01:06:29.200
[Guest]: is hastily slammed shut, the tie that is askew, the bindi that is rubbed off.

01:06:29.200 --> 01:06:30.200
[Guest]: All these are there.

01:06:30.200 --> 01:06:33.320
[Guest]: I mean, Rajesh Khanna is often looking disheveled.

01:06:33.320 --> 01:06:36.480
[Guest]: He's often looking sort of, you know, and Amitabh Bachchan is often looking deep into

01:06:36.480 --> 01:06:37.480
[Guest]: his eyes.

01:06:37.480 --> 01:06:44.040
[Guest]: We would normally understand that as a sign of sexual love.

01:06:44.040 --> 01:06:47.960
[Guest]: When these two men are looking into each other's eyes, why do we not read that as sexual love?

01:06:47.960 --> 01:06:52.120
[Guest]: It's a question for us, not a question for the film.

01:06:52.120 --> 01:06:56.480
[Amit Varma]: And as we go into a commercial break, I'll leave you with the reimagining of a film dialogue

01:06:56.480 --> 01:06:57.480
[Amit Varma]: inspired by Madhavi.

01:06:57.480 --> 01:06:59.800
[Amit Varma]: So if you don't like it, blame Madhavi.

01:06:59.800 --> 01:07:05.040
[Amit Varma]: This is that classic scene where Amitabh Bachchan asks Shashi Kapoor, mere paas ghar hai, gari

01:07:05.040 --> 01:07:09.000
[Amit Varma]: hai, ye hai, wo hai, tumhare paas kya hai, and Shashi Kapoor replies, mere paas condom

01:07:09.000 --> 01:07:10.000
[Amit Varma]: hai.

