01:08:27.000 --> 01:08:32.080
[Amit Varma]: We are chatting with Madhavi Menon about The Scene and The Unseen of Human Desire.

01:08:32.080 --> 01:08:36.760
[Amit Varma]: And you know, so before we went to the break, you were telling me about how Bollywood has

01:08:36.760 --> 01:08:41.640
[Amit Varma]: all these tropes to not show sex, for example, you know, whatever the two roses kissing and

01:08:41.640 --> 01:08:44.200
[Amit Varma]: the closed door and the bindi out of place.

01:08:44.200 --> 01:08:48.640
[Amit Varma]: And it struck me while reading your book, that our mythology has these as well, because

01:08:48.640 --> 01:08:51.960
[Amit Varma]: the gods are never actually shown reproducing.

01:08:51.960 --> 01:08:55.600
[Amit Varma]: And you know, one of the finest stories that you have outlined at length, and I shall ask

01:08:55.600 --> 01:09:00.880
[Amit Varma]: you to do so again, is the story of Ayyappa, you know, right from his origin story to everything

01:09:00.880 --> 01:09:05.760
[Amit Varma]: that happens with him, is mind blowing and is extremely relevant to our times as well,

01:09:05.760 --> 01:09:08.280
[Amit Varma]: because Ayyappa is the god at Sabarimala.

01:09:08.280 --> 01:09:09.640
[Amit Varma]: That's what the first is all about.

01:09:09.640 --> 01:09:10.640
[Amit Varma]: That's right.

01:09:10.640 --> 01:09:12.120
[Guest]: So take us through a bit of that.

01:09:12.120 --> 01:09:13.120
[Guest]: That's right.

01:09:13.120 --> 01:09:16.240
[Guest]: Amit, I see you're sort of hellbent on getting me into trouble, but that's okay.

01:09:16.240 --> 01:09:17.240
[Amit Varma]: We'll both get into trouble.

01:09:17.240 --> 01:09:18.240
[Amit Varma]: I'm used to that.

01:09:18.240 --> 01:09:20.920
[Amit Varma]: This podcast has gone on for more than an hour.

01:09:20.920 --> 01:09:22.600
[Amit Varma]: I do not think that, you know.

01:09:22.600 --> 01:09:23.600
[Amit Varma]: They would have got to this point.

01:09:23.600 --> 01:09:28.560
[Guest]: Exactly. Well, I've already gotten into trouble about this.

01:09:28.560 --> 01:09:33.640
[Guest]: I wrote an article on this in the Indian Express, and I had a police complaint filed against

01:09:33.640 --> 01:09:34.640
[Guest]: me.

01:09:34.640 --> 01:09:35.640
[Guest]: Are you serious?

01:09:35.640 --> 01:09:36.640
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:09:36.640 --> 01:09:37.640
[Guest]: Which luckily has not yet been converted into an FIR.

01:09:37.640 --> 01:09:39.920
[Guest]: So I'm just hoping it stays that way.

01:09:39.920 --> 01:09:46.000
[Guest]: And the complaint said, of course, I had outraged, hurt, insulted, one of those words, the sentiments

01:09:46.000 --> 01:09:50.440
[Guest]: of lakhs and lakhs of Hindus, which I actually found funny, because the person thought they

01:09:50.440 --> 01:09:56.520
[Guest]: were just lakhs of Hindus, rather than millions, or hundreds of millions, who are these lakhs

01:09:56.520 --> 01:09:57.520
[Amit Varma]: of Hindus?

01:09:57.520 --> 01:09:58.520
[Amit Varma]: You felt offended.

01:09:58.520 --> 01:10:00.360
[Amit Varma]: I have only offended so many people.

01:10:00.360 --> 01:10:02.040
[Guest]: I must be doing something wrong.

01:10:02.040 --> 01:10:03.040
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:10:03.040 --> 01:10:08.760
[Guest]: Let me go on Amit's show and rectify that, exactly, exactly.

01:10:08.760 --> 01:10:12.440
[Guest]: I mean, and also part of the problem, of course, is this classification of Hindus, which, you

01:10:12.440 --> 01:10:14.760
[Guest]: know, I don't need to talk about right now.

01:10:14.760 --> 01:10:18.360
[Guest]: But the story of Ayyappan is just fascinating.

01:10:18.360 --> 01:10:25.720
[Guest]: And as you just said, he is the presiding deity at this place of worship called Sabarimala

01:10:25.720 --> 01:10:28.440
[Guest]: in Kerala, and is the presiding deity.

01:10:28.440 --> 01:10:34.760
[Guest]: And I have known him all my life, because my maternal family, my mother's family, have

01:10:34.760 --> 01:10:37.040
[Guest]: been Ayyappan devotees for a long time.

01:10:37.040 --> 01:10:42.000
[Guest]: So my grandfather, my maternal grandfather, I don't know, made that pilgrimage over 30

01:10:42.000 --> 01:10:46.040
[Guest]: times to Sabarimala, and in fact, wanted to take us as well.

01:10:46.040 --> 01:10:50.120
[Guest]: And my sister and I were taken, went along with my father and grandfather, when I was

01:10:50.120 --> 01:10:51.120
[Guest]: eight years old.

01:10:51.120 --> 01:10:56.120
[Guest]: And I like sort of scandalizing people by saying, I am a woman who has been to Sabarimala,

01:10:56.120 --> 01:10:58.000
[Guest]: and I was bleeding when I went.

01:10:58.000 --> 01:11:01.280
[Guest]: But of course, the story is that a leech had attached itself to my foot, and so I was bleeding

01:11:01.280 --> 01:11:02.280
[Guest]: in that sense.

01:11:02.280 --> 01:11:03.280
[Amit Varma]: Non-sanskari leech.

01:11:03.280 --> 01:11:04.280
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:11:04.280 --> 01:11:09.720
[Guest]: And the lecherous leech.

01:11:09.720 --> 01:11:11.560
[Guest]: So I went when I was seven or eight years old.

01:11:11.560 --> 01:11:17.920
[Guest]: And so Ayyappan and the Sabarimala temple has been a part of my upbringing, I mean,

01:11:17.920 --> 01:11:20.680
[Guest]: part of everyday life.

01:11:20.680 --> 01:11:25.320
[Guest]: So it was fascinating to me, this entire court case that has, the way it's played out over

01:11:25.320 --> 01:11:30.560
[Guest]: the last two or three years, because I was very glad that someone had filed a case against

01:11:30.560 --> 01:11:31.560
[Guest]: it.

01:11:31.560 --> 01:11:36.700
[Guest]: I mean, I am not enough of a believer in pilgrimages to have been outraged by that.

01:11:36.700 --> 01:11:39.860
[Guest]: But there was something, I'm so glad that this happened, and I'm very glad the Supreme

01:11:39.860 --> 01:11:43.720
[Guest]: Court ruled the way it did, even though it seems to make no difference because the government

01:11:43.720 --> 01:11:48.960
[Guest]: is still not allowing women of menstruating age to enter through the front steps.

01:11:48.960 --> 01:11:55.400
[Guest]: So what I wrote about Ayyappan, the article that got me into trouble, is that the fundamental

01:11:55.400 --> 01:12:02.680
[Guest]: premise behind people who do not want women of menstruating age in the temple, the fundamental

01:12:02.680 --> 01:12:11.200
[Guest]: premise of those people are that Ayyappan is a celibate God, which is to say, and this

01:12:11.200 --> 01:12:16.560
[Guest]: is the fundamental assumption number two, that Ayyappan as a male God is going to be

01:12:16.560 --> 01:12:19.680
[Guest]: attracted to women.

01:12:19.680 --> 01:12:25.320
[Guest]: And menstruating women, because they are sexually active, will be the ones to tempt Ayyappan,

01:12:25.320 --> 01:12:26.880
[Guest]: the male celibate God.

01:12:26.880 --> 01:12:29.200
[Guest]: So you see the number of assumptions going on here.

01:12:29.200 --> 01:12:33.840
[Guest]: And this ties back to our earlier conversations, what we take to a conversation that we regard

01:12:33.840 --> 01:12:37.660
[Guest]: as normal are just assumptions we've never been told to think about.

01:12:37.660 --> 01:12:40.600
[Guest]: So the assumption of heterosexuality is just rampant here.

01:12:40.600 --> 01:12:44.720
[Guest]: Ayyappan, male God, should not see women because his celibacy should not be challenged.

01:12:44.720 --> 01:12:46.640
[Guest]: And such a weak God that we need to protect.

01:12:46.640 --> 01:12:47.640
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:12:47.640 --> 01:12:48.640
[Guest]: Who was it?

01:12:48.640 --> 01:12:51.960
[Guest]: Shashi Tharoor who said, there was a time when we thought the gods would protect us,

01:12:51.960 --> 01:12:55.520
[Guest]: and now we feel that we need to protect the gods.

01:12:55.520 --> 01:12:58.080
[Guest]: And so that's the fundamental premise.

01:12:58.080 --> 01:13:03.560
[Guest]: And what I find fascinating is that there is actually nothing in Ayyappan's mythological

01:13:03.560 --> 01:13:08.160
[Guest]: stories or histories to suggest heterosexuality in the least.

01:13:08.160 --> 01:13:11.280
[Guest]: Now, this is not to say he is or is not heterosexual.

01:13:11.280 --> 01:13:13.240
[Guest]: I'm actually not interested in that.

01:13:13.240 --> 01:13:17.280
[Guest]: But it is to say that if heterosexuality is the fundamental belief with which people are

01:13:17.280 --> 01:13:22.260
[Guest]: being monitored, can you show me where that belief is coming from?

01:13:22.260 --> 01:13:25.040
[Guest]: And so there are three stories about Ayyappan that we know.

01:13:25.040 --> 01:13:28.760
[Guest]: They're all mythological, of course, like all the stories of our gods are.

01:13:28.760 --> 01:13:29.760
[Guest]: But there are three stories.

01:13:29.760 --> 01:13:33.120
[Guest]: And as I said, none of them points in the direction of heterosexuality.

01:13:33.120 --> 01:13:38.560
[Guest]: The first, of course, an origin story is that Ayyappan is the son of two men.

01:13:38.560 --> 01:13:43.680
[Guest]: He's the son of Shiva and Vishnu, Vishnu in drag as Mohini.

01:13:43.680 --> 01:13:49.520
[Guest]: You know, as you know, Mohini is brought into being to defeat the demon so that the gods

01:13:49.520 --> 01:13:52.280
[Guest]: can churn the nectar and steal the nectar for themselves.

01:13:52.280 --> 01:13:57.160
[Guest]: I mean, what is wonderful about the pantheon of Hindu gods is that they're always up to

01:13:57.160 --> 01:14:00.760
[Guest]: no good, always up to mischief, always cheating, always doing this.

01:14:00.760 --> 01:14:01.760
[Amit Varma]: It's great.

01:14:01.760 --> 01:14:02.760
[Amit Varma]: Our gods are awesome.

01:14:02.760 --> 01:14:06.000
[Amit Varma]: Our gods are so much cooler than the people who follow them.

01:14:06.000 --> 01:14:07.000
[Guest]: Absolutely.

01:14:07.000 --> 01:14:08.000
[Guest]: Never a dull moment.

01:14:08.000 --> 01:14:09.000
[Guest]: Right.

01:14:09.000 --> 01:14:10.680
[Guest]: It's just all fun all the time.

01:14:10.680 --> 01:14:17.360
[Guest]: And so Shiva and Vishnu, Vishnu takes on the avatar of Mohini, destroys this demon called

01:14:17.360 --> 01:14:20.440
[Guest]: Tarakasura, who is actually threatening Shiva.

01:14:20.440 --> 01:14:25.880
[Guest]: Shiva is hidden in a tree trunk, Mohini does her charm, and then Mohini turns back into

01:14:25.880 --> 01:14:26.880
[Amit Varma]: Vishnu.

01:14:26.880 --> 01:14:30.200
[Amit Varma]: And I found even the origin story of the origin story very funny, the way you told it.

01:14:30.200 --> 01:14:31.200
[Unknown]: Exactly.

01:14:31.200 --> 01:14:34.640
[Amit Varma]: That this demon went to Shiva and said, kindly give me a boon, everything I turn should turn

01:14:34.640 --> 01:14:35.920
[Amit Varma]: to ash.

01:14:35.920 --> 01:14:39.120
[Amit Varma]: And Shiva is like chilling and all, he says, fine.

01:14:39.120 --> 01:14:40.720
[Amit Varma]: And then this guy starts chasing Shiva.

01:14:40.720 --> 01:14:41.720
[Amit Varma]: To touch him.

01:14:41.720 --> 01:14:42.720
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

01:14:42.720 --> 01:14:44.720
[Guest]: And Shiva goes up a tree and he tells Vishnu, come and help me.

01:14:44.720 --> 01:14:45.720
[Guest]: Please come and help me.

01:14:45.720 --> 01:14:50.000
[Guest]: So Vishnu comes as Mohini destroys Tarakasura by making him touch himself.

01:14:50.000 --> 01:14:51.000
[Guest]: So he turns to ash.

01:14:51.000 --> 01:14:55.040
[Guest]: And then Vishnu says, done and dusted, I'm back now as Vishnu.

01:14:55.040 --> 01:14:57.040
[Guest]: And Shiva comes out and says, thanks so much.

01:14:57.040 --> 01:15:03.660
[Guest]: But you know, I got a dim glimpse of you as Mohini and you were really sexy.

01:15:03.660 --> 01:15:06.560
[Guest]: So can you just sort of turn back into Mohini again?

01:15:06.560 --> 01:15:08.120
[Guest]: And so Vishnu says, sure, no problem.

01:15:08.120 --> 01:15:10.840
[Guest]: I actually love, I love all that stuff.

01:15:10.840 --> 01:15:13.600
[Guest]: Becomes Mohini and Shiva is so excited, he spills his semen, right?

01:15:13.600 --> 01:15:17.360
[Guest]: That's one of the secrets about our gods is that they never actually have genital intercourse.

01:15:17.360 --> 01:15:22.360
[Guest]: It's always the sun inseminated the rock or the river.

01:15:22.360 --> 01:15:23.360
[Guest]: Semen is spilt here.

01:15:23.360 --> 01:15:25.000
[Guest]: So it's always that kind of.

01:15:25.000 --> 01:15:28.880
[Guest]: So again, to go back to what counts as sexual desire, you know, it's a desire for a rock

01:15:28.880 --> 01:15:30.640
[Guest]: in many cases.

01:15:30.640 --> 01:15:35.360
[Guest]: Shiva spills his semen, off that comes the person who becomes Ayyappan, right?

01:15:35.360 --> 01:15:36.360
[Guest]: In different avatars.

01:15:36.360 --> 01:15:40.840
[Guest]: So Ayyappan is the son of Shiva and Vishnu in drag as Mohini.

01:15:40.840 --> 01:15:43.440
[Guest]: The son of two men.

01:15:43.440 --> 01:15:48.920
[Guest]: The second story we know about Ayyappan, for a fact, is that his best friend forever, his

01:15:48.920 --> 01:15:52.880
[Guest]: BFF, is a Muslim pirate called Babur.

01:15:52.880 --> 01:15:53.880
[Amit Varma]: And in fact.

01:15:53.880 --> 01:15:54.880
[Amit Varma]: Bengalis call Babur.

01:15:54.880 --> 01:16:00.040
[Amit Varma]: I'm half Bengali, so self-deprecating, kindly do not be offended if you are some Mukherjee

01:16:00.040 --> 01:16:01.120
[Amit Varma]: person listening to this.

01:16:01.120 --> 01:16:02.120
[Amit Varma]: I am also Bengali.

01:16:02.120 --> 01:16:03.120
[Guest]: Lakhs of Mukherjees.

01:16:03.120 --> 01:16:04.120
[Amit Varma]: Babur.

01:16:04.120 --> 01:16:05.120
[Amit Varma]: Lakhs and lakhs of Mukherjees.

01:16:05.120 --> 01:16:13.320
[Guest]: But anyway, so Babur, in fact, they are so close that the pilgrimage in Sabarimala, you

01:16:13.320 --> 01:16:18.880
[Guest]: have to start from the mosque of Babur, dedicated to Babur, and then go up to Sabarimala.

01:16:18.880 --> 01:16:24.440
[Guest]: So in fact, you cannot worship Ayyappan without worshipping Babur.

01:16:24.440 --> 01:16:28.360
[Guest]: And again, stories of how they got together, whether they fought together, all that is

01:16:28.360 --> 01:16:30.520
[Guest]: the multiple stories.

01:16:30.520 --> 01:16:36.040
[Guest]: But we do have a story in which Ayyappan tells his father, please treat Babur as you would

01:16:36.040 --> 01:16:37.560
[Guest]: treat me.

01:16:37.560 --> 01:16:42.560
[Guest]: And the sense of we are one, again talking about tropes of romance, is very much one

01:16:42.560 --> 01:16:44.600
[Guest]: between Ayyappan and Babur.

01:16:44.600 --> 01:16:50.760
[Guest]: And just as a slight sidebar, the worship of Babur being an absolute necessary prelude

01:16:50.760 --> 01:16:57.720
[Guest]: to a worship of Ayyappan just shows you what a syncretic, pluralistic monument Sabarimala

01:16:57.720 --> 01:16:58.720
[Guest]: is.

01:16:58.720 --> 01:17:03.680
[Guest]: It has also historically been one of the few temples in Kerala that has never had prohibitions

01:17:03.680 --> 01:17:08.400
[Guest]: on caste, which is why the prohibition on women makes so little sense, but I'll come

01:17:08.400 --> 01:17:09.400
[Guest]: back to that later.

01:17:09.400 --> 01:17:10.720
[Guest]: So that's the second story.

01:17:10.720 --> 01:17:12.480
[Guest]: His best friend is Babur.

01:17:12.480 --> 01:17:18.400
[Guest]: The third story now, perhaps most fascinating of all, is that Ayyappan says, build me this

01:17:18.400 --> 01:17:19.400
[Guest]: temple.

01:17:19.400 --> 01:17:22.760
[Guest]: Here is my statue, and I'm going to go up to heaven.

01:17:22.760 --> 01:17:27.680
[Guest]: Goes up to heaven, because he's the son of Shiva and Vishnu, he's the elite, right?

01:17:27.680 --> 01:17:32.360
[Guest]: His elite god, and is soon set to sort of take over control of the heaven.

01:17:32.360 --> 01:17:34.360
[Amit Varma]: He's Lutyens' elite in heaven.

01:17:34.360 --> 01:17:37.120
[Unknown]: Lots of real estate, right?

01:17:37.120 --> 01:17:41.700
[Guest]: And so he's set over to take over the heavens, and he has one grand plan.

01:17:41.700 --> 01:17:48.040
[Guest]: He said, my grand plan is, I want to abolish both birth and death.

01:17:48.040 --> 01:17:52.900
[Guest]: Because if we don't die, then we won't need to give birth to more people, because we give

01:17:52.900 --> 01:17:56.000
[Guest]: birth to children, because we fear we will die, and then we want someone to continue

01:17:56.000 --> 01:17:57.000
[Guest]: after us.

01:17:57.000 --> 01:17:59.880
[Guest]: But if we're not going to die, why bother giving birth to children?

01:17:59.880 --> 01:18:02.740
[Guest]: We can just enjoy ourselves throughout our life.

01:18:02.740 --> 01:18:06.120
[Guest]: So he sort of starts thinking about, how can I execute this plan?

01:18:06.120 --> 01:18:10.680
[Guest]: And the other gods start getting worried, because they know that most of the offerings

01:18:10.680 --> 01:18:14.240
[Guest]: that come to them come because people don't want to die, and because people want to give

01:18:14.240 --> 01:18:15.240
[Guest]: birth.

01:18:15.240 --> 01:18:19.860
[Guest]: And they said, if we abolish birth and death, what the hell is going to happen to our revenues?

01:18:19.860 --> 01:18:25.640
[Guest]: So they send Narada to Ayyappan and says, please, get him to change his mind, distract

01:18:25.640 --> 01:18:29.400
[Guest]: him, take him away from this idea, it's a bad idea.

01:18:29.400 --> 01:18:33.400
[Guest]: So Narada goes to Ayyappan and says, excuse me, can I have a minute with you?

01:18:33.400 --> 01:18:36.660
[Guest]: And Ayyappan says, you know, I'm really busy right now, I'm coming up with this plan of

01:18:36.660 --> 01:18:41.120
[Guest]: abolishing birth and death, you know, it'll take me a few months, maybe after that you

01:18:41.120 --> 01:18:44.360
[Guest]: and I can chat, coffee sometime, right?

01:18:44.360 --> 01:18:47.240
[Guest]: And Narada says, no, no, no, it'll just take two minutes right now, please, please, please.

01:18:47.240 --> 01:18:52.120
[Guest]: So Ayyappan, being a nice, kind-hearted guy says, okay, sets aside his blueprints and

01:18:52.120 --> 01:18:53.800
[Guest]: said, okay, what is it?

01:18:53.800 --> 01:18:57.840
[Guest]: So Narada says, I have just one question for you, Ayyappan said, okay, what?

01:18:57.840 --> 01:19:06.600
[Guest]: He says, can you tell me how you are related to your father's wife and your mother's wife?

01:19:06.600 --> 01:19:12.920
[Guest]: And legend has it that Ayyappan was so perplexed by that question, that he in fact came back

01:19:12.920 --> 01:19:17.800
[Guest]: down to earth into his temple at Sabarimala, where he continues to this day, because he

01:19:17.800 --> 01:19:21.960
[Guest]: has still not found an answer to that question, right?

01:19:21.960 --> 01:19:27.480
[Guest]: If you think about it for a second, right, father's wife, Parvati, okay, you can say

01:19:27.480 --> 01:19:33.520
[Guest]: she's my stepmother, she's my father's wife, but not my mother, this, that, and the other.

01:19:33.520 --> 01:19:39.040
[Guest]: Vishnu's wife, first of all, is Vishnu my mother or is Mohini my mother?

01:19:39.040 --> 01:19:42.360
[Guest]: Is Vishnu my mother in drag as a man?

01:19:42.360 --> 01:19:44.920
[Guest]: So is my mother really a father?

01:19:44.920 --> 01:19:48.440
[Guest]: And then is my father's wife or consort Lakshmi, what is she?

01:19:48.440 --> 01:19:51.080
[Guest]: Is she the wife of my mother or my father?

01:19:51.080 --> 01:19:53.120
[Amit Varma]: He's still trying to work out those permutations.

01:19:53.120 --> 01:19:54.120
[Amit Varma]: Or is the rock my mother?

01:19:54.120 --> 01:19:58.280
[Guest]: Is the rock my mother or the tree trunk or whatever, right?

01:19:58.280 --> 01:20:06.360
[Guest]: And so the idea of sexual indeterminacy is written into the very legend of Ayyappan at

01:20:06.360 --> 01:20:09.120
[Guest]: every level that we know about him.

01:20:09.120 --> 01:20:13.540
[Guest]: So to presume that this man, son of two men, deeply enmeshed with another man, wanting

01:20:13.540 --> 01:20:17.560
[Guest]: to abolish birth and death, should be the presider of heterosexuality.

01:20:17.560 --> 01:20:21.200
[Guest]: It's like, where is this coming from?

01:20:21.200 --> 01:20:27.200
[Guest]: And it is coming, of course, as I dared to answer, from us.

01:20:27.200 --> 01:20:34.400
[Guest]: That answer of Ayyappan is a male heterosexual God who is celibate is coming from male Brahminical

01:20:34.400 --> 01:20:37.080
[Guest]: priests at Sabarimala.

01:20:37.080 --> 01:20:42.360
[Guest]: And you know, in any court of law anywhere in the world, your first question in a criminal

01:20:42.360 --> 01:20:45.040
[Guest]: case is who stands to gain?

01:20:45.040 --> 01:20:50.080
[Guest]: The only people who stand to gain here are the male priests and what they think of as

01:20:50.080 --> 01:20:51.080
[Guest]: their tradition.

01:20:51.080 --> 01:20:54.880
[Amit Varma]: In fact, it could be argued that they have literally imprisoned their God.

01:20:54.880 --> 01:20:55.880
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:20:55.880 --> 01:21:01.160
[Guest]: Whereas the traditions as we know it in relation to Ayyappan all set him free, which is why

01:21:01.160 --> 01:21:06.720
[Guest]: Sabarimala is usually such a wonderfully open, syncretic place.

01:21:06.720 --> 01:21:09.860
[Guest]: No barrier on caste, no barrier on religion.

01:21:09.860 --> 01:21:12.340
[Guest]: The only barrier is misogynistic.

01:21:12.340 --> 01:21:13.840
[Guest]: And I just find that shocking.

01:21:13.840 --> 01:21:15.400
[Amit Varma]: Indeed.

01:21:15.400 --> 01:21:20.800
[Amit Varma]: And while talking about Ayyappan and Vavar, you spoke about how Ayyappan went to his dad

01:21:20.800 --> 01:21:25.760
[Amit Varma]: and said that, you know, my BFF Vavar or whatever, treat us as one.

01:21:25.760 --> 01:21:29.200
[Amit Varma]: And you know, you have a very interesting chapter in your book, and this is actually

01:21:29.200 --> 01:21:36.720
[Amit Varma]: chapter 1.5 called Fractions, where you sort of militate against this notion of two people

01:21:36.720 --> 01:21:38.720
[Amit Varma]: being treated as one.

01:21:38.720 --> 01:21:43.880
[Amit Varma]: And you know, you refer back to Aristophanes, who is asked to, you know, sort of talk about

01:21:43.880 --> 01:21:44.880
[Amit Varma]: desire.

01:21:44.880 --> 01:21:48.720
[Amit Varma]: And Aristophanes said that, you know, man and woman was once joined and they were separated.

01:21:48.720 --> 01:21:52.360
[Amit Varma]: So now the two are trying to become one again, which is that whole romantic notion.

01:21:52.360 --> 01:21:55.400
[Amit Varma]: But you point out that all desire isn't like that.

01:21:55.400 --> 01:21:59.160
[Amit Varma]: You know, and in fact, I often, you know, these days, people are talking about the uniform

01:21:59.160 --> 01:22:02.600
[Amit Varma]: civil code coming into action at some point in time and whatever.

01:22:02.600 --> 01:22:06.400
[Amit Varma]: And I have always thought that in a utopian world, you would not have a civil code at

01:22:06.400 --> 01:22:07.400
[Amit Varma]: all.

01:22:07.400 --> 01:22:11.360
[Amit Varma]: You would have individuals freely associating with themselves in whatever way, drawing up

01:22:11.360 --> 01:22:15.280
[Amit Varma]: their own marriage deeds, if they so desire, without the state being involved.

01:22:15.280 --> 01:22:16.280
[Amit Varma]: And why just two individuals?

01:22:16.280 --> 01:22:20.240
[Amit Varma]: It could be three individuals or four individuals, you know, voluntary exchange.

01:22:20.240 --> 01:22:21.240
[Guest]: Right.

01:22:21.240 --> 01:22:22.240
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:22:22.240 --> 01:22:29.000
[Guest]: The one thing that I would add to your recounting of my Greek story from Plato, Aristophanes's

01:22:29.000 --> 01:22:32.880
[Guest]: idea is that we were all double once.

01:22:32.880 --> 01:22:36.320
[Guest]: And it was not only men and women who were joined, men and women were only one third

01:22:36.320 --> 01:22:38.000
[Guest]: of those who were joined.

01:22:38.000 --> 01:22:41.720
[Guest]: Another category were men and men, another category were women and women.

01:22:41.720 --> 01:22:47.320
[Guest]: And so, and these human beings, doubled human beings became so strong that the gods became

01:22:47.320 --> 01:22:48.320
[Guest]: jealous.

01:22:48.320 --> 01:22:49.320
[Guest]: Right.

01:22:49.320 --> 01:22:51.960
[Guest]: Greek gods are also quite as fascinating as our gods because they're also up to machinations

01:22:51.960 --> 01:22:53.440
[Guest]: all the time.

01:22:53.440 --> 01:22:55.920
[Guest]: And the gods say, let's divide them and half their power.

01:22:55.920 --> 01:22:57.800
[Guest]: So everyone gets divided.

01:22:57.800 --> 01:23:01.120
[Guest]: And so according to this myth, that is why we keep saying we're searching for our other

01:23:01.120 --> 01:23:05.600
[Guest]: half because we once used to be double and we've been divided.

01:23:05.600 --> 01:23:10.800
[Guest]: But that still sticks, as I point out with this idea of whole numbers and has given rise

01:23:10.800 --> 01:23:14.280
[Guest]: to this entire thing of one plus one equals one.

01:23:14.280 --> 01:23:15.280
[Guest]: Right.

01:23:15.280 --> 01:23:18.920
[Guest]: I and my lover come together and we are one because we're actually half and half that

01:23:18.920 --> 01:23:23.440
[Guest]: come together as one, two becomes one and one plus one becomes one.

01:23:23.440 --> 01:23:26.120
[Guest]: This is the mathematics of love, if you will have it.

01:23:26.120 --> 01:23:27.120
[Guest]: Right.

01:23:27.120 --> 01:23:28.120
[Guest]: So I've always been interested.

01:23:28.120 --> 01:23:31.440
[Guest]: Remember I said at the very beginning, I'm interested in things that people don't like

01:23:31.440 --> 01:23:32.960
[Guest]: to think about.

01:23:32.960 --> 01:23:37.880
[Guest]: We like to think about whole numbers, but what about the things between these two numbers?

01:23:37.880 --> 01:23:40.280
[Guest]: And so I was always fascinated.

01:23:40.280 --> 01:23:46.680
[Guest]: If one plus one equals one, what about one plus half or half plus three quarters?

01:23:46.680 --> 01:23:47.680
[Guest]: Right.

01:23:47.680 --> 01:23:52.720
[Guest]: If we had to measure our mathematical investment in our partners, it probably won't be whole.

01:23:52.720 --> 01:23:55.520
[Guest]: You're thinking about 55 other things, about 65 other people.

01:23:55.520 --> 01:23:56.520
[Guest]: Right.

01:23:56.520 --> 01:23:58.320
[Guest]: So if we're doing this mathematically, what is it?

01:23:58.320 --> 01:24:01.160
[Guest]: How much is it that we are in this relationship?

01:24:01.160 --> 01:24:08.360
[Guest]: So when this film going back to Bollywood came out, it just fascinated me because here

01:24:08.360 --> 01:24:13.520
[Guest]: is a film that is actually talking about ishq in relation, not to whole numbers, but to

01:24:13.520 --> 01:24:15.600
[Guest]: a fraction.

01:24:15.600 --> 01:24:20.840
[Guest]: And this is how I say Bollywood can really be brilliant without necessarily saying here

01:24:20.840 --> 01:24:22.200
[Guest]: is a gay character.

01:24:22.200 --> 01:24:23.200
[Guest]: Right.

01:24:23.200 --> 01:24:25.240
[Guest]: And, you know, this is going to be a spoiler alert.

01:24:25.240 --> 01:24:29.200
[Guest]: Anyone who has not seen it, please fast forward the next five minutes.

01:24:29.200 --> 01:24:32.960
[Amit Varma]: But even if you give a spoiler, we have agreed it's the journey and not the destination.

01:24:32.960 --> 01:24:33.960
[Guest]: There you go.

01:24:33.960 --> 01:24:34.960
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:24:34.960 --> 01:24:44.120
[Guest]: So the the point of Dehdish Kiya is that these two women are lovers, but we don't know that

01:24:44.120 --> 01:24:48.840
[Guest]: in the film at all because the two women also have two men, Nasruddin Shah and Arshad Warsi.

01:24:48.840 --> 01:24:53.360
[Guest]: The women are Madhuri Dixit and Richa Chadda.

01:24:53.360 --> 01:24:59.640
[Guest]: We always are pairing up these two, man, woman, man, woman, and completely blind to the possibility

01:24:59.640 --> 01:25:02.400
[Guest]: that it might be the two women together.

01:25:02.400 --> 01:25:06.400
[Guest]: And so the joke is on us at the end of the film when we finally realize, oh, my God,

01:25:06.400 --> 01:25:08.280
[Guest]: it's the two women who are together.

01:25:08.280 --> 01:25:13.040
[Guest]: Because what that shows us is that to go back to our earlier conversation, we have been

01:25:13.040 --> 01:25:19.000
[Guest]: looking from a perspective that seems so commonplace, that seems so right that we don't think about

01:25:19.000 --> 01:25:20.000
[Amit Varma]: it.

01:25:20.000 --> 01:25:23.280
[Guest]: So the revelation in the film is not about the characters, it's about the viewers.

01:25:23.280 --> 01:25:24.280
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:25:24.280 --> 01:25:29.800
[Guest]: And, you know, this film is based on an Ismat Chugtai short story called Lihav, The Quilt,

01:25:29.800 --> 01:25:31.760
[Guest]: which, as you know, is famous now.

01:25:31.760 --> 01:25:37.880
[Guest]: But my favorite story about Lihav is that Chugtai had a case filed against her.

01:25:37.880 --> 01:25:42.880
[Guest]: Mantu had a case filed against him similarly, I think, for a Kali Shalwar or something of

01:25:42.880 --> 01:25:43.960
[Guest]: the kind.

01:25:43.960 --> 01:25:47.680
[Guest]: They both traveled to Lahore together in 1942 to appear before the court.

01:25:47.680 --> 01:25:51.320
[Guest]: And it's still the British High Court, Lahore High Court.

01:25:51.320 --> 01:25:55.840
[Guest]: And the charge is obscenity against Lihav.

01:25:55.840 --> 01:26:02.640
[Guest]: And Ismat Chugtai's lawyer gets her off because he asks every witness for the prosecution,

01:26:02.640 --> 01:26:06.400
[Guest]: OK, you have alleged that this is an obscene story.

01:26:06.400 --> 01:26:10.680
[Guest]: Can you point to a single word in the story that's obscene?

01:26:10.680 --> 01:26:12.640
[Guest]: And none of the witnesses could do that.

01:26:12.640 --> 01:26:15.880
[Guest]: And so the judge said, well, if you can't point to a single word that's obscene, let's

01:26:15.880 --> 01:26:17.400
[Guest]: get rid of this.

01:26:17.400 --> 01:26:23.040
[Guest]: And that, to me, is the beauty of this tale, because there is no word like gay, lesbian,

01:26:23.040 --> 01:26:25.200
[Guest]: sex, nothing.

01:26:25.200 --> 01:26:29.440
[Guest]: Yet here is the canonical love story between two women in our culture.

01:26:29.440 --> 01:26:31.040
[Amit Varma]: And it's a masterpiece of subtlety.

01:26:31.040 --> 01:26:34.480
[Amit Varma]: Can you tell our listeners, you know, briefly what it's about?

01:26:34.480 --> 01:26:36.280
[Guest]: I mean, it is stunning.

01:26:36.280 --> 01:26:43.640
[Guest]: It is about this woman, Begum Jaan, and her maid, Rabbu, which is exactly the template

01:26:43.640 --> 01:26:45.840
[Guest]: that's recreated in Dedesh Kiya.

01:26:45.840 --> 01:26:50.960
[Guest]: Begum Jaan is married to a man who we would now call a gay man, who is interested only

01:26:50.960 --> 01:26:53.680
[Guest]: in young men and sort of spent all his money on them.

01:26:53.680 --> 01:26:57.800
[Guest]: The assumption is that they never had sex, never consummate their relationship.

01:26:57.800 --> 01:27:02.640
[Guest]: And the story goes on about how Begum Jaan is wilting with each passing day.

01:27:02.640 --> 01:27:09.280
[Guest]: And she develops what the story evocatively and brilliantly calls an itch.

01:27:09.280 --> 01:27:13.680
[Guest]: So she develops an itch and she's scratching herself all the time, called the doctors and

01:27:13.680 --> 01:27:16.200
[Guest]: the doctors say, there's nothing wrong with you.

01:27:16.200 --> 01:27:18.520
[Guest]: We don't know where this itch is coming from.

01:27:18.520 --> 01:27:19.520
[Guest]: But she's in agony.

01:27:19.520 --> 01:27:20.520
[Guest]: She's in pain.

01:27:20.520 --> 01:27:25.000
[Guest]: She's in distress until the maid, Rabbu, comes and says, I can give you a massage.

01:27:25.000 --> 01:27:28.020
[Guest]: I can press you in a way that the itch will disappear.

01:27:28.020 --> 01:27:32.200
[Guest]: And the story is narrated about how Rabbu's massages cure the Begum entirely.

01:27:32.200 --> 01:27:35.480
[Guest]: And she blossoms and glows and looks delighted.

01:27:35.480 --> 01:27:40.600
[Guest]: Now this entire story is being told from the vantage point of a 10-year-old girl who is

01:27:40.600 --> 01:27:42.600
[Guest]: Begum Jaan's niece.

01:27:42.600 --> 01:27:44.880
[Guest]: And so she says, what is all this massaging going on?

01:27:44.880 --> 01:27:48.300
[Guest]: I don't understand it, but Begum Jaan seems to love it.

01:27:48.300 --> 01:27:52.600
[Guest]: And the story is about how she's sleeping in Begum Jaan's room at night in a cot like

01:27:52.600 --> 01:27:55.400
[Guest]: we all do, you know, relative sleep in the same room.

01:27:55.400 --> 01:28:01.220
[Guest]: But Rabbu is also in the same bed giving Begum Jaan a massage and how the little child wakes

01:28:01.220 --> 01:28:08.120
[Guest]: up in the middle of the night and sees the lihaaf, the razae, the quilt, rising and falling

01:28:08.120 --> 01:28:12.880
[Guest]: in interesting shapes because of the activity going on underneath it.

01:28:12.880 --> 01:28:16.280
[Guest]: And till the end of the story, she has no idea what's going on.

01:28:16.280 --> 01:28:17.600
[Guest]: So what are you going to say?

01:28:17.600 --> 01:28:21.960
[Guest]: Razae is obscene, lihaaf is obscene, itch is obscene.

01:28:21.960 --> 01:28:23.100
[Guest]: What do you say?

01:28:23.100 --> 01:28:30.240
[Guest]: But you put all these together and you have a clear story about the lack of sexual satisfaction

01:28:30.240 --> 01:28:32.840
[Guest]: and then the consummation of sexual desire.

01:28:32.840 --> 01:28:37.760
[Guest]: And so Chukta's brilliance, and the lawyer's brilliance actually, is to say, what do you

01:28:37.760 --> 01:28:41.600
[Guest]: think of as obscene cannot always be named?

01:28:41.600 --> 01:28:45.720
[Guest]: Which takes us back to that entire conversation about identity politics and categories of

01:28:45.720 --> 01:28:46.720
[Guest]: naming.

01:28:46.720 --> 01:28:47.720
[Guest]: Right?

01:28:47.720 --> 01:28:50.280
[Guest]: What do you lose when you name and what do you gain without a name?

01:28:50.280 --> 01:28:54.040
[Amit Varma]: And just thinking about what seems beautiful about the story is that it also seems to illustrate

01:28:54.040 --> 01:28:57.240
[Amit Varma]: what Marshall McLuhan said about the medium being the message.

01:28:57.240 --> 01:29:01.080
[Amit Varma]: Because what is so beautiful about the story is not just what happens, but the way it is

01:29:01.080 --> 01:29:02.080
[Amit Varma]: told.

01:29:02.080 --> 01:29:03.080
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

01:29:03.080 --> 01:29:07.160
[Amit Varma]: And that interplay with the viewer where, you know, you get everything and yet don't

01:29:07.160 --> 01:29:08.160
[Amit Varma]: get anything.

01:29:08.160 --> 01:29:09.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, exactly.

01:29:09.160 --> 01:29:10.160
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely.

01:29:10.160 --> 01:29:11.160
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely.

01:29:11.160 --> 01:29:15.280
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, and you would have more Danish gear, I'll quickly sort of quote these words

01:29:15.280 --> 01:29:20.340
[Amit Varma]: from your book, which sort of make it explicit what you just said, quote, the film is operating

01:29:20.340 --> 01:29:24.200
[Amit Varma]: on three basic principles of desire that affect us all.

01:29:24.200 --> 01:29:28.560
[Amit Varma]: First, it shows how easy it is to see heterosexual couples everywhere.

01:29:28.560 --> 01:29:34.160
[Amit Varma]: Second, it shows us that non-coupled, non-normative desires are everywhere around us, even if

01:29:34.160 --> 01:29:36.160
[Amit Varma]: we don't know how to see them.

01:29:36.160 --> 01:29:41.600
[Amit Varma]: The third principle with which the film works, there is always more and less to desire than

01:29:41.600 --> 01:29:43.560
[Amit Varma]: meets the eye, stop quote.

01:29:43.560 --> 01:29:44.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:29:44.560 --> 01:29:45.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:29:45.560 --> 01:29:49.600
[Amit Varma]: I was also sort of, and I wonder when you say that, you know, the second principle,

01:29:49.600 --> 01:29:53.760
[Amit Varma]: that it shows us that non-coupled, non-normative desires are everywhere around us, even if

01:29:53.760 --> 01:29:55.760
[Amit Varma]: we don't know how to see them.

01:29:55.760 --> 01:29:59.960
[Amit Varma]: Would it also then hold that even when we don't know how to see them in us?

01:29:59.960 --> 01:30:00.960
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:30:00.960 --> 01:30:01.960
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:30:01.960 --> 01:30:07.120
[Guest]: So if we stick with the first part right now, you know, there's a park outside the studio

01:30:07.120 --> 01:30:11.280
[Guest]: with benches and in Delhi, winter sun, of course, there are always people sitting there.

01:30:11.280 --> 01:30:17.960
[Guest]: And I have a fantastic photo that I took of three men on that bench, watching something

01:30:17.960 --> 01:30:19.880
[Guest]: on a phone, one of the guy's phone.

01:30:19.880 --> 01:30:20.880
[Guest]: Definitely TikTok.

01:30:20.880 --> 01:30:21.880
[Guest]: Oh really?

01:30:21.880 --> 01:30:26.560
[Guest]: And they are completely intertwined, like arms around each other.

01:30:26.560 --> 01:30:31.080
[Guest]: One guy's leg is over the other guy's thigh, completely immersed in this video, which could

01:30:31.080 --> 01:30:32.720
[Guest]: well have been of a woman dancing.

01:30:32.720 --> 01:30:33.720
[Guest]: I don't know.

01:30:33.720 --> 01:30:40.080
[Guest]: But their body language, any other so-called developed country in the world that outlaws

01:30:40.080 --> 01:30:43.500
[Guest]: homosexuality, they'd be arrested right there on the spot.

01:30:43.500 --> 01:30:48.360
[Guest]: So for me, yes, we don't know how to see, and we don't know what it is that we're seeing,

01:30:48.360 --> 01:30:53.400
[Guest]: because they might be perfectly heterosexual, or they might be perfectly homosexual, or

01:30:53.400 --> 01:30:54.900
[Guest]: they might be a bit of both.

01:30:54.900 --> 01:31:00.400
[Guest]: We don't know what we're seeing, but imposing normativity on everything that we see, which

01:31:00.400 --> 01:31:02.680
[Guest]: is exactly what we do with ourselves.

01:31:02.680 --> 01:31:09.360
[Guest]: So I was asked last week, I was in Trivandrum for the Lit Fest there, and I was asked, what

01:31:09.360 --> 01:31:12.640
[Guest]: do we do when we go into rural areas?

01:31:12.640 --> 01:31:16.480
[Guest]: And this was by an activist, extremely well-meaning, lovely guy.

01:31:16.480 --> 01:31:21.160
[Guest]: He said, what do we do when we go into rural areas and people don't want to identify themselves

01:31:21.160 --> 01:31:22.160
[Guest]: as gay?

01:31:22.160 --> 01:31:25.440
[Guest]: Isn't that a setback to the gay movement, and this, that, and the other?

01:31:25.440 --> 01:31:30.520
[Guest]: And I said very clearly, millions of people in India do not even know the word gay.

01:31:30.520 --> 01:31:34.720
[Guest]: There are men who have sex with men who have no idea what homosexuality is, and that's

01:31:34.720 --> 01:31:40.280
[Guest]: exactly as it should be, because the whole force of a queer politics is that we don't

01:31:40.280 --> 01:31:45.320
[Guest]: always have to name everything, that there are things that elude naming.

01:31:45.320 --> 01:31:50.080
[Guest]: So I could be a woman who thinks of myself as heterosexual, who is married to a man,

01:31:50.080 --> 01:31:53.160
[Guest]: but who might suddenly have a desire for a woman, right?

01:31:53.160 --> 01:31:58.560
[Guest]: This was the big scandal of Deepa Mehta's fire, like how are these two women, heterosexual

01:31:58.560 --> 01:32:02.380
[Guest]: women, married to two men, suddenly coming together?

01:32:02.380 --> 01:32:09.340
[Guest]: So we don't know where desire will emerge from within us, let alone within others.

01:32:09.340 --> 01:32:14.920
[Guest]: And so if we name ourselves X, we are going to be bound by it in a way that I don't think

01:32:14.920 --> 01:32:21.440
[Guest]: is necessarily healthy or desirable, that we have to be able to say, the name is not

01:32:21.440 --> 01:32:26.960
[Guest]: me, that there are desires here that I can't name, that escape naming, and that's what

01:32:26.960 --> 01:32:28.760
[Amit Varma]: makes them so sexy.

01:32:28.760 --> 01:32:32.760
[Amit Varma]: Which is also hard at a human level, because I think how we make sense of the world is

01:32:32.760 --> 01:32:37.920
[Amit Varma]: by simplifying it with narratives and taxonomies and actually naming things and putting them

01:32:37.920 --> 01:32:41.440
[Amit Varma]: into categories or pigeonholes, as it were.

01:32:41.440 --> 01:32:46.800
[Amit Varma]: So it seems that that is also hard to pull off, especially when the culture is sort of

01:32:46.800 --> 01:32:47.800
[Amit Varma]: like that.

01:32:47.800 --> 01:32:51.880
[Amit Varma]: One of the other revelations of the book, which I should have known, but I didn't know,

01:32:51.880 --> 01:32:59.000
[Amit Varma]: is Shakuntala Devi's history, and everyone thinks of her as, you know, a genius mathematician.

01:32:59.000 --> 01:33:04.320
[Amit Varma]: But at the same age that, in the same year that she pulled off one of her great mathematical

01:33:04.320 --> 01:33:09.200
[Unknown]: feats, which I have already forgotten, she published a book called The World of Homosexuals.

01:33:09.200 --> 01:33:13.960
[Amit Varma]: And she was, of course, married and later divorced to a homosexual, but she responded

01:33:13.960 --> 01:33:18.220
[Amit Varma]: to this with, not with anger, but empathy, and wrote this book in which she said the

01:33:18.220 --> 01:33:23.040
[Amit Varma]: following words, quote, heterosexual society dictates to the world how people should live

01:33:23.040 --> 01:33:24.920
[Amit Varma]: and what they should do.

01:33:24.920 --> 01:33:27.760
[Amit Varma]: Heterosexual society is based mostly on authoritarianism.

01:33:27.760 --> 01:33:32.720
[Amit Varma]: The authoritarians are judges, priests and professors, and their weapons of control are

01:33:32.720 --> 01:33:37.040
[Amit Varma]: guilt, justice, punishment, and fear, stop quote.

01:33:37.040 --> 01:33:38.040
[Amit Varma]: Strong words.

01:33:38.040 --> 01:33:39.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:33:39.040 --> 01:33:40.040
[Guest]: Which kind of, yeah.

01:33:40.040 --> 01:33:41.040
[Unknown]: And this was 1977.

01:33:41.040 --> 01:33:42.040
[Unknown]: That's right.

01:33:42.040 --> 01:33:43.040
[Amit Varma]: Pretty freaky.

01:33:43.040 --> 01:33:44.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:33:44.040 --> 01:33:45.040
[Guest]: So the next sort of question is something.

01:33:45.040 --> 01:33:47.040
[Amit Varma]: Can I just sort of address something you just said?

01:33:47.040 --> 01:33:48.040
[Amit Varma]: Sure, sure.

01:33:48.040 --> 01:33:53.200
[Guest]: When you said that human life, you know, we want to simplify it, we want to have taxonomies

01:33:53.200 --> 01:33:54.480
[Guest]: and categories.

01:33:54.480 --> 01:33:55.600
[Guest]: And you're absolutely right.

01:33:55.600 --> 01:33:56.960
[Guest]: We always do.

01:33:56.960 --> 01:34:02.720
[Guest]: The reason I'm fascinated by desire rather than, let's say, zoology, which is also very

01:34:02.720 --> 01:34:11.200
[Guest]: taxonomic and very categorical, is that desire has always, for as long as we've known, across

01:34:11.200 --> 01:34:15.000
[Guest]: cultures, always defied taxonomy.

01:34:15.000 --> 01:34:22.960
[Guest]: So what is it about this thing, this multi-leveled, multi-headed hydra that we have been trying

01:34:22.960 --> 01:34:26.520
[Guest]: to tame for centuries and have not managed to tame?

01:34:26.520 --> 01:34:31.000
[Guest]: That's why I think it continues to provide such rich material for thought and conversation

01:34:31.000 --> 01:34:35.320
[Guest]: and scholarship is actually, for instance, if you think about laws, the number of laws

01:34:35.320 --> 01:34:41.000
[Guest]: that are in place to try and police desire, what is this thing that is so scary?

01:34:41.000 --> 01:34:42.680
[Guest]: And why does it resist taxonomy?

01:34:42.680 --> 01:34:49.160
[Guest]: So I just want to sort of say, in that sense, desire is more resistant to taxonomy than

01:34:49.160 --> 01:34:51.020
[Guest]: we would like to think it is.

01:34:51.020 --> 01:34:56.000
[Guest]: And that's what makes it fascinating, which is also why it's sad when we think that our

01:34:56.000 --> 01:35:02.200
[Guest]: liberation lies in taxonomizing it, that our liberation lies in coming up with more and

01:35:02.200 --> 01:35:10.600
[Guest]: more names to describe what we are, rather than allowing namelessness or un-namability

01:35:10.600 --> 01:35:13.040
[Amit Varma]: to be one of those possibilities.

01:35:13.040 --> 01:35:14.440
[Amit Varma]: That's a very profound insight.

01:35:14.440 --> 01:35:18.280
[Amit Varma]: And just going back to zoology, it strikes me that if you look at a cow, a cow being

01:35:18.280 --> 01:35:23.800
[Amit Varma]: a cow doesn't depend on how you look at it, it doesn't depend on how a cow looks at itself,

01:35:23.800 --> 01:35:26.500
[Amit Varma]: and it doesn't depend on what the law says it is.

01:35:26.500 --> 01:35:31.400
[Amit Varma]: But all of these different factors affect any kind of desire, obviously.

01:35:31.400 --> 01:35:37.620
[Amit Varma]: And it also strikes me since you brought laws up, I think one of the issues that confuses

01:35:37.620 --> 01:35:43.080
[Amit Varma]: a lot of people is that we tend to conflate legality with morality, and that shapes and

01:35:43.080 --> 01:35:44.080
[Amit Varma]: changes society.

01:35:44.080 --> 01:35:48.720
[Amit Varma]: So you can have, as the British did when they came in with the IPC, that you can have a

01:35:48.720 --> 01:35:54.680
[Amit Varma]: codification of laws that is imposed from top down, and which hasn't come up organically,

01:35:54.680 --> 01:35:59.120
[Amit Varma]: and yet it changes society because, you know, the coercive nature of the power of the state

01:35:59.120 --> 01:36:01.120
[Amit Varma]: is going to impose a lot of that.

01:36:01.120 --> 01:36:05.800
[Guest]: I mean, to give you one example, Amit, well, I mean, there are actually two, but let me

01:36:05.800 --> 01:36:11.680
[Guest]: give you one example, 377, right, the judgment about 377, which, let me just say upfront

01:36:11.680 --> 01:36:12.960
[Guest]: is wonderful.

01:36:12.960 --> 01:36:15.360
[Guest]: I'm really glad it happened.

01:36:15.360 --> 01:36:16.520
[Guest]: It was long overdue.

01:36:16.520 --> 01:36:21.680
[Guest]: And I'm just relieved that we are now living in a country where 377 has been read down.

01:36:21.680 --> 01:36:27.400
[Guest]: But even though it was a victory for us, for me, it was also a bit of a defeat.

01:36:27.400 --> 01:36:32.320
[Guest]: Because you see, 377, you remember the wording of it under Macaulay's instructions in the

01:36:32.320 --> 01:36:38.240
[Guest]: IPC, is it bans carnal acts against the law of nature.

01:36:38.240 --> 01:36:44.200
[Guest]: Now, successive judges have interpreted law of nature to mean reproduction, anything resulting

01:36:44.200 --> 01:36:51.200
[Guest]: in reproduction, which is to say, anybody in the world who is sexually active performs

01:36:51.200 --> 01:36:56.600
[Guest]: acts against the laws of nature, because not every sexual act results in reproduction,

01:36:56.600 --> 01:36:57.960
[Guest]: every single person.

01:36:57.960 --> 01:37:06.200
[Guest]: Now, 377 was for a variety of reasons, equated more and more narrowly with male homosexuality

01:37:06.200 --> 01:37:09.280
[Guest]: in India, not even female homosexuality so much.

01:37:09.280 --> 01:37:14.160
[Guest]: And so the way in which the legal team, the wonderful legal team that won the case finally

01:37:14.160 --> 01:37:19.640
[Guest]: in the Supreme Court, fought the case, is by saying this is discriminatory to homosexuals

01:37:19.640 --> 01:37:25.740
[Guest]: in India, which at one level of police harassment was absolutely true.

01:37:25.740 --> 01:37:30.520
[Guest]: But at another level, and this is where I think we lost the battle, it is true as a

01:37:30.520 --> 01:37:36.260
[Guest]: law, it is true about every single sexually active person in this country.

01:37:36.260 --> 01:37:40.800
[Guest]: So for instance, the first Supreme Court bench that overturned the Delhi High Court ruling,

01:37:40.800 --> 01:37:46.160
[Guest]: and that Supreme Court ruling was so phobic, including a sitting judge of the Supreme Court

01:37:46.160 --> 01:37:53.520
[Guest]: saying in open court, he said, I do not know a single gay man, therefore, I don't think

01:37:53.520 --> 01:37:55.960
[Guest]: this affects that many people in this country.

01:37:55.960 --> 01:38:01.680
[Guest]: The reason he's able to say that is because we have so narrowed our definitions about

01:38:01.680 --> 01:38:05.940
[Guest]: who this law affects, that he's able to make that kind of phobic statement and get away

01:38:05.940 --> 01:38:07.360
[Guest]: with it.

01:38:07.360 --> 01:38:12.840
[Guest]: If everyone in that courtroom had stood up and said, I perform acts against nature, carnal

01:38:12.840 --> 01:38:16.480
[Guest]: acts against the order of nature, what would that judge have done?

01:38:16.480 --> 01:38:19.800
[Guest]: Because in fact, it is true that every one of us is affected by this, right?

01:38:19.800 --> 01:38:25.000
[Guest]: And these are very, these are two different ways of approaching the question of desire

01:38:25.000 --> 01:38:30.160
[Guest]: and of sexuality, which is one is the minoritizing narrative, where you say sort of sexual identities

01:38:30.160 --> 01:38:36.920
[Guest]: are minority demographics, and the universalizing narrative where you say desire equally stuns

01:38:36.920 --> 01:38:40.380
[Guest]: all of us, equally undoes us all.

01:38:40.380 --> 01:38:45.680
[Guest]: And so rather than saying, ghettoizing particular sexual identities, and therefore allowing

01:38:45.680 --> 01:38:51.680
[Guest]: one to be triumphant, we say all sexual identities are just all over the place and cannot be

01:38:51.680 --> 01:38:52.960
[Guest]: pinned down.

01:38:52.960 --> 01:38:59.920
[Guest]: So for me, the triumph of 377, which was based on a minoritizing narrative, lost the battle

01:38:59.920 --> 01:39:02.100
[Guest]: of the universalizing impulse.

01:39:02.100 --> 01:39:04.320
[Guest]: And for me, that is an actual loss as well.

01:39:04.320 --> 01:39:09.640
[Amit Varma]: No, and it strikes me also, you know, just the phrase against the order of nature, commits

01:39:09.640 --> 01:39:15.120
[Amit Varma]: both a historical fallacy in claiming, in implying that heterosexuality is what is normal

01:39:15.120 --> 01:39:16.600
[Amit Varma]: and nothing else.

01:39:16.600 --> 01:39:21.800
[Amit Varma]: And also the naturalistic fallacy in making the connection that if it only what is natural

01:39:21.800 --> 01:39:26.440
[Amit Varma]: is right, which is also, you know, obviously, not the case, you know, so you were speaking

01:39:26.440 --> 01:39:30.120
[Amit Varma]: in this about one of the reasons about why it's against the act of nature is that it

01:39:30.120 --> 01:39:32.200
[Amit Varma]: doesn't lead to reproduction.

01:39:32.200 --> 01:39:34.000
[Amit Varma]: Let's talk of reproduction for a bit.

01:39:34.000 --> 01:39:38.080
[Amit Varma]: You know, it strikes me like, you know, you have a great chapter on celibacy, right?

01:39:38.080 --> 01:39:43.740
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that a lot of the people who choose celibacy are in a sense trying

01:39:43.740 --> 01:39:48.760
[Amit Varma]: to move, are trying to get away from the way their desires are governed.

01:39:48.760 --> 01:39:53.880
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that in the modern age, with birth control, which therefore liberates

01:39:53.880 --> 01:39:58.460
[Amit Varma]: all of us from having to worry about reproduction, but especially women, that you can now give

01:39:58.460 --> 01:40:02.120
[Amit Varma]: free rein to your desires and you're not bound by that.

01:40:02.120 --> 01:40:07.680
[Amit Varma]: Has that therefore changed the way that our desires are now expressed and can be expressed?

01:40:07.680 --> 01:40:12.200
[Guest]: Ah, but you see what you're underestimating, which I know you don't, but in that question

01:40:12.200 --> 01:40:16.200
[Guest]: you're underestimating, is the social pressure, right?

01:40:16.200 --> 01:40:20.400
[Guest]: So of course, we can say women, you are free now, you can have birth control, men, you

01:40:20.400 --> 01:40:26.240
[Guest]: should use condoms like Shashi Kapoor in relation to Amitabh Bachchan, but it simply doesn't

01:40:26.240 --> 01:40:27.240
[Guest]: happen, right?

01:40:27.240 --> 01:40:30.760
[Guest]: The first question you're asked within a month or two of getting married is, when are you

01:40:30.760 --> 01:40:31.960
[Guest]: going to have children?

01:40:31.960 --> 01:40:36.880
[Guest]: I think one of the most criminal developments in our country is that on every street corner

01:40:36.880 --> 01:40:42.200
[Guest]: now in cities, you can see IBF clinics, as though what we are suffering from is a lack

01:40:42.200 --> 01:40:44.340
[Guest]: of population, right?

01:40:44.340 --> 01:40:49.200
[Guest]: So the social pressure to have children, and I, for the life of me, do not know where this

01:40:49.200 --> 01:40:51.080
[Guest]: comes from.

01:40:51.080 --> 01:40:52.720
[Guest]: There's no lack of children.

01:40:52.720 --> 01:40:57.480
[Guest]: We have, as I said, pantheons of gods who never actually have their own biological children.

01:40:57.480 --> 01:41:02.920
[Guest]: I don't know where this pressure comes from, but it nonetheless exists and exists hugely.

01:41:02.920 --> 01:41:08.000
[Guest]: So women are not free any longer, even now, despite contraception and the advances in

01:41:08.000 --> 01:41:12.760
[Guest]: contraception to say, okay, I'm not going to have a child, because it's fairly impossible

01:41:12.760 --> 01:41:16.720
[Guest]: to escape that trajectory once you're on it.

01:41:16.720 --> 01:41:20.400
[Guest]: Then you can say, okay, if you have to have a child, have just one child.

01:41:20.400 --> 01:41:25.120
[Guest]: And then all these narratives, oh, one child will suffer, and only child will suffer.

01:41:25.120 --> 01:41:26.640
[Guest]: You need a second child to come along.

01:41:26.640 --> 01:41:27.640
[Amit Varma]: It's, you know, one of my-

01:41:27.640 --> 01:41:29.960
[Guest]: And oh, both childs are girls, you need a boy.

01:41:29.960 --> 01:41:30.960
[Guest]: You need a boy.

01:41:30.960 --> 01:41:39.000
[Guest]: So one of my theories is, and it's, I think, a true one, is that the more difficult an

01:41:39.000 --> 01:41:43.160
[Guest]: action is, the more we sentimentalize it, right?

01:41:43.160 --> 01:41:46.400
[Guest]: So we sentimentalize, for instance, war.

01:41:46.400 --> 01:41:49.520
[Guest]: And similarly, I think we sentimentalize motherhood.

01:41:49.520 --> 01:41:52.320
[Guest]: So for instance, if you just, again, do that blind test, right?

01:41:52.320 --> 01:41:57.840
[Guest]: Ask somebody, any random person, how would you like your body taken over for nine months

01:41:57.840 --> 01:42:03.960
[Guest]: by an alien being, being extremely sick through all of those nine months, not have any control

01:42:03.960 --> 01:42:11.260
[Guest]: over your body, have your body torn open and blood and guts spilling out in order to give

01:42:11.260 --> 01:42:12.660
[Guest]: birth to this alien being?

01:42:12.660 --> 01:42:15.080
[Guest]: You think anybody will say yes?

01:42:15.080 --> 01:42:17.440
[Guest]: If they said, we'll say, my God, you're mad.

01:42:17.440 --> 01:42:21.040
[Guest]: How can you want to inflict that kind of violence on yourself, right?

01:42:21.040 --> 01:42:27.800
[Guest]: Because it is such a violent act, it is smothered over by layers and layers and layers of sentimentality,

01:42:27.800 --> 01:42:32.480
[Guest]: motherhood is the best thing that can happen to you.

01:42:32.480 --> 01:42:36.960
[Guest]: You haven't lived, if you haven't experienced the joys of motherhood, there is no phrase

01:42:36.960 --> 01:42:38.900
[Guest]: like the sorrows of motherhood, right?

01:42:38.900 --> 01:42:40.960
[Guest]: It's always the joys of motherhood.

01:42:40.960 --> 01:42:43.640
[Guest]: And ask any mother.

01:42:43.640 --> 01:42:46.280
[Guest]: And if they're being honest, they'll say to you, my God, this is a pain.

01:42:46.280 --> 01:42:49.080
[Guest]: I can't believe I signed up for this.

01:42:49.080 --> 01:42:50.080
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:42:50.080 --> 01:42:51.640
[Guest]: And it's a pain for the rest of your life.

01:42:51.640 --> 01:42:53.800
[Guest]: Do you ever stop worrying about the child?

01:42:53.800 --> 01:42:57.160
[Guest]: Do you ever stop fearing bodily damage or mental damage to them?

01:42:57.160 --> 01:43:04.080
[Guest]: So no one in their right minds would sign up for this experience, if it were not utterly

01:43:04.080 --> 01:43:07.260
[Guest]: sentimentalized to within an inch of your life.

01:43:07.260 --> 01:43:11.280
[Amit Varma]: So I once wrote a column which will be linked from the show notes for your perusal, for

01:43:11.280 --> 01:43:14.360
[Amit Varma]: which I got trolled more than anything else I have ever written.

01:43:14.360 --> 01:43:17.040
[Amit Varma]: And the column basically argued that it's immoral to have children.

01:43:17.040 --> 01:43:18.040
[Guest]: Good for you.

01:43:18.040 --> 01:43:19.040
[Guest]: I must read that.

01:43:19.040 --> 01:43:20.040
[Guest]: Not for obvious reasons.

01:43:20.040 --> 01:43:21.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:43:21.040 --> 01:43:22.040
[Amit Varma]: Linked from the show notes.

01:43:22.040 --> 01:43:27.200
[Amit Varma]: And, and parent trolls, I realized are worse than Bhak trolls or Shah Rukh Khan trolls,

01:43:27.200 --> 01:43:30.200
[Unknown]: all the different kinds of trolls that I have encountered in my life.

01:43:30.200 --> 01:43:31.200
[Amit Varma]: Wow.

01:43:31.200 --> 01:43:35.120
[Amit Varma]: A deeper thought here is that I wasn't saying that birth control is a kind of panacea, obviously

01:43:35.120 --> 01:43:38.200
[Amit Varma]: social change happens at a seemingly glacial pace.

01:43:38.200 --> 01:43:42.760
[Amit Varma]: So if you look back on the last four or five decades, like my God, how much we have progressed.

01:43:42.760 --> 01:43:49.720
[Amit Varma]: But I would also say that one of the fundamental, that the fundamental battle of humanity is

01:43:49.720 --> 01:43:54.880
[Amit Varma]: as rational beings, we fight the way we are hardwired, right, for example, my wife and

01:43:54.880 --> 01:43:59.360
[Amit Varma]: I have decided not to have kids, however, we are hardwired to create kids, we are fighting

01:43:59.360 --> 01:44:06.160
[Amit Varma]: a hard wiring, I might feel all kinds of impulses in the course of a day, which I fight, I am

01:44:06.160 --> 01:44:08.300
[Amit Varma]: fighting my biology.

01:44:08.300 --> 01:44:14.040
[Amit Varma]: And you know, and you could see that a lot of for example, the social pressures to have

01:44:14.040 --> 01:44:20.800
[Amit Varma]: children or whatever, are a codification of the way we are hardwired, but equally culture,

01:44:20.800 --> 01:44:25.520
[Amit Varma]: just as it can enforce our hardwiring can also militate against it.

01:44:25.520 --> 01:44:30.920
[Amit Varma]: And that's sort of the whole kind of battle and all these desires are clearly natural

01:44:30.920 --> 01:44:31.920
[Amit Varma]: to us.

01:44:31.920 --> 01:44:36.320
[Guest]: And yet we fight them, you know, which is why the phrase hardwiring I'm not it's not

01:44:36.320 --> 01:44:37.940
[Guest]: my best friend.

01:44:37.940 --> 01:44:41.080
[Guest]: Because I actually I don't think there's that much that's hardwired.

01:44:41.080 --> 01:44:46.960
[Guest]: I mean, clearly, there are some things that are but these things, the sort of things that

01:44:46.960 --> 01:44:51.960
[Guest]: we associate with sentiment and emotion and things like that, are not hardwired and just

01:44:51.960 --> 01:44:55.500
[Guest]: to stick with the example of children and childbearing.

01:44:55.500 --> 01:45:04.000
[Guest]: If you look back even, let's say, 200 years, people routinely had x number of children,

01:45:04.000 --> 01:45:07.320
[Guest]: half of whom would routinely die.

01:45:07.320 --> 01:45:11.440
[Guest]: And this idea of Oh, my God, the loss of a child is the worst thing ever in the world

01:45:11.440 --> 01:45:15.000
[Guest]: simply does not exist as a narrative.

01:45:15.000 --> 01:45:21.320
[Guest]: Which is to say the relation of a parent to a child, as we understand it today, i.e. the

01:45:21.320 --> 01:45:26.720
[Guest]: craving and all that is a fairly recent phenomenon, cultural phenomenon, which is what I mean

01:45:26.720 --> 01:45:28.520
[Guest]: about the sentimentalizing thing, right?

01:45:28.520 --> 01:45:33.320
[Guest]: If you're saying 1000s of years ago, people had children, because to go back to Ayyappan's

01:45:33.320 --> 01:45:37.480
[Guest]: dilemma, we're going to die and we want someone to take over our cave.

01:45:37.480 --> 01:45:38.480
[Guest]: That's different.

01:45:38.480 --> 01:45:39.480
[Guest]: Right?

01:45:39.480 --> 01:45:43.240
[Guest]: If people said today, we are only producing children because we want to hang on to our

01:45:43.240 --> 01:45:44.240
[Guest]: money.

01:45:44.240 --> 01:45:47.880
[Guest]: I'd actually have a lot of more sympathy for that kind of narrative.

01:45:47.880 --> 01:45:52.280
[Amit Varma]: But I think both are a cultural rationalization of a natural hardwired instinct.

01:45:52.280 --> 01:45:57.720
[Guest]: But I don't know if it's hardwired, if it requires cultural rationalization, you see,

01:45:57.720 --> 01:46:02.460
[Guest]: that's my, that's my thing that that if it is hardwired, then it doesn't need anything.

01:46:02.460 --> 01:46:05.560
[Guest]: If it needs something, that means it's actually more tenuous than

01:46:05.560 --> 01:46:11.280
[Amit Varma]: No, I think it always needs a little bit of dressing to seem sort of, you know, respectable

01:46:11.280 --> 01:46:12.280
[Amit Varma]: and whatever.

01:46:12.280 --> 01:46:15.600
[Amit Varma]: Anyways, so that's a whole different argument.

01:46:15.600 --> 01:46:19.040
[Unknown]: We could do an episode on that as well sometime.

01:46:19.040 --> 01:46:23.240
[Amit Varma]: Let's move on to what I think is a very important aspect of your book, and you have a chapter

01:46:23.240 --> 01:46:27.300
[Amit Varma]: on this as well, which is about the role that language plays.

01:46:27.300 --> 01:46:32.360
[Amit Varma]: And the fascinating fact that there are some languages, like most of our Indian languages,

01:46:32.360 --> 01:46:34.320
[Amit Varma]: which are gendered languages.

01:46:34.320 --> 01:46:38.400
[Amit Varma]: So you know, a chair is a particular gender and all and some which are not like Persian

01:46:38.400 --> 01:46:45.040
[Amit Varma]: and English, you know, tell me a little bit about how languages play a part in the landscape

01:46:45.040 --> 01:46:46.040
[Guest]: of desire.

01:46:46.040 --> 01:46:47.040
[Guest]: Right?

01:46:47.040 --> 01:46:52.040
[Guest]: You know, the reason, side note, why you as with Bengali blood in your family, and why

01:46:52.040 --> 01:46:56.160
[Guest]: me as South Indian blood in my family, the reason Hindi speakers often laugh at us is

01:46:56.160 --> 01:46:58.360
[Amit Varma]: because we get our genders wrong.

01:46:58.360 --> 01:47:03.320
[Guest]: Because both Bengali and Malayalam are not as gendered languages as Hindi, right?

01:47:03.320 --> 01:47:04.960
[Guest]: Some nouns have gender, but not all of them.

01:47:04.960 --> 01:47:08.120
[Guest]: So in fact, we don't have that usage of gender in our language.

01:47:08.120 --> 01:47:10.320
[Amit Varma]: I am always mocked for this.

01:47:10.320 --> 01:47:13.800
[Guest]: Those who are listening kindly don't mock me anymore.

01:47:13.800 --> 01:47:14.800
[Guest]: I am too.

01:47:14.800 --> 01:47:17.720
[Guest]: And I am a Dilliwali born and bred.

01:47:17.720 --> 01:47:22.000
[Guest]: But you know, talk about hard wiring, there's something in me, where my Hindi in terms of

01:47:22.000 --> 01:47:27.400
[Guest]: gender is completely subservient to my scant knowledge of Malayalam, where the gender doesn't

01:47:27.400 --> 01:47:28.400
[Guest]: play out that way.

01:47:28.400 --> 01:47:35.240
[Guest]: Anyway, there are only two things in the world that have gender, physical human and animal

01:47:35.240 --> 01:47:41.880
[Guest]: beings and languages, that's it, which I find fascinating, because gender is what confers

01:47:41.880 --> 01:47:44.920
[Guest]: identity on human beings and animals.

01:47:44.920 --> 01:47:47.320
[Guest]: But for now, we'll talk about human beings.

01:47:47.320 --> 01:47:51.200
[Guest]: And it's also what confers identity in language.

01:47:51.200 --> 01:47:59.760
[Guest]: So for instance, in gendered languages, like Hindi, like Urdu, like all the Romance languages

01:47:59.760 --> 01:48:03.960
[Guest]: in the world, all nouns will have a gender attached to it, right?

01:48:03.960 --> 01:48:12.440
[Guest]: And they are awful, like cities, all objects will be feminine, cars, for instance, or cities

01:48:12.440 --> 01:48:13.440
[Guest]: and things like that.

01:48:13.440 --> 01:48:17.940
[Guest]: Whereas English in that sense is an extremely gender free language, because other than he

01:48:17.940 --> 01:48:23.560
[Guest]: and she, nothing else has gender, no nouns have gender table, everything is an it.

01:48:23.560 --> 01:48:31.240
[Guest]: So if we want to correlate language and gender identity, it seems like people who speak English

01:48:31.240 --> 01:48:33.020
[Guest]: should be less gendered.

01:48:33.020 --> 01:48:36.440
[Guest]: And people who speak Hindi should be more gendered, which is not the case.

01:48:36.440 --> 01:48:40.300
[Guest]: But what I find fascinating is that languages can play a really interesting role in how

01:48:40.300 --> 01:48:41.820
[Guest]: we think about desire.

01:48:41.820 --> 01:48:45.800
[Guest]: So for instance, and this is going to go back actually to Tony Joseph, who you brought up

01:48:45.800 --> 01:48:51.880
[Guest]: earlier in this idea of migration, people sort of think of Sanskrit as the Ur language

01:48:51.880 --> 01:48:52.880
[Guest]: of India, right?

01:48:52.880 --> 01:48:57.240
[Guest]: The language of the Indian soil, which was nothing of the kind, because Sanskrit actually

01:48:57.240 --> 01:49:03.640
[Guest]: comes from the old Indo-Persian family of languages, and actually shares more in common

01:49:03.640 --> 01:49:06.720
[Guest]: with Persian than it does with many other languages.

01:49:06.720 --> 01:49:12.040
[Guest]: So for instance, the word ast, which in Sanskrit means I am, it's the fundamental assertion,

01:49:12.040 --> 01:49:15.520
[Guest]: is the same word in Persian, ast, right?

01:49:15.520 --> 01:49:20.000
[Guest]: And so Persian, though, is a non-gendered language.

01:49:20.000 --> 01:49:22.720
[Guest]: And Sanskrit is a gendered language.

01:49:22.720 --> 01:49:30.600
[Guest]: But one of the arguments I'm making is that the reason why the Kama Sutra, Buddhist texts,

01:49:30.600 --> 01:49:37.320
[Guest]: Jain texts, Vedic texts, all these texts written in Sanskrit, sometimes in Pali, but sometimes

01:49:37.320 --> 01:49:44.000
[Guest]: in Sanskrit, a lot of them are able to talk about genders as being more than just two.

01:49:44.000 --> 01:49:49.120
[Guest]: There is also the Napunsak, which is the third, there is the male Napunsak, and there is the

01:49:49.120 --> 01:49:50.120
[Guest]: female Napunsak.

01:49:50.120 --> 01:49:53.240
[Guest]: There are like five or six categories of gender.

01:49:53.240 --> 01:49:56.800
[Guest]: And one of the arguments I'm making is that the reason why, say, these texts written in

01:49:56.800 --> 01:50:02.000
[Guest]: Sanskrit are able to have multiple genders is because they still have a trace memory

01:50:02.000 --> 01:50:08.400
[Guest]: of where they come from, which is Central Asia, which is the Persian family of languages.

01:50:08.400 --> 01:50:13.920
[Guest]: And so for me, it's really fascinating which languages will and will not allow that capaciousness.

01:50:13.920 --> 01:50:17.200
[Guest]: English, for instance, does not allow that capaciousness historically.

01:50:17.200 --> 01:50:21.440
[Guest]: They're so horrified by anything that does not fit two genders, they say, we have to

01:50:21.440 --> 01:50:22.520
[Guest]: shut it down.

01:50:22.520 --> 01:50:24.920
[Guest]: But linguistically, they're great.

01:50:24.920 --> 01:50:29.620
[Guest]: They don't feminize objects and they don't masculinize valor and things like that.

01:50:29.620 --> 01:50:35.880
[Guest]: So there isn't a direct correlation, but there very much is a relationship between, to go

01:50:35.880 --> 01:50:39.000
[Guest]: back to what you were saying about our desire to categorize.

01:50:39.000 --> 01:50:41.200
[Guest]: Language is our means of categorizing.

01:50:41.200 --> 01:50:47.360
[Guest]: And when we categorize the world around us according to gender, the world looks different

01:50:47.360 --> 01:50:50.560
[Guest]: from when we don't categorize the world according to gender.

01:50:50.560 --> 01:50:57.400
[Amit Varma]: So I've always sort of speculated on the role that language plays in shaping a society.

01:50:57.400 --> 01:51:01.880
[Amit Varma]: For example, it strikes me that one of the reasons that I like Japanese literature so

01:51:01.880 --> 01:51:06.360
[Amit Varma]: much, for example, is that my aesthetic preference is to minimalism.

01:51:06.360 --> 01:51:12.520
[Amit Varma]: So all the writers that I read, whether they are Kawabata, Murakami, Yoko Ogawa, or whoever,

01:51:12.520 --> 01:51:14.320
[Amit Varma]: are all minimal, very clean writers.

01:51:14.320 --> 01:51:16.520
[Amit Varma]: And that completely plays to me.

01:51:16.520 --> 01:51:19.500
[Amit Varma]: And English has some of those values and others.

01:51:19.500 --> 01:51:23.100
[Amit Varma]: And when you look at Urdu poetry, for example, it is just the opposite.

01:51:23.100 --> 01:51:26.760
[Amit Varma]: It's very sensuous and florid and all of that.

01:51:26.760 --> 01:51:33.320
