01:55:19.640 --> 01:55:25.800
[Amit Varma]: attractiveness as soon as hair begins to sprout and so on and so forth.

01:55:25.800 --> 01:55:30.760
[Amit Varma]: Looking at that with the lens of morality as we do today, and the importance we correctly

01:55:30.760 --> 01:55:36.180
[Amit Varma]: finally give to consent, you know, how does that affect your looking at desire?

01:55:36.180 --> 01:55:41.920
[Amit Varma]: Because these notions of consent and individual rights and all of that are in a sense, you

01:55:41.920 --> 01:55:46.640
[Amit Varma]: know, relatively recent, I won't say inventions, but they've been given importance relatively

01:55:46.640 --> 01:55:48.640
[Guest]: in recent centuries.

01:55:48.640 --> 01:55:53.240
[Amit Varma]: So how does one, you know, you have this beautiful multiplicity of desires, there's so much happening,

01:55:53.240 --> 01:55:54.600
[Guest]: but there are also these questions.

01:55:54.600 --> 01:55:59.240
[Guest]: Yeah, so tricky, you know, I mean, so complex and complicated.

01:55:59.240 --> 01:56:03.480
[Guest]: What we call underage today, as you know, was not always underage.

01:56:03.480 --> 01:56:07.280
[Guest]: We all have great, great, great grandmothers and grandfathers who were married when they

01:56:07.280 --> 01:56:12.000
[Guest]: were nine or 10, which will strike people with horror now, but frankly, that is where

01:56:12.000 --> 01:56:14.360
[Guest]: we all came from.

01:56:14.360 --> 01:56:21.000
[Guest]: One of the things that I don't like about us saying, oh, in that time period or in that

01:56:21.000 --> 01:56:25.360
[Guest]: day and age, because that implies a position, a vantage point of superiority now, which

01:56:25.360 --> 01:56:27.560
[Guest]: I don't think is fully earned.

01:56:27.560 --> 01:56:33.680
[Guest]: So this entire thing about age is one of these things that I think is a bit, and should be

01:56:33.680 --> 01:56:38.640
[Guest]: at least treated as a bit more fluid and complicated than it is right now, because we all have

01:56:38.640 --> 01:56:42.220
[Guest]: had ancestors who were quote unquote underage.

01:56:42.220 --> 01:56:43.480
[Guest]: So that is one thing, right?

01:56:43.480 --> 01:56:49.120
[Guest]: The idea that somehow when you're 18, everything becomes okay is a fairly arbitrary sign.

01:56:49.120 --> 01:56:55.120
[Guest]: In fact, Alfred Kinsey, who you know, is a famous, famous American sexologist, has compelling

01:56:55.120 --> 01:57:00.960
[Guest]: sections where he says, by saying that you are only an adult when you're 18 years old,

01:57:00.960 --> 01:57:06.680
[Guest]: is to completely ignore the most turbulent sexual years of the teenage, when you're told

01:57:06.680 --> 01:57:10.480
[Guest]: that it's not only illegal, but immoral to be sexually active.

01:57:10.480 --> 01:57:16.400
[Guest]: And he says the kinds of neurotic disorders that produces is actually harming society

01:57:16.400 --> 01:57:17.600
[Guest]: much more than we know it, right?

01:57:17.600 --> 01:57:22.440
[Guest]: So to suddenly say, at 18, you are and can be sexually active, I think is actually a

01:57:22.440 --> 01:57:24.760
[Guest]: slightly pernicious thing to say.

01:57:24.760 --> 01:57:29.780
[Guest]: Because long before 18, we are actually sexually active in our minds, if nowhere else, right?

01:57:29.780 --> 01:57:34.200
[Guest]: And to be told over and over again, that's wrong, really doesn't number on people, right?

01:57:34.200 --> 01:57:38.520
[Guest]: As we know, in our country as well, really sort of to be told that's bad, that's wrong

01:57:38.520 --> 01:57:41.240
[Guest]: is really problematic.

01:57:41.240 --> 01:57:46.280
[Guest]: The question of consent is just so much more complex.

01:57:46.280 --> 01:57:50.680
[Guest]: I think there is no doubt, the two things I want to say about it, the first is, there

01:57:50.680 --> 01:57:59.320
[Guest]: is no doubt that in an ideal world, we should all be able to experience, express and recognize

01:57:59.320 --> 01:58:01.000
[Guest]: consent.

01:58:01.000 --> 01:58:07.280
[Guest]: The reason why it is so difficult is because consent is not a transparent thing, right?

01:58:07.280 --> 01:58:09.800
[Guest]: If it was, then it wouldn't be a big deal.

01:58:09.800 --> 01:58:15.440
[Guest]: We wouldn't have all these things about consent is necessary and all that if it was that transparent.

01:58:15.440 --> 01:58:19.680
[Guest]: The reason it's not transparent to others is because it's not always transparent to

01:58:19.680 --> 01:58:21.640
[Guest]: ourselves.

01:58:21.640 --> 01:58:25.920
[Guest]: So do I want something now that five minutes later, I won't want?

01:58:25.920 --> 01:58:28.680
[Guest]: Do I not want something now that five minutes later, I might?

01:58:28.680 --> 01:58:33.960
[Guest]: Do I want something now that two days later will fill me with so much shame that I will

01:58:33.960 --> 01:58:37.720
[Guest]: retrospectively say I did not want it then, right?

01:58:37.720 --> 01:58:40.040
[Guest]: Where is the consent in all this?

01:58:40.040 --> 01:58:42.320
[Guest]: What is my consent in all this?

01:58:42.320 --> 01:58:49.320
[Guest]: And I think those are questions that necessarily complicate what we understand as consent.

01:58:49.320 --> 01:58:54.280
[Guest]: The problem with those complications, of course, is that people can use it as loopholes for

01:58:54.280 --> 01:58:57.280
[Guest]: very real violence.

01:58:57.280 --> 01:59:00.640
[Guest]: And this brings me to my second point, which is so far, and I don't know how long we've

01:59:00.640 --> 01:59:03.240
[Guest]: been talking, an hour and a half, two hours.

01:59:03.240 --> 01:59:08.720
[Guest]: So far, we've been talking about desires and about sexualities and the plurality of desires

01:59:08.720 --> 01:59:12.360
[Guest]: in unadulteratedly happy terms and good terms.

01:59:12.360 --> 01:59:20.520
[Guest]: It's a good thing, but desire more than anything else in the world has an underbelly, which

01:59:20.520 --> 01:59:27.520
[Guest]: is not that great, which is in fact violent, which can be sadistic, which can be really

01:59:27.520 --> 01:59:31.120
[Guest]: intent on wreaking damage in the world.

01:59:31.120 --> 01:59:37.680
[Guest]: Freud's big insight is that our desires are always both things.

01:59:37.680 --> 01:59:43.920
[Guest]: They're always something that we want to give us joy, but it also is something that gives

01:59:43.920 --> 01:59:46.400
[Guest]: us destructiveness.

01:59:46.400 --> 01:59:53.320
[Guest]: And so when we think about desire, unfortunately, we have to be aware that desire can be extremely

01:59:53.320 --> 01:59:55.520
[Guest]: violent.

01:59:55.520 --> 01:59:57.920
[Guest]: That's the danger of desire, right?

01:59:57.920 --> 02:00:03.220
[Guest]: It can be violent in a way that we like because it can question the status quo.

02:00:03.220 --> 02:00:04.520
[Guest]: That's how we've been talking about it.

02:00:04.520 --> 02:00:07.660
[Guest]: And that kind of violence is something to be encouraged.

02:00:07.660 --> 02:00:11.600
[Guest]: It can be violent because it can throw acid in the face of a woman who has said no to

02:00:11.600 --> 02:00:12.600
[Guest]: me.

02:00:12.600 --> 02:00:15.400
[Guest]: That's the kind of violence we don't want.

02:00:15.400 --> 02:00:17.380
[Guest]: How do we separate the one from the other?

02:00:17.380 --> 02:00:20.800
[Guest]: Because it's often one that turns into the other.

02:00:20.800 --> 02:00:25.040
[Guest]: All these people, many of these narratives of acid attacks, for instance, the man would

02:00:25.040 --> 02:00:27.600
[Guest]: say I loved her.

02:00:27.600 --> 02:00:31.240
[Guest]: That can strike us and should as being utterly warped.

02:00:31.240 --> 02:00:37.940
[Guest]: But the dirty secret of desire is that all desire is potentially warped that way.

02:00:37.940 --> 02:00:43.000
[Guest]: And this is something that is the complicating factor.

02:00:43.000 --> 02:00:47.140
[Guest]: This is what we need to also think about when we think about the multitudes of desire.

02:00:47.140 --> 02:00:49.680
[Guest]: Because this too is one among those multitudes.

02:00:49.680 --> 02:00:55.180
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that we are constantly involved in trying to figure out a trade off between

02:00:55.180 --> 02:00:56.440
[Unknown]: two things.

02:00:56.440 --> 02:01:01.120
[Amit Varma]: One is celebrating our natural desires as the Kama Sutra does.

02:01:01.120 --> 02:01:06.120
[Amit Varma]: And the other is repressing our desires as say yoga seeks to do.

02:01:06.120 --> 02:01:12.560
[Amit Varma]: And I think the second is very important as well, for the simple reason that it's again,

02:01:12.560 --> 02:01:19.400
[Amit Varma]: me as a rational machine, fighting my programming, that, you know, I might feel that my desires

02:01:19.400 --> 02:01:22.920
[Amit Varma]: get in the way of doing things that I feel I should be doing rationally.

02:01:22.920 --> 02:01:26.720
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, I try to bring an end to it, I try to discipline my mind.

02:01:26.720 --> 02:01:30.600
[Amit Varma]: This is why mindfulness meditation is such a big deal these days.

02:01:30.600 --> 02:01:35.880
[Amit Varma]: You know, this was one of the core reasonings for why kind of yoga came up, it's kind of

02:01:35.880 --> 02:01:36.880
[Amit Varma]: both things.

02:01:36.880 --> 02:01:37.880
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:01:37.880 --> 02:01:40.580
[Guest]: And no, I mean, I was, I agree completely.

02:01:40.580 --> 02:01:44.760
[Guest]: This is why, you know, I mean, philosophers and thinkers for centuries have known this,

02:01:44.760 --> 02:01:45.760
[Guest]: right?

02:01:45.760 --> 02:01:49.680
[Guest]: Which is why someone like Hobbes is able to say that life in nature is nasty, brutish

02:01:49.680 --> 02:01:54.120
[Guest]: and short, because actually left to our own devices, we'll all just kill each other, right?

02:01:54.120 --> 02:01:56.800
[Guest]: Because that is actually our instinct.

02:01:56.800 --> 02:01:58.960
[Guest]: Freud is very, very clear about this.

02:01:58.960 --> 02:02:04.240
[Guest]: He says the only when he writes this famous book, Civilization and its Discontents, he

02:02:04.240 --> 02:02:09.200
[Guest]: says the only way we can be civilized is if we repress our desires.

02:02:09.200 --> 02:02:12.960
[Guest]: And so repression for him is actually what results in civilization.

02:02:12.960 --> 02:02:15.660
[Guest]: You cannot have civilization without repression.

02:02:15.660 --> 02:02:16.800
[Guest]: And so that's absolutely right.

02:02:16.800 --> 02:02:19.920
[Guest]: We have to repress our desires.

02:02:19.920 --> 02:02:24.000
[Guest]: But with the knowledge that we're doing that, because our desires can go in directions that

02:02:24.000 --> 02:02:28.520
[Guest]: we have no control over, which is what makes desire fascinating, right, for me and for

02:02:28.520 --> 02:02:29.520
[Guest]: us.

02:02:29.520 --> 02:02:35.760
[Guest]: Yes, to repression, but repression is not necessarily the same, although it has been

02:02:35.760 --> 02:02:40.100
[Guest]: allied with immorality, illegality, all that stuff.

02:02:40.100 --> 02:02:45.200
[Guest]: We all walk that fine line between expression and repression.

02:02:45.200 --> 02:02:49.720
[Guest]: That line is different for everybody individually.

02:02:49.720 --> 02:02:53.320
[Guest]: There is no perfect golden mean for what that line is.

02:02:53.320 --> 02:02:58.520
[Guest]: Absolutely the sort of yoga karma relation is very much that attempt at finding that

02:02:58.520 --> 02:03:01.760
[Guest]: balance failing most of the time.

02:03:01.760 --> 02:03:07.560
[Guest]: But yes, repression has a role to play and a huge role to play in ensuring that we can

02:03:07.560 --> 02:03:10.200
