[Guest]: And sex or our desire always straddles fantasy and reality.

02:06:03.480 --> 02:06:07.520
[Guest]: And so that's one of the reasons why I said the idea of consent is not at all a transparent

02:06:07.520 --> 02:06:12.240
[Guest]: one, because we actually want different things.

02:06:12.240 --> 02:06:14.040
[Guest]: We don't want to be raped.

02:06:14.040 --> 02:06:19.520
[Guest]: But we have been brought up in a culture in which violence against women has been so naturalized

02:06:19.520 --> 02:06:22.560
[Guest]: as to be sexualized as well.

02:06:22.560 --> 02:06:23.680
[Guest]: And we live in that culture, right?

02:06:23.680 --> 02:06:25.320
[Guest]: We don't live in Mars.

02:06:25.320 --> 02:06:31.840
[Guest]: And so for instance, how is it possible that all these old men, 75, 85, oligarchs, rich

02:06:31.840 --> 02:06:37.480
[Guest]: men, all have young 25 something wives, or girlfriends or lovers or whatever it is.

02:06:37.480 --> 02:06:42.920
[Guest]: It's not because the women are finding them that sexually attractive, but sexual attractiveness

02:06:42.920 --> 02:06:50.900
[Guest]: also has being involved with men, rich men in power as one of its tags.

02:06:50.900 --> 02:06:55.600
[Guest]: And so in that case, then sexual desire to go back to our earlier conversation has barely

02:06:55.600 --> 02:07:00.760
[Guest]: anything to do with genitalia, and everything to do with this guy is a rich patriarch.

02:07:00.760 --> 02:07:04.280
[Guest]: And so for instance, why would Monica Lewinsky have an affair with Bill Clinton?

02:07:04.280 --> 02:07:06.960
[Guest]: Because he's the President of the United States of America.

02:07:06.960 --> 02:07:11.640
[Amit Varma]: But I'd argue that that is the proximate reason, but not the ultimate one, in the sense that

02:07:11.640 --> 02:07:17.200
[Amit Varma]: what, you know, evolutionary psychologists would say is that women have been hardwired

02:07:17.200 --> 02:07:23.560
[Amit Varma]: to be attracted to successful men, and, you know, older men who can look after them and

02:07:23.560 --> 02:07:25.360
[Amit Varma]: their babies well.

02:07:25.360 --> 02:07:30.720
[Amit Varma]: And so that attraction will result in say, a Monica Lewinsky going for a Bill Clinton.

02:07:30.720 --> 02:07:32.960
[Guest]: And it's kind of hardwired in that sense.

02:07:32.960 --> 02:07:35.440
[Guest]: See, this is why I don't like hardwired at all, right?

02:07:35.440 --> 02:07:39.380
[Guest]: Which is why evolutionary psychology, I think, can be fascinating.

02:07:39.380 --> 02:07:44.640
[Guest]: But I don't like this phrase of it, because it's not like if you're thinking about hardwired

02:07:44.640 --> 02:07:47.600
[Guest]: as you know, something that comes down over centuries.

02:07:47.600 --> 02:07:52.120
[Guest]: It's not like 50,000 years ago, a neanderthal woman was saying, let me find someone who

02:07:52.120 --> 02:07:54.600
[Guest]: was 90 years old to look after me and my children.

02:07:54.600 --> 02:07:55.880
[Amit Varma]: I mean, that's simply not the case.

02:07:55.880 --> 02:07:59.320
[Amit Varma]: You'd be drawn to success, you'd be drawn to the alpha male in the tribe, which would,

02:07:59.320 --> 02:08:01.880
[Amit Varma]: of course, increase your chances of reproductive success.

02:08:01.880 --> 02:08:05.600
[Guest]: But you could also be drawn in the opposite way, which we don't say at all, right?

02:08:05.600 --> 02:08:09.680
[Guest]: You could be drawn to the woman who has multiple children, because you think she'll have more

02:08:09.680 --> 02:08:10.680
[Guest]: children.

02:08:10.680 --> 02:08:11.680
[Guest]: That's not the case that happens here.

02:08:11.680 --> 02:08:12.680
[Guest]: At all.

02:08:12.680 --> 02:08:15.320
[Guest]: Men are not attracted to women who have multiple children, necessarily, right?

02:08:15.320 --> 02:08:17.880
[Amit Varma]: Men are attracted to multiple women for just that reason.

02:08:17.880 --> 02:08:20.600
[Guest]: Men are more promiscuous naturally than women.

02:08:20.600 --> 02:08:22.240
[Guest]: See, naturally ka nahi pata.

02:08:22.240 --> 02:08:23.240
[Guest]: Not at all.

02:08:23.240 --> 02:08:27.400
[Guest]: You see, I think we're naturalizing something, and then saying it is natural.

02:08:27.400 --> 02:08:31.800
[Amit Varma]: I think it's sort of, you know, in the whole nature versus nature thing, I think it's sort

02:08:31.800 --> 02:08:34.120
[Amit Varma]: of dangerous to go to one extreme or the other.

02:08:34.120 --> 02:08:38.840
[Amit Varma]: I like the phrasing that I'd once heard, that nature gives us knobs, nurture turns them.

02:08:38.840 --> 02:08:43.400
[Amit Varma]: So I think both are incredibly important, and we should not deny one or the other.

02:08:43.400 --> 02:08:44.400
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:08:44.400 --> 02:08:45.400
[Guest]: No, no, there's no question of denying.

02:08:45.400 --> 02:08:49.720
[Guest]: But I sort of don't think that 25-year-olds being attracted to 90-year-olds is somehow

02:08:49.720 --> 02:08:56.520
[Guest]: hardwired, because there are plenty of, let's say, 24-year-olds who are perfectly rich men,

02:08:56.520 --> 02:08:57.520
[Guest]: for instance.

02:08:57.520 --> 02:09:01.720
[Guest]: You know, and it also doesn't explain the fact that women are always younger, the men

02:09:01.720 --> 02:09:08.200
[Guest]: always have to be older, you know, all that stuff is problematic.

02:09:08.200 --> 02:09:13.880
[Guest]: And you know, talk about underage or whatever it is, these things are very complicated.

02:09:13.880 --> 02:09:18.600
[Guest]: And yes, there is centuries of conditioning of one kind or the other.

02:09:18.600 --> 02:09:22.400
[Guest]: That's the compromise we can arrive at, of conditioning of one kind or the other.

02:09:22.400 --> 02:09:29.580
[Guest]: But all this conditioning means that in some ways, many ways, many of us might have naturalized

02:09:29.580 --> 02:09:35.200
[Guest]: our own oppression, to the extent that it doesn't even feel oppressive to us any longer.

02:09:35.200 --> 02:09:36.200
[Guest]: Right?

02:09:36.200 --> 02:09:40.460
[Guest]: And this was a big insight, say, by someone like Michel Foucault, where he says, you know,

02:09:40.460 --> 02:09:44.840
[Guest]: people keep saying, oh, we want relationships of equality, where there is no power differential

02:09:44.840 --> 02:09:45.840
[Guest]: between the two.

02:09:45.840 --> 02:09:51.040
[Guest]: And he says, you can't have a relationship without power difference, it is an impossibility.

02:09:51.040 --> 02:09:54.520
[Guest]: And in fact, this is also an insight of the best kind of feminist thinking, is that power

02:09:54.520 --> 02:09:58.400
[Guest]: difference is sexy, is attractive.

02:09:58.400 --> 02:10:01.480
[Guest]: So to sort of say we want a relationship of equality is a pipe dream.

02:10:01.480 --> 02:10:06.760
[Guest]: But again, as I say, there's always fantasy and reality involved in all these conversations

02:10:06.760 --> 02:10:07.760
[Guest]: across the spectrum.

02:10:07.760 --> 02:10:08.760
[Amit Varma]: No.

02:10:08.760 --> 02:10:14.440
[Amit Varma]: And you know, another interesting finding of everybody lies has nothing to do with nature.

02:10:14.440 --> 02:10:17.400
[Amit Varma]: Because this particular finding was unique to India.

02:10:17.400 --> 02:10:24.040
[Amit Varma]: And this finding was that so basically, what he did was, he typed my husband wants into

02:10:24.040 --> 02:10:26.880
[Amit Varma]: the search bar to see what would pop up.

02:10:26.880 --> 02:10:31.360
[Amit Varma]: And apparently, for Indians, the number one result was, my husband wants me to breastfeed

02:10:31.360 --> 02:10:32.360
[Amit Varma]: him.

02:10:32.360 --> 02:10:37.600
[Amit Varma]: And this is apparently 50 times more common in India than anywhere in the world.

02:10:37.600 --> 02:10:40.360
[Amit Varma]: So it is clearly not nothing to do with hardwiring.

02:10:40.360 --> 02:10:45.280
[Amit Varma]: It is clearly a cultural thing, that Indian men want to be breastfed.

02:10:45.280 --> 02:10:50.240
[Amit Varma]: And this is just so bizarre that, you know, I couldn't fathom what the reasons was cultural

02:10:50.240 --> 02:10:54.240
[Amit Varma]: for whatever, for something like this to even evolve to this stage.

02:10:54.240 --> 02:10:55.240
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah.

02:10:55.240 --> 02:10:59.520
[Guest]: No, really, it doesn't make that phrase, ma ka ladla, even more evocative, doesn't it?

02:10:59.520 --> 02:11:00.520
[Amit Varma]: It does.

02:11:00.520 --> 02:11:09.640
[Guest]: This, the sense of, I mean, we've always known that about, about Indian men, or rather Indian,

02:11:09.640 --> 02:11:13.680
[Guest]: Indians obsession with having male children, and therefore those male children being sort

02:11:13.680 --> 02:11:18.600
[Guest]: of pedestalized in ways that I think are actually very dangerous, both for the child and the

02:11:18.600 --> 02:11:19.600
[Amit Varma]: mother.

02:11:19.600 --> 02:11:20.600
[Amit Varma]: And then also the saas bahu dynamics.

02:11:20.600 --> 02:11:21.600
[Guest]: Exactly, exactly.

02:11:21.600 --> 02:11:26.920
[Guest]: But I'd be interested, I mean, I haven't read the book, but does he say there's an equivalent

02:11:26.920 --> 02:11:30.600
[Guest]: in, let's say, the Jewish community, because that's the other community that is supposed

02:11:30.600 --> 02:11:32.640
[Amit Varma]: to have that mother-son thing.

02:11:32.640 --> 02:11:37.280
[Amit Varma]: Not this specific things, but he did find that while there are things that are common

02:11:37.280 --> 02:11:41.880
[Amit Varma]: across cultures, which plays to the whole hardwiring nature thing, but there are also

02:11:41.880 --> 02:11:42.880
[Amit Varma]: many, many differences.

02:11:42.880 --> 02:11:43.880
[Amit Varma]: Sure.

02:11:43.880 --> 02:11:48.240
[Amit Varma]: You know, and this was one of the unique things about, I'll quote him, in fact, I have it

02:11:48.240 --> 02:11:53.080
[Amit Varma]: right in front of me, quote, porn searches for depictions of women, breastfeeding men

02:11:53.080 --> 02:11:57.960
[Amit Varma]: are four times higher in India and Bangladesh than in any other country in the world.

02:11:57.960 --> 02:11:59.640
[Guest]: India and Bangladesh.

02:11:59.640 --> 02:12:00.640
[Guest]: Wow.

02:12:00.640 --> 02:12:01.640
[Guest]: Wow.

02:12:01.640 --> 02:12:02.640
[Guest]: That's fascinating.

02:12:02.640 --> 02:12:03.640
[Guest]: It's really fascinating.

02:12:03.640 --> 02:12:10.920
[Guest]: But you know, porn in, in East Asia, Southeast Asia, Korea, and all that is very scatological,

02:12:10.920 --> 02:12:11.920
[Guest]: right?

02:12:11.920 --> 02:12:16.100
[Guest]: In Japan, there are these bars where you lie under a glass table and have women shitting

02:12:16.100 --> 02:12:17.100
[Guest]: on you.

02:12:17.100 --> 02:12:18.100
[Amit Varma]: Have you heard of that?

02:12:18.100 --> 02:12:20.240
[Guest]: I'm not surprised, but I haven't heard of it.

02:12:20.240 --> 02:12:21.240
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:12:21.240 --> 02:12:25.680
[Guest]: So men lie under glass tables and have women sitting on top of them, shitting on them,

02:12:25.680 --> 02:12:28.240
[Amit Varma]: which is just, which is just fascinating to me.

02:12:28.240 --> 02:12:30.480
[Amit Varma]: As a student of Desire, does porn interest you?

02:12:30.480 --> 02:12:34.720
[Amit Varma]: Did you look at a lot of porn while, I mean, look at not in that sense, but did you sort

02:12:34.720 --> 02:12:35.720
[Amit Varma]: of study?

02:12:35.720 --> 02:12:42.240
[Guest]: Only, I mean, for this book, only for the chapter on bhabhis, because that's the other

02:12:42.240 --> 02:12:48.600
[Guest]: finding in Pornhub is that Indians search for that word bhabhi.

02:12:48.600 --> 02:12:53.040
[Guest]: One of the searches, one of the highly, highly, highly ranked searches is bhabhi.

02:12:53.040 --> 02:12:59.060
[Guest]: And also that women are the, in India are the third biggest demographic who watch porn

02:12:59.060 --> 02:13:04.600
[Guest]: on Pornhub, which is also fascinating given how repressed women are in India.

02:13:04.600 --> 02:13:07.500
[Guest]: Porn, my answer is yes and no.

02:13:07.500 --> 02:13:15.140
[Guest]: It fascinates me in as much as it is a popular exploration of sexual desires that might not

02:13:15.140 --> 02:13:16.520
[Guest]: be sanctioned, right?

02:13:16.520 --> 02:13:18.920
[Guest]: On the one hand, I find that fascinating.

02:13:18.920 --> 02:13:23.780
[Guest]: On the other hand, those desires that aren't sanctioned actually are such a mirror image

02:13:23.780 --> 02:13:28.260
[Guest]: of ones that are sanctioned that I'm not that interested in it actually.

02:13:28.260 --> 02:13:33.460
[Guest]: So in other words, if I just study sort of the daylight world as opposed to the twilight

02:13:33.460 --> 02:13:38.080
[Guest]: world, and I'm using this only metaphorically, the daylight world of desire, that is sort

02:13:38.080 --> 02:13:43.160
[Guest]: of pornographic enough in its imagination as than porn is.

02:13:43.160 --> 02:13:44.160
[Amit Varma]: Great.

02:13:44.160 --> 02:13:48.280
